window.SOURCE_SEGMENTS = [{"title": "MySQL Basics", "desc": "Understand databases, tables, SELECT, filters, sorting, and limits.", "lessons": [{"title": "Databases, Tables, and the Analyst's Mental Model", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 1 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Databases, Tables, and the Analyst&#x27;s Mental Model</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain databases, tables, and the analyst&#x27;s mental model, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Analysts turn business questions into columns, rows, filters, and sorted results every day.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>No prior SQL knowledge required.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Before writing syntax, you need a precise picture of what SQL acts on. This section introduces relational tables, row grain, and the difference between stored data and a query result.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Thinking Like a Database Analyst 🧠📊</p><p>We are going to learn MySQL using a simple example: a coffee shop sales database.</p><p>That fits data analytics perfectly because analysts often answer questions like:</p><p>Which product sells the most?<br>What day had the highest revenue?<br>What customers ordered more than once?<br>What is the average order-row revenue?<br>Which items are underperforming?</p><p>Before writing serious SQL, you need to understand how data is stored.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What is MySQL?\"><h3>What is MySQL?</h3><p>MySQL is a database system.</p><p>A database is like a very organized spreadsheet system, but much more powerful.</p><p>Instead of one messy spreadsheet, you usually have many connected tables.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">DATABASE\n│\n├── customers table\n├── orders table\n├── products table\n└── employees table</pre><p>For data analytics, MySQL helps you ask questions using code.</p><p>That code is called SQL.</p><p>SQL means:</p><p>Structured Query Language</p><p>A query is just a question you ask the database.</p><p>Example:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>*</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>*</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Expect 10 rows with columns order_id, product_name, category, quantity, unit_price, order_date. Check the row count before interpreting values.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>That means:</p><p>Show me everything from the orders table.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Database vs Table vs Row vs Column\"><h3>Database vs Table vs Row vs Column</h3><p>Think of a database like a folder.</p><p>Inside the folder are tables.</p><p>Each table looks like a spreadsheet.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><caption>Example: products table</caption><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now let’s label the parts.</p><p>TABLE: products</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Columns ↓\n┌────────────┬──────────────┬──────────┬───────┐\n│ product_id │ product_name │ category │ price │\n├────────────┼──────────────┼──────────┼───────┤\n│     1      │ Iced Latte   │ Coffee   │ 2.750 │ ← Row\n│     2      │ Cold Brew    │ Coffee   │ 3.000 │ ← Row\n│     3      │ Croissant    │ Pastry   │ 1.500 │ ← Row\n└────────────┴──────────────┴──────────┴───────┘\nColumn</pre><p>A column is one type of information.</p><p>Examples:</p><p>product_id<br>product_name<br>category<br>price<br>Row</p><p>A row is one full record.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That one row represents one product.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why Data Analysts Love Tables\"><h3>Why Data Analysts Love Tables</h3><p>Tables make it easy to calculate things.</p><p>For example, this table has product prices.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>You can ask:</p><p>What is the most expensive product?<br>What is the cheapest product?<br>What is the average price?<br>How many products are coffee?</p><p>This is where SQL becomes powerful.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-01-sql-basics.webp\" alt=\"SQL basics illustrated as selecting columns, filtering rows, and sorting a database result.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>A database holds related tables. SELECT chooses columns, WHERE filters rows, and ORDER BY sorts the result. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "What is MySQL?", "Database vs Table vs Row vs Column", "Why Data Analysts Love Tables"]}, {"title": "Constructing a SELECT Statement", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 1 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Constructing a SELECT Statement</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain constructing a select statement, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Analysts turn business questions into columns, rows, filters, and sorted results every day.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Databases, Tables, and the Analyst&#x27;s Mental Model.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A SELECT statement is a request for a result, not a command to change the table. We build the request from its two essential decisions: which columns to display and which table supplies the rows.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Your First SQL Command: SELECT\"><h3>Your First SQL Command: SELECT</h3><p>The most important SQL command is:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>SELECT means:</p><p>Choose which columns I want to see.</p><p>Example:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then return <code>product_name</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Expect 6 rows with columns product_name. Check the row count before interpreting values.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><p>product_name<br>Iced Latte<br>Cold Brew<br>Croissant<br>Brownie</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products table\n┌────────────┬──────────────┬──────────┬───────┐\n│ product_id │ product_name │ category │ price │\n├────────────┼──────────────┼──────────┼───────┤\n│ 1          │ Iced Latte   │ Coffee   │ 2.750 │\n│ 2          │ Cold Brew    │ Coffee   │ 3.000 │\n│ 3          │ Croissant    │ Pastry   │ 1.500 │\n│ 4          │ Brownie      │ Dessert  │ 1.750 │\n└────────────┴──────────────┴──────────┴───────┘</pre><p>SQL says:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><pre class=\"diagram\">MySQL returns only this column:\n┌──────────────┐\n│ product_name │\n├──────────────┤\n│ Iced Latte   │\n│ Cold Brew    │\n│ Croissant    │\n│ Brownie      │\n└──────────────┘</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Selecting Multiple Columns\"><h3>Selecting Multiple Columns</h3><p>You can select more than one column.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>The comma separates columns.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT column_1, column_2\nFROM table_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Selecting Everything with *\"><h3>Selecting Everything with *</h3><p>The star symbol means:</p><p>everything</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>In real analytics work, SELECT * is useful when first exploring a table.</p><p>But later, you usually select only the columns you need.</p><p>Better analyst habit:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, category, price\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The Basic SQL Shape\"><h3>The Basic SQL Shape</h3><p>Most beginner SQL queries follow this shape:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT columns\nFROM table;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">SELECT  → What do you want to see?\nFROM    → Which table should MySQL look in?\nExample:\nSELECT product_name, price\nFROM products;</pre><p>Read it like English:</p><p>Show me product_name and price<br>from the products table.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Your First SQL Command: SELECT", "Selecting Multiple Columns", "Selecting Everything with *", "The Basic SQL Shape"]}, {"title": "Filtering and Shaping a Result", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 1 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Filtering and Shaping a Result</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain filtering and shaping a result, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Analysts turn business questions into columns, rows, filters, and sorted results every day.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Constructing a SELECT Statement.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Most business questions need only some rows in a useful order. Here we develop WHERE, comparison operators, ORDER BY, and LIMIT as connected parts of one query.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Filtering Data with WHERE\"><h3>Filtering Data with WHERE</h3><p>WHERE means:</p><p>Only show rows that match a condition.</p><p>Example:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then keep rows where <code>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</code>, then return <code>product_name, price</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, price</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Expect 3 rows with columns product_name, price. Check the row count before interpreting values.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products table\n┌──────────────┬──────────┬───────┐\n│ product_name │ category │ price │\n├──────────────┼──────────┼───────┤\n│ Iced Latte   │ Coffee   │ 2.750 │ ✅ keep\n│ Cold Brew    │ Coffee   │ 3.000 │ ✅ keep\n│ Croissant    │ Pastry   │ 1.500 │ ❌ remove\n│ Brownie      │ Dessert  │ 1.750 │ ❌ remove\n└──────────────┴──────────┴───────┘</pre><p>The condition was:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Important detail:</p><p>Text values use quotes.</p><p>&#x27;Coffee&#x27;</p><p>Numbers do not need quotes.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE price &gt; 2</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Comparison Operators\"><h3>Comparison Operators</h3><p>You can filter using math-style comparisons.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Operator</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>=</td><td>equal to</td><td>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>greater than</td><td>price &gt; 2</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>&lt;</td><td>less than</td><td>price &lt; 2</td></tr><tr><td>&gt;=</td><td>greater than or equal to</td><td>price &gt;= 2</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;=</td><td>less than or equal to</td><td>price &lt;= 2</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;&gt;</td><td>not equal to</td><td>category &lt;&gt; &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nWHERE price &gt; 2;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Sorting Data with ORDER BY\"><h3>Sorting Data with ORDER BY</h3><p>ORDER BY means:</p><p>Sort the results.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>By default, MySQL sorts from smallest to largest.</p><p>That is called ascending order.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>ORDER BY price ASC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>ASC means ascending.</p><p>For highest to lowest:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>DESC means descending.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">ASC:  1 → 2 → 3 → 4 → 5\nDESC: 5 → 4 → 3 → 2 → 1</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Limiting Results with LIMIT\"><h3>Limiting Results with LIMIT</h3><p>LIMIT means:</p><p>Only show a certain number of rows.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This answers:</p><p>What is the most expensive product?</p><p>Because we sorted highest to lowest, then kept only the first row.</p><p>Visual:</p><p>Step 1: Sort by price DESC</p><p>Cold Brew     3.000  ← highest<br>Iced Latte    2.750<br>Brownie       1.750<br>Croissant     1.500</p><p>Step 2: LIMIT 1</p><p>Cold Brew     3.000</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The Order SQL Usually Runs\"><h3>The Order SQL Usually Runs</h3><p>Even though you write SQL like this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nWHERE price &gt; 2\nORDER BY price DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>MySQL thinks through it more like this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">1. FROM products\n      ↓\n2. WHERE price &gt; 2\n      ↓\n3. SELECT product_name, price\n      ↓\n4. ORDER BY price DESC\n      ↓\n5. LIMIT 1</pre><p>Visual pipeline:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products table\n      ↓\nfilter rows\n      ↓\nchoose columns\n      ↓\nsort results\n      ↓\nlimit output</pre><p>This is very important.</p><p>A SQL query is like a data machine.</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Raw table → Filter → Select columns → Sort → Final result</pre></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Filtering Data with WHERE", "Comparison Operators", "Sorting Data with ORDER BY", "Limiting Results with LIMIT", "The Order SQL Usually Runs"]}, {"title": "Guided Lab: Reading the Product Catalog", "time": 21, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 1 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Guided Lab: Reading the Product Catalog</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain reading the product catalog, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Analysts turn business questions into columns, rows, filters, and sorted results every day.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Filtering and Shaping a Result.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The best way to learn retrieval is to predict a result and then run the query. Work through these tasks in order; each adds one decision to the same product dataset.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Mini Practice Dataset\"><h3>Mini Practice Dataset</h3><p>Use this table mentally for now.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><caption>products</caption><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Show all products.\"><h3>Practice 1: Show all products.</h3><p>Try writing the SQL for each one.</p><p>Show all products.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then return <code>*</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>*</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Expect 6 rows with columns product_id, product_name, category, price. Check the row count before interpreting values.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Show only product names.\"><h3>Practice 2: Show only product names.</h3><p>Show only product names.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Show product names and prices.\"><h3>Practice 3: Show product names and prices.</h3><p>Show product names and prices.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Show only coffee products.\"><h3>Practice 4: Show only coffee products.</h3><p>Show only coffee products.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, category, price\nFROM products\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Show products cheaper than 2.000.\"><h3>Practice 5: Show products cheaper than 2.000.</h3><p>Show products cheaper than 2.000.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nWHERE price &lt; 2;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 6: Show the most expensive product.\"><h3>Practice 6: Show the most expensive product.</h3><p>Show the most expensive product.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Mini Practice Dataset", "Practice 1: Show all products.", "Practice 2: Show only product names.", "Practice 3: Show product names and prices.", "Practice 4: Show only coffee products.", "Practice 5: Show products cheaper than 2.000.", "Practice 6: Show the most expensive product."]}, {"title": "Analyst Reasoning and Chapter Review", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 1 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Analyst Reasoning and Chapter Review</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain analyst reasoning and chapter review, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Analysts turn business questions into columns, rows, filters, and sorted results every day.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Guided Lab: Reading the Product Catalog.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Syntax matters, but the professional habit is translating a vague question into a specific result grain, columns, filters, and sort order. This review connects the vocabulary to that workflow.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Analyst Mindset: Every Query Answers a Question\"><h3>Analyst Mindset: Every Query Answers a Question</h3><p>Do not think of SQL as just code.</p><p>Think of it like this:</p><p>Business question:<br>Which product is most expensive?</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then return <code>product_name, price</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, price</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>price DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>LIMIT</code><strong>1</strong><p>Keep only this many rows after sorting.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Expect 1 row with columns product_name, price. Check the row count before interpreting values.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Answer:<br>Cold Brew, 3.000</p><p>That is data analytics.</p><p>You start with a question.</p><p>Then you use SQL to answer it.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Your First MySQL Vocabulary\"><h3>Your First MySQL Vocabulary</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Word</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Database</td><td>A container that holds tables</td></tr><tr><td>Table</td><td>A structured set of rows and columns</td></tr><tr><td>Column</td><td>A field/category of data</td></tr><tr><td>Row</td><td>One record in a table</td></tr><tr><td>Query</td><td>A question written in SQL</td></tr><tr><td>SELECT</td><td>Choose columns to show</td></tr><tr><td>FROM</td><td>Choose the table</td></tr><tr><td>WHERE</td><td>Filter rows</td></tr><tr><td>ORDER BY</td><td>Sort results</td></tr><tr><td>LIMIT</td><td>Restrict number of rows</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 1 Skill Check ✅\"><h3>Segment 1 Skill Check ✅</h3><p>By the end of this segment, you should be able to understand this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nORDER BY price DESC\nLIMIT 2;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>It means:</p><p>From the products table,<br>show me product_name and price,<br>but only for Coffee products,<br>sort the most expensive first,<br>and only show the top 2.</p><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Analyst Mindset: Every Query Answers a Question", "Your First MySQL Vocabulary", "Segment 1 Skill Check ✅"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 1</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Analysts turn business questions into columns, rows, filters, and sorted results every day.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Analyst Reasoning and Chapter Review.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"FROM identifies the table that supplies rows.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>Which clause chooses the source table?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">SELECT</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">FROM</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">WHERE</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"&gt;= means greater than or equal to.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Which filter includes prices of exactly 3.000?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">price &gt; 3.000</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">price &gt;= 3.000</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">price &lt;&gt; 3.000</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"Descending order puts the highest values first, then LIMIT keeps two rows.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>How do you return the two highest prices?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">ORDER BY price DESC LIMIT 2</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">ORDER BY price ASC LIMIT 2</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">LIMIT 2 ORDER BY price</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Menu explorer", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 1</p><h2>Menu explorer</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Analysts turn business questions into columns, rows, filters, and sorted results every day.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>The shop manager needs a short menu review before changing prices.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Return product name, category, and price for Coffee products.</li><li>Sort most expensive first and keep the top three.</li><li>Write one sentence explaining the result.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Uses explicit column names</li><li>Filters category correctly</li><li>Uses deterministic ORDER BY and LIMIT</li><li>Result and written conclusion agree</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, category, price\nFROM products\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nORDER BY price DESC, product_name\nLIMIT 3;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 1, "workflow_number": 1}, {"title": "Build the Database", "desc": "Create coffee_shop, design products, load data, reset safely, and debug errors.", "lessons": [{"title": "From Server to Table", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 2 · SECTION 1</p><h2>From Server to Table</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain from server to table, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A MySQL server can hold many databases, and each database can hold many related tables. This section follows the path from creating the container to selecting it as the active workspace.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>MySQL for Data Analytics — Segment 2<br>Building Your First Database + Table 🧱📊</p><p>In this segment, we are going to create a small database for a coffee shop.</p><p>We will build this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">MySQL Server\n│\n└── coffee_shop database\n    │\n    └── products table\n        │\n        ├── Iced Latte\n        ├── Cold Brew\n        ├── Croissant\n        ├── Brownie\n        ├── Matcha Latte\n        └── Americano</pre><p>The goal is to understand how data gets created, stored, and viewed.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The Big Picture\"><h3>The Big Picture</h3><p>Before this segment, we were only looking at example tables.</p><p>Now we are going to actually create one.</p><p>Think of it like building a spreadsheet from scratch.</p><p>Step 1: Create the database<br>Step 2: Choose the database<br>Step 3: Create a table<br>Step 4: Insert rows<br>Step 5: View the data</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">CREATE DATABASE\n      ↓\nUSE DATABASE\n      ↓\nCREATE TABLE\n      ↓\nINSERT DATA\n      ↓\nSELECT DATA</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Creating a Database\"><h3>Creating a Database</h3><p>A database is a container.</p><p>For this lesson, our database will be called:</p><p>coffee_shop</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to create a database container for <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE DATABASE</code><strong>CREATE DATABASE coffee_shop;</strong><p>Create a database container.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><p>This means:</p><p>Make a new database named coffee_shop.</p><p>Visual:</p><p>Before:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">MySQL Server\n│\n└── no coffee_shop database yet</pre><p>After:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">MySQL Server\n│\n└── coffee_shop</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Using the Database\"><h3>Using the Database</h3><p>After creating a database, you need to tell MySQL:</p><p>This is the database I want to work inside.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></aside><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">MySQL Server\n│\n├── database_a\n├── database_b\n└── coffee_shop  ← active database</pre><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop; is like opening a folder before working inside it.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>USE coffee_shop</code></strong><span>Selects the active database; no result grid.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>is like opening a folder before working inside it.</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li></ol></aside></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-02-build-database.webp\" alt=\"Database construction illustrated in four stages: create database, create table, define columns, and insert rows.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>Build the container first, define its table structure, then load rows that follow that structure. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "The Big Picture", "Creating a Database", "Using the Database"]}, {"title": "Designing the Products Table", "time": 24, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 2 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Designing the Products Table</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain designing the products table, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: From Server to Table.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Table design begins with what one row represents. From that decision, we choose columns, data types, punctuation, and a verification query that make the structure unambiguous.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Creating Your First Table\"><h3>Creating Your First Table</h3><p>Now we create the products table.</p><p>This table will store items sold by the coffee shop.</p><p>We want it to look like this:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Before adding data, we need to define the table structure.</p><p>That means telling MySQL:</p><p>What columns should this table have?<br>What type of data goes into each column?</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Table Blueprint\"><h3>Table Blueprint</h3><p>Before building the table, let’s design it.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><caption>Table name: products</caption><thead><tr><th>Column Name</th><th>What It Stores</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>product_id</td><td>Unique ID for each product</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>product_name</td><td>Name of the product</td><td>&#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>category</td><td>Type of product</td><td>&#x27;Coffee&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>price</td><td>Product price</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><p>products table blueprint</p><pre class=\"diagram\">┌──────────────┬───────────────┐\n│ Column       │ Type of Data  │\n├──────────────┼───────────────┤\n│ product_id   │ whole number  │\n│ product_name │ text          │\n│ category     │ text          │\n│ price        │ decimal       │\n└──────────────┴───────────────┘</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Data Types\"><h3>Data Types</h3><p>MySQL needs to know what kind of data each column will hold.</p><p>This is very important.</p><p>A number column should hold numbers.</p><p>A text column should hold text.</p><p>A price column should hold decimals.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><caption>Common beginner data types</caption><thead><tr><th>Data Type</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>INT</td><td>Whole number</td><td>1, 25, 100</td></tr><tr><td>VARCHAR(100)</td><td>Text up to 100 characters</td><td>&#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>DECIMAL(6,3)</td><td>Decimal number</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>DATE</td><td>Calendar date</td><td>&#x27;2026-06-25&#x27;</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>For our first table, we will use:</p><p>product_id     INT<br>product_name   VARCHAR(100)<br>category       VARCHAR(50)<br>price          DECIMAL(6,3)</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Understanding VARCHAR\"><h3>Understanding VARCHAR</h3><p>VARCHAR means variable-length text.</p><p>Example:</p><p>product_name VARCHAR(100)</p><p>That means:</p><p>This column stores text, up to 100 characters long.</p><p>Examples that fit:</p><p>Iced Latte<br>Cold Brew<br>Large Iced Caramel Latte With Oat Milk</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">VARCHAR(100)\n│\n└── text value can be short or long,\n    but not longer than 100 characters</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Understanding DECIMAL(6,3)\"><h3>Understanding DECIMAL(6,3)</h3><p>For prices, we use:</p><p>DECIMAL(6,3)</p><p>This means:</p><p>6 total digits<br>3 digits after the decimal point</p><p>Visual:</p><p>DECIMAL(6,3)</p><pre class=\"diagram\">999.999\n│ │\n│ └── 3 digits after decimal\n└──── 3 digits before decimal</pre><p>Total digits = 6</p><p>Examples that fit:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Value</th><th>Fits?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2.750</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>15.500</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>999.999</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>1000.000</td><td>No</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Why use DECIMAL instead of normal number types?</p><p>Because money should be exact.</p><p>For analytics, exact numbers matter.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Creating the products Table\"><h3>Creating the products Table</h3><p>Here is the full SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to define an empty table and its rules for <code>products</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE TABLE</code><strong>CREATE TABLE products ( product_id INT, product_name VARCHAR(100), category VARCHAR(50), price DECI…</strong><p>Define an empty table and its rules.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    price DECIMAL(6,3)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>Read it slowly:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>Means:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Create a table named products.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><p>Then this part:</p><p>(<br>    product_id INT,<br>    product_name VARCHAR(100),<br>    category VARCHAR(50),<br>    price DECIMAL(6,3)<br>)</p><p>Means:</p><p>These are the columns inside the table.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products\n│\n├── product_id      INT\n├── product_name    VARCHAR(100)\n├── category        VARCHAR(50)\n└── price           DECIMAL(6,3)</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Important SQL Punctuation\"><h3>Important SQL Punctuation</h3><p>SQL punctuation matters.</p><p>Look at this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    price DECIMAL(6,3)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>Parentheses<br>The columns go inside parentheses:<br>(<br>    columns go here<br>)<br>Commas<br>Each column line gets a comma except the last one.<br>product_id INT,<br>product_name VARCHAR(100),<br>category VARCHAR(50),<br>price DECIMAL(6,3)<br>Visual:<br>Column 1,  ← comma<br>Column 2,  ← comma<br>Column 3,  ← comma<br>Column 4   ← no comma<br>Semicolon<br>The semicolon ends the SQL command.<br>;</p><p>Think of it like a period at the end of a sentence.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Seeing Your Table\"><h3>Seeing Your Table</h3><p>After creating the table, you can ask MySQL to show the table structure.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DESCRIBE products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Null</th><th>Key</th><th>Default</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">product_id</td><td class=\"\">int</td><td class=\"\">NO</td><td class=\"\">PRI</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\"></td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">product_name</td><td class=\"\">varchar(100)</td><td class=\"\">NO</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\"></td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">category</td><td class=\"\">varchar(50)</td><td class=\"\">NO</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\"></td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">price</td><td class=\"\">decimal(6,3)</td><td class=\"\">NO</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\"></td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Null</th><th>Key</th><th>Default</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>product_id</td><td>int</td><td>YES</td><td></td><td>NULL</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>product_name</td><td>varchar(100)</td><td>YES</td><td></td><td>NULL</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>category</td><td>varchar(50)</td><td>YES</td><td></td><td>NULL</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>price</td><td>decimal(6,3)</td><td>YES</td><td></td><td>NULL</td><td></td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Do not worry about every column in this result yet.</p><p>Focus on these:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>product_id</td><td>int</td></tr><tr><td>product_name</td><td>varchar(100)</td></tr><tr><td>category</td><td>varchar(50)</td></tr><tr><td>price</td><td>decimal(6,3)</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This confirms the table exists.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Creating Your First Table", "Table Blueprint", "Data Types", "Understanding VARCHAR", "Understanding DECIMAL(6,3)", "Creating the products Table", "Important SQL Punctuation", "Seeing Your Table"]}, {"title": "Loading and Inspecting Rows", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 2 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Loading and Inspecting Rows</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain loading and inspecting rows, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Designing the Products Table.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">INSERT maps values to columns by position. We begin with one row, extend the pattern to several rows, and verify that text, numbers, and decimals arrived in the intended columns.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Inserting Data into the Table\"><h3>Inserting Data into the Table</h3><p>Right now, the table exists, but it is empty.</p><p>Visual:</p><p>products table</p><pre class=\"diagram\">┌────────────┬──────────────┬──────────┬───────┐\n│ product_id │ product_name │ category │ price │\n├────────────┼──────────────┼──────────┼───────┤\n│            │              │          │       │\n└────────────┴──────────────┴──────────┴───────┘</pre><p>To add rows, we use:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to validate and store new rows for <code>the named database object</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>INSERT INTO</code><strong>INSERT INTO</strong><p>Validate and store new rows.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports the affected rows in <code>the target table</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Insert One Row\"><h3>Insert One Row</h3><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price)\nVALUES (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>This means:</p><p>Into the products table,<br>put values into these columns:<br>product_id, product_name, category, price</p><p>The values are:<br>1, Iced Latte, Coffee, 2.750</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Columns:\nproduct_id | product_name | category | price\n     ↓            ↓            ↓          ↓\nValues:\n     1       Iced Latte     Coffee      2.750</pre><p>Resulting table:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Text Values Need Quotes\"><h3>Text Values Need Quotes</h3><p>This is very important.</p><p>Text needs quotes:</p><p>&#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;<br>&#x27;Coffee&#x27;</p><p>Numbers do not:</p><p>1<br>2.750</p><p>Correct:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>VALUES (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Incorrect:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>VALUES (1, Iced Latte, Coffee, 2.750);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Why is that incorrect?</p><p>Because without quotes, MySQL thinks Iced, Latte, and Coffee are column names or commands.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Insert Multiple Rows\"><h3>Insert Multiple Rows</h3><p>Instead of inserting one row at a time, you can insert many rows at once.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price)\nVALUES\n    (2, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3.000),\n    (3, &#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1.500),\n    (4, &#x27;Brownie&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;, 1.750),\n    (5, &#x27;Matcha Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, 2.900),\n    (6, &#x27;Americano&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1.250);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 5 affected rows in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">INSERT INTO products\n      ↓\nAdd row 2\nAdd row 3\nAdd row 4\nAdd row 5\nAdd row 6</pre><p>Now the table has six products.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Viewing Your Data\"><h3>Viewing Your Data</h3><p>To see everything in the table:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This is the first moment where your database becomes useful.</p><p>You created structure.</p><p>You inserted data.</p><p>Now you can query it.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Inserting Data into the Table", "Insert One Row", "Text Values Need Quotes", "Insert Multiple Rows", "Viewing Your Data"]}, {"title": "Reproducible Setup and Safe Resets", "time": 21, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 2 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Reproducible Setup and Safe Resets</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain reproducible setup and safe resets, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Loading and Inspecting Rows.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A useful learning database must be reproducible. We assemble the complete script, examine duplicate-object and duplicate-data failures, then develop a reset pattern that returns the schema to a known state.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Full Code for This Segment\"><h3>Full Code for This Segment</h3><p>Run this as one full script:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to create a database container for <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE DATABASE</code><strong>CREATE DATABASE coffee_shop;</strong><p>Create a database container.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Running a complete setup script\"><h3>Running a complete setup script</h3><p>Some MySQL tools let you execute a saved SQL file from the prompt with <code>SOURCE path/to/file.sql;</code>. The command runs the statements in the file in order.</p><p>Use <code>SOURCE</code> for reproducible setup scripts, then run <code>USE database_name;</code> so later queries point at the intended database. If your editor does not support <code>SOURCE</code>, open the script, select all of it, and execute it manually.</p></section></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    price DECIMAL(6,3)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price)\nVALUES\n    (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750),\n    (2, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3.000),\n    (3, &#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1.500),\n    (4, &#x27;Brownie&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;, 1.750),\n    (5, &#x27;Matcha Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, 2.900),\n    (6, &#x27;Americano&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1.250);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 6 affected rows in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What Happens When You Run the Full Script\"><h3>What Happens When You Run the Full Script</h3><p>Visual flow:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">CREATE DATABASE coffee_shop;\n        ↓\nA new database is created\nUSE coffee_shop;\n        ↓\nMySQL enters that database\nCREATE TABLE products (...);\n        ↓\nA blank products table is created\nINSERT INTO products (...);\n        ↓\nRows are added\nSELECT * FROM products;\n        ↓\nThe rows are displayed</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common Beginner Error: Database Already Exists\"><h3>Common Beginner Error: Database Already Exists</h3><p>If you run this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><p>More than once, MySQL may say:</p><p>Error Code: 1007. Can&#x27;t create database &#x27;coffee_shop&#x27;; database exists</p><p>That simply means:</p><p>You already created it.</p><p>A safer version is:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><p>This means:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Create this database only if it does not already exist.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><p>Better beginner-friendly script:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common Beginner Error: Table Already Exists\"><h3>Common Beginner Error: Table Already Exists</h3><p>If you run this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    price DECIMAL(6,3)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>More than once, MySQL may say:</p><p>Error Code: 1050. Table &#x27;products&#x27; already exists</p><p>That means:</p><p>The table has already been created.</p><p>A safer version is:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS products (\n    product_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    price DECIMAL(6,3)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common Beginner Error: Duplicate Data\"><h3>Common Beginner Error: Duplicate Data</h3><p>If you run the insert statement multiple times:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price)\nVALUES\n    (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750),\n    (2, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3.000);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 2 affected rows in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>You may accidentally insert the same products again.</p><p>Your table could become:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That is bad data.</p><p>In analytics, duplicate data can ruin your results.</p><p>For example, if Cold Brew appears twice, your sales analysis may be wrong.</p><p>We will fix this in a later segment using:</p><p>PRIMARY KEY</p><p>For now, just know:</p><p>Duplicate rows = dangerous for analysis</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Clean Reset Script\"><h3>Clean Reset Script</h3><p>When learning, sometimes you want to restart fresh.</p><p>This script deletes the old table and rebuilds it.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    price DECIMAL(6,3)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price)\nVALUES\n    (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750),\n    (2, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3.000),\n    (3, &#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1.500),\n    (4, &#x27;Brownie&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;, 1.750),\n    (5, &#x27;Matcha Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, 2.900),\n    (6, &#x27;Americano&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1.250);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 6 affected rows in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>This is the best script to use while practicing.</p><p>Important:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><p>Means:</p><p>Delete the products table if it already exists.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Old products table\n      ↓\nDROP TABLE\n      ↓\nGone\n      ↓\nCREATE TABLE\n      ↓\nFresh empty table\n      ↓\nINSERT INTO\n      ↓\nClean practice data</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Data Analyst Thinking: Why This Matters\"><h3>Data Analyst Thinking: Why This Matters</h3><p>As a data analyst, you will often receive messy data.</p><p>Your job is to understand:</p><p>Where is the data?<br>What tables exist?<br>What columns exist?<br>What does each row represent?<br>Are there duplicates?<br>Are the data types correct?<br>Can I trust the numbers?</p><p>Even this tiny table teaches important skills.</p><p>Look at the products table:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A beginner sees:</p><p>A list of products.</p><p>An analyst sees:</p><p>I can calculate:<br>- number of products<br>- average price<br>- cheapest product<br>- most expensive product<br>- products by category<br>- price range by category</p><p>That is the mindset shift.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Full Code for This Segment", "What Happens When You Run the Full Script", "Common Beginner Error: Database Already Exists", "Common Beginner Error: Table Already Exists", "Common Beginner Error: Duplicate Data", "Clean Reset Script", "Data Analyst Thinking: Why This Matters", "Running a complete setup script"]}, {"title": "Retrieval Lab", "time": 21, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 2 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Retrieval Lab</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain retrieval lab, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Reproducible Setup and Safe Resets.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Use the table you built to practice column selection, filters, sorting, and top-N questions. Write each query before revealing or comparing the supplied answer.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Show all products\"><h3>Practice 1: Show all products</h3><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to select the active database for <code>the</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>USE THE</code><strong>Use the table you created. SELECT * FROM products;</strong><p>Select the active database.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use the table you created.\nSELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>the</code>.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Show only names and prices\"><h3>Practice 2: Show only names and prices</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Show only coffee products\"><h3>Practice 3: Show only coffee products</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, category, price\nFROM products\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Show products more expensive than 2.000\"><h3>Practice 4: Show products more expensive than 2.000</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nWHERE price &gt; 2.000;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2.900</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Show cheapest products first\"><h3>Practice 5: Show cheapest products first</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price ASC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Americano</td><td>1.250</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 6: Show most expensive products first\"><h3>Practice 6: Show most expensive products first</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 7: Show the top 3 most expensive products\"><h3>Practice 7: Show the top 3 most expensive products</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC\nLIMIT 3;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Show all products", "Practice 2: Show only names and prices", "Practice 3: Show only coffee products", "Practice 4: Show products more expensive than 2.000", "Practice 5: Show cheapest products first", "Practice 6: Show most expensive products first", "Practice 7: Show the top 3 most expensive products"]}, {"title": "Debugging and Chapter Review", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 2 · SECTION 6</p><h2>Debugging and Chapter Review</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Recognize, explain, and correct debugging and chapter review instead of guessing at a fix.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Retrieval Lab.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Errors are information about the statement MySQL could not interpret or execute. This section separates punctuation, quoting, identifier, and object-existence problems so you can debug deliberately.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Challenge Question 🧠\"><h3>Challenge Question 🧠</h3><p>Try to read this query like English:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then keep rows where <code>price &lt; 2.000</code>, then return <code>product_name, category, price</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>price &lt; 2.000</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, category, price</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>price DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Expect 3 rows with columns product_name, category, price. Check the row count before interpreting values.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, category, price\nFROM products\nWHERE price &lt; 2.000\nORDER BY price DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>It means:</p><p>Show product_name, category, and price<br>from the products table,<br>but only for products cheaper than 2.000,<br>then sort those results from highest price to lowest price.</p><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Tiny Debugging Section 🔧\"><h3>Tiny Debugging Section 🔧</h3><p>SQL errors are normal. They do not mean you are bad at this.</p><p>They usually mean one tiny thing is missing.</p><p>Missing semicolon</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><p>Better:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Missing quotes around text</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products\nWHERE category = Coffee;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>MySQL rejects this example</strong></div><p><code>ERROR 1054 (42S22) at line 1: Unknown column &#x27;Coffee&#x27; in &#x27;where clause&#x27;</code></p></aside><p>Better:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Misspelled column name</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT productname\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>MySQL rejects this example</strong></div><p><code>ERROR 1054 (42S22) at line 1: Unknown column &#x27;productname&#x27; in &#x27;field list&#x27;</code></p></aside><p>Better:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Misspelled table name</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM product;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>MySQL rejects this example</strong></div><p><code>ERROR 1146 (42S02) at line 1: Table &#x27;coffee_shop.product&#x27; doesn&#x27;t exist</code></p></aside><p>Better:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 2 Checklist ✅\"><h3>Segment 2 Checklist ✅</h3><p>You should now understand:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>You Practiced It</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Create a database</td><td>CREATE DATABASE coffee_shop;</td></tr><tr><td>Choose a database</td><td>USE coffee_shop;</td></tr><tr><td>Create a table</td><td>CREATE TABLE products (...)</td></tr><tr><td>Insert rows</td><td>INSERT INTO products ...</td></tr><tr><td>View rows</td><td>SELECT * FROM products;</td></tr><tr><td>Filter rows</td><td>WHERE</td></tr><tr><td>Sort rows</td><td>ORDER BY</td></tr><tr><td>Limit rows</td><td>LIMIT</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Segment 3 Preview 🚀</p><p>Next we will make this feel much more like real data analytics.</p><p>We’ll create an orders table.</p><p>That means we will move from:</p><p>What products do we sell?</p><p>To:</p><p>What did customers actually buy?<br>How much money did we make?<br>Which products sold the most?<br>What was the average order-row revenue?</p><p>The database will grow from this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">coffee_shop\n│\n└── products</pre><p>To this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">coffee_shop\n│\n├── products\n└── orders</pre></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Challenge Question 🧠", "Tiny Debugging Section 🔧", "Segment 2 Checklist ✅"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 2</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Debugging and Chapter Review.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"A column data type constrains the values stored in it.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What does a data type protect?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">The browser theme</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">The kind of value a column accepts</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">The row order</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"An explicit column list makes the mapping clear and safer when schemas change.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Why name INSERT columns explicitly?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">It documents value-to-column mapping</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">It sorts the rows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">It creates an index</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"DECIMAL stores exact fixed-point numeric values.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Which type stores an exact course price?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">DATE</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">DECIMAL(6,3)</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">VARCHAR(6)</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Build a suppliers table", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 2</p><h2>Build a suppliers table</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Reliable analysis starts with tables whose names, types, and stored values match the intended design.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>The shop needs a clean supplier directory that can be loaded repeatedly during practice.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Create suppliers with supplier_id, supplier_name, city, and active columns.</li><li>Choose and explain suitable MySQL data types.</li><li>Insert at least four rows and verify them with DESCRIBE and SELECT.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Script runs in coffee_shop</li><li>Columns use appropriate types</li><li>INSERT names its columns</li><li>Verification statements are included</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE suppliers (\n  supplier_id INT,\n  supplier_name VARCHAR(100),\n  city VARCHAR(80),\n  active BOOLEAN\n);\n\nINSERT INTO suppliers (supplier_id, supplier_name, city, active) VALUES\n(1, &#x27;North Roast&#x27;, &#x27;Kuwait City&#x27;, TRUE),\n(2, &#x27;Flour House&#x27;, &#x27;Hawalli&#x27;, TRUE),\n(3, &#x27;Tea Garden&#x27;, &#x27;Salmiya&#x27;, TRUE),\n(4, &#x27;Old Stock Co&#x27;, &#x27;Farwaniya&#x27;, FALSE);\n\nDESCRIBE suppliers;\nSELECT * FROM suppliers;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>CREATE TABLE suppliers ( supplier_id INT, supplier_name VARCHAR(100),…</code></strong><span>Creates the table definition; the new table initially has zero rows.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>INSERT INTO suppliers (supplier_id, supplier_name, city, active) VALU…</code></strong><span>Inserts the VALUES rows; this script contains 4 row groups.</span></li><li><strong>3. <code>DESCRIBE suppliers</code></strong><span>Returns one definition row per table column (Field, Type, Null, Key, Default, Extra).</span></li><li><strong>4. <code>SELECT * FROM suppliers</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li></ol></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 2, "workflow_number": 2}, {"title": "Keys & Database Design", "desc": "Replace repeated product data with primary and foreign keys.", "lessons": [{"title": "From Repeated Text to Relational Design", "time": 19, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 3 · SECTION 1</p><h2>From Repeated Text to Relational Design</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain from repeated text to relational design, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The early schema was convenient for learning but repeats product facts in every order. We diagnose the update risk and replace repeated attributes with a stable relationship.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>You’ve now learned how to query data.</p><p>Now we’re going to learn how to design tables properly so your queries are safer, cleaner, and more professional.</p><p>This segment is a big step toward thinking like a real data analyst.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The Problem With Our Current Design\"><h3>The Problem With Our Current Design</h3><p>Right now, our orders table looks like this:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This works for learning.</p><p>But in a professional database, this design has problems.</p><p>Problem 1 — We repeat product information</p><p>Every time someone orders an Iced Latte, we repeat:</p><p>repeated data<br>Iced Latte<br>Coffee<br>2.750</p><p>That means the same product details are stored in multiple places.</p><p>That creates risk.</p><p>Problem 2 — Product names can be typed differently</p><p>Imagine this happens:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Iced latte</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Ice Latte</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Iced Latte Large</td><td>1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A human understands these might be related.</p><p>A database does not.</p><p>To MySQL, these are different text values.</p><p>So this join might break:</p><p>ON o.product_name = p.product_name</p><p>Because text has to match exactly.</p><p>Problem 3 — Updating products becomes dangerous</p><p>Imagine the shop changes:</p><p>Iced Latte</p><p>to:</p><p>Iced Vanilla Latte</p><p>If the product name is stored inside every order, you may have to update old sales records.</p><p>That is bad.</p><p>Old orders are historical records. You usually do not want to rewrite history.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The Professional Solution\"><h3>The Professional Solution</h3><p>Instead of storing the product name in the orders table, we store the product’s ID.</p><p>Current beginner design:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders.product_name  →  products.product_name</pre><p>Better professional design:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders.product_id  →  products.product_id</pre><p>Visually:</p><p>products table<br>+------------+--------------+----------+-------+<br>product_id  product_name    category    price<br>+------------+--------------+----------+-------+<br>1   Iced Latte  Coffee  2.750<br>2   Cold Brew   Coffee  3.000<br>+------------+--------------+----------+-------+</p><p>orders table<br>+----------+------------+----------+------------+------------+<br>order_id    product_id  quantity    unit_price  order_date<br>+----------+------------+----------+------------+------------+<br>1   1   2   2.750   2026-06-20<br>2   2   1   3.000   2026-06-20<br>+----------+------------+----------+------------+------------+</p><p>The order does not need to say:</p><p>Iced Latte</p><p>It only needs to say:</p><p>product_id = 1</p><p>Then MySQL can look up product 1 in the products table.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"New Terms You Need To Know\"><h3>New Terms You Need To Know</h3><p>PRIMARY KEY</p><p>A PRIMARY KEY is the main unique ID for each row in a table.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Here, product_id is the primary key.</p><p>That means:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Must be unique</td><td>No two products can have the same product_id</td></tr><tr><td>Cannot be NULL</td><td>Every row must have an ID</td></tr><tr><td>Identifies one row</td><td>It tells MySQL exactly which product you mean</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Think of it like a passport number for each product.</p><p>FOREIGN KEY</p><p>A FOREIGN KEY is a column in one table that points to the primary key in another table.</p><p>Example:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders.product_id → products.product_id</pre><p>The orders table uses product_id.</p><p>But the official product information lives in the products table.</p><p>So this:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>means:</p><p>Order 1 sold 2 units of product 1.</p><p>Then MySQL checks the products table:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>So the full meaning becomes:</p><p>Order 1 sold 2 Iced Lattes.</p><p>AUTO_INCREMENT</p><p>AUTO_INCREMENT means MySQL automatically creates the next ID number for you.</p><p>Instead of writing this manually:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to validate and store new rows for <code>products</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>INSERT INTO</code><strong>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price) VALUES (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;,…</strong><p>Validate and store new rows.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price)\nVALUES (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>You can write this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_name, category, price)\nVALUES (&#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>MySQL fills in product_id automatically.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This prevents duplicate IDs and mistakes.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The New Database Design\"><h3>The New Database Design</h3><p>We are going to redesign the database like this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">coffee_shop\n│\n├── products\n│   ├── product_id      PRIMARY KEY\n│   ├── product_name\n│   ├── category\n│   └── price\n│\n└── orders\n    ├── order_id        PRIMARY KEY\n    ├── product_id      FOREIGN KEY\n    ├── quantity\n    ├── unit_price\n    └── order_date</pre><p>The relationship is:</p><p>One product can appear in many orders.</p><p>Example:</p><p>Iced Latte appears in order 1, order 5, and order 10.</p><p>So we call this:</p><p>One-to-many relationship</p><p>Visually:</p><p>products                          orders<br>--------                          ------<br>product_id 1  Iced Latte   ---&gt;   order_id 1   product_id 1<br>                           ---&gt;   order_id 5   product_id 1<br>                           ---&gt;   order_id 10  product_id 1</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Important Question: Why Keep unit_price in Orders?\"><h3>Important Question: Why Keep unit_price in Orders?</h3><p>You may ask:</p><p>If the product price is already in the products table, why keep unit_price in orders?</p><p>Great question.</p><p>Because the products.price column represents the current listed price.</p><p>The orders.unit_price column represents the price at the time of sale.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>date</th><th>product</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2026-07-01</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>If you delete the old price from history, your old revenue reports become wrong.</p><p>So this is professional:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Table</th><th>Price Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>products.price</td><td>Current menu price</td></tr><tr><td>orders.unit_price</td><td>Historical sale price</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That is very important for analytics.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-07-keys.webp\" alt=\"Primary keys in a parent products table connected to foreign keys in child order rows.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>Primary keys identify parent rows. Foreign keys create protected one-to-many relationships. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "The Problem With Our Current Design", "The Professional Solution", "New Terms You Need To Know", "The New Database Design", "Important Question: Why Keep unit_price in Orders?"]}, {"title": "Rebuilding with Keys and Constraints", "time": 18, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 3 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Rebuilding with Keys and Constraints</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain rebuilding with keys and constraints, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: From Repeated Text to Relational Design.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A professional rebuild defines primary keys, foreign keys, required values, and historical sale price deliberately. We load valid rows and test that an invalid relationship is rejected.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Rebuild the Tables Properly\"><h3>Rebuild the Tables Properly</h3><p>We will now rebuild the database with keys.</p><p>Run this full script:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to create a database container for <code>IF</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE DATABASE</code><strong>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</strong><p>Create a database container.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n    category VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL,\n    PRIMARY KEY (product_id)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE orders (\n    order_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    product_id INT NOT NULL,\n    quantity INT NOT NULL,\n    unit_price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL,\n    order_date DATE NOT NULL,\n    PRIMARY KEY (order_id),\n    FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products(product_id)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>orders</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE orders;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Understand the New products Table\"><h3>Understand the New products Table</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n    category VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL,\n    PRIMARY KEY (product_id)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>Line by line:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>product_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT</td><td>Product ID is a whole number and MySQL creates it automatically</td></tr><tr><td>product_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL</td><td>Product name is text and cannot be empty</td></tr><tr><td>category VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL</td><td>Category is text and cannot be empty</td></tr><tr><td>price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL</td><td>Price is decimal and cannot be empty</td></tr><tr><td>PRIMARY KEY (product_id)</td><td>product_id uniquely identifies each product</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Understand the New orders Table\"><h3>Understand the New orders Table</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE orders (\n    order_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    product_id INT NOT NULL,\n    quantity INT NOT NULL,\n    unit_price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL,\n    order_date DATE NOT NULL,\n    PRIMARY KEY (order_id),\n    FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products(product_id)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>orders</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE orders;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>Line by line:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>order_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT</td><td>MySQL creates a new order row ID automatically</td></tr><tr><td>product_id INT NOT NULL</td><td>Every order must connect to a product</td></tr><tr><td>quantity INT NOT NULL</td><td>Every order must have a quantity</td></tr><tr><td>unit_price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL</td><td>Every order stores the sale price</td></tr><tr><td>order_date DATE NOT NULL</td><td>Every order needs a date</td></tr><tr><td>PRIMARY KEY (order_id)</td><td>Each order row has a unique ID</td></tr><tr><td>FOREIGN KEY (product_id)</td><td>This connects orders to products</td></tr><tr><td>REFERENCES products(product_id)</td><td>The product ID must exist in the products table</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Insert Products Without Typing IDs\"><h3>Insert Products Without Typing IDs</h3><p>Now insert products.</p><p>Notice we do not insert product_id.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_name, category, price)\nVALUES\n    (&#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750),\n    (&#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3.000),\n    (&#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1.500),\n    (&#x27;Brownie&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;, 1.750),\n    (&#x27;Matcha Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, 2.900),\n    (&#x27;Americano&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1.250);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 6 affected rows in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>Now check the table:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>MySQL created the product IDs for us.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Insert Orders Using product_id\"><h3>Insert Orders Using product_id</h3><p>Now our orders should use product IDs instead of product names.</p><p>Old version:</p><p>(1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;)</p><p>New version:</p><p>(1, 2, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;)</p><p>Meaning:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>value</th><th>meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>product_id = 1</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>quantity = 2</td></tr><tr><td>2.750</td><td>unit price at time of sale</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>order date</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now insert the orders:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO orders (product_id, quantity, unit_price, order_date)\nVALUES\n    (1, 2, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (2, 1, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (3, 3, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (4, 2, 1.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (1, 1, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (5, 2, 2.900, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (6, 4, 1.250, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (2, 2, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (3, 1, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (1, 3, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-23&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 10 affected rows in <code>orders</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>Check the table:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>4</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>5</td><td>2</td><td>2.900</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>6</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>3</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>1</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Test the Foreign Key\"><h3>Test the Foreign Key</h3><p>This is where things get cool.</p><p>Try this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO orders (product_id, quantity, unit_price, order_date)\nVALUES (999, 1, 4.000, &#x27;2026-06-24&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>orders</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>This should fail.</p><p>Why?</p><p>Because there is no product with:</p><p>product_id = 999</p><p>The foreign key protects your database from bad data.</p><p>That is a professional database behavior.</p><p>Without a Foreign Key</p><p>MySQL might allow this:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>11</td><td>999</td><td>1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>But product 999 does not exist.</p><p>That is called an orphan record.</p><p>Bad.</p><p>With a Foreign Key</p><p>MySQL says:</p><p>No. You cannot sell a product that does not exist in the products table.</p><p>That is exactly what we want.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Rebuild the Tables Properly", "Understand the New products Table", "Understand the New orders Table", "Insert Products Without Typing IDs", "Insert Orders Using product_id", "Test the Foreign Key"]}, {"title": "Querying the Normalized Schema", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 3 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Querying the Normalized Schema</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain querying the normalized schema, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Rebuilding with Keys and Constraints.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Normalization changes where facts live, not the business questions. Joins restore product labels and categories while order rows retain quantity, date, and charged price.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Query the New Design\"><h3>Query the New Design</h3><p>Now, if we want readable order data, we use a join.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>o.order_id, p.product_name, p.category, o.quantity, o.unit_price, o.quantity * o.…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>INNER JOIN</code><strong>products</strong><p>Connect rows using o.product_id = p.product_id.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>o.order_id, p.product_name, p.category, o.quantity, o.unit_price, o.quantity * o.…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.unit_price,\n    o.quantity * o.unit_price AS revenue,\n    o.order_date\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_id = p.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>4.500</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>3.500</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2</td><td>2.900</td><td>5.800</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>5.000</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>6.000</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>8.250</td><td>2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>The result looks almost the same as before.</p><p>But the database is now much cleaner underneath.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Analytics Question: Revenue by Product\"><h3>Analytics Question: Revenue by Product</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Which products made the most money?</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_id = o.product_id\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Same answer as before.</p><p>But now we are grouping by a stable product ID, not text.</p><p>That is better.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Analytics Question: Revenue by Category\"><h3>Analytics Question: Revenue by Category</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Which category makes the most revenue?</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">13</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>12</td><td>30.500</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now the category comes from the products table.</p><p>That means we do not need to repeat category inside every order.</p><p>Cleaner database. Cleaner analytics.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Analytics Question: Daily Revenue\"><h3>Analytics Question: Daily Revenue</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>How much revenue did we make each day?</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_date,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nGROUP BY o.order_date\nORDER BY o.order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>13.000</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>12.050</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>12.500</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-23</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Notice something important:</p><p>This query does not need the products table.</p><p>Why?</p><p>Because revenue is already fully stored in orders:</p><p>quantity * unit_price</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use joins only when you need information from another table.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>joins</code>.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Analytics Question: Menu Price vs Sold Price\"><h3>Analytics Question: Menu Price vs Sold Price</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Did we sell anything at a different price than the current menu price?</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    o.unit_price AS sold_price,\n    p.price AS current_menu_price,\n    o.unit_price - p.price AS price_difference\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_id = p.product_id\nWHERE o.unit_price &lt;&gt; p.price;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>Expected result right now:</p><p>No rows.</p><p>That means every item was sold at the current listed price.</p><p>But imagine we later run a discount.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO orders (product_id, quantity, unit_price, order_date)\nVALUES (1, 1, 2.250, &#x27;2026-06-24&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>orders</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>That means:</p><p>Sold 1 Iced Latte for 2.250 instead of 2.750.</p><p>Now the price mismatch query would find it.</p><p>This is very useful for analytics.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Query the New Design", "Analytics Question: Revenue by Product", "Analytics Question: Revenue by Category", "Analytics Question: Daily Revenue", "Analytics Question: Menu Price vs Sold Price"]}, {"title": "Integrity and Professional Database Behavior", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 3 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Integrity and Professional Database Behavior</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain integrity and professional database behavior, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Querying the Normalized Schema.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Keys protect identity and history. We examine deletion behavior, parent-child responsibility, and the validation habits expected when schemas support real reporting.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why This Design Is Better\"><h3>Why This Design Is Better</h3><p>Old design</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders\n├── order_id\n├── product_name\n├── category\n├── quantity\n├── unit_price\n└── order_date</pre><p>Problems:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Problem</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Repeated product names</td><td>Iced Latte typed many times</td></tr><tr><td>Repeated categories</td><td>Coffee typed many times</td></tr><tr><td>Text joins are fragile</td><td>Iced Latte vs Ice Latte</td></tr><tr><td>Harder to update products</td><td>Name changes affect many rows</td></tr><tr><td>Easier to create bad data</td><td>Orders can reference products that do not exist</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>New design</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products\n├── product_id\n├── product_name\n├── category\n└── price\norders\n├── order_id\n├── product_id\n├── quantity\n├── unit_price\n└── order_date</pre><p>Benefits:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Benefit</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cleaner data</td><td>Product details live in one place</td></tr><tr><td>Safer joins</td><td>IDs are more reliable than names</td></tr><tr><td>Better reporting</td><td>Categories come from one official table</td></tr><tr><td>Less duplication</td><td>Orders only store what orders need</td></tr><tr><td>Foreign key protection</td><td>Orders cannot point to missing products</td></tr><tr><td>More professional</td><td>This is closer to real analytics databases</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"PRIMARY KEY vs FOREIGN KEY\"><h3>PRIMARY KEY vs FOREIGN KEY</h3><p>This is important enough to slow down.</p><p>Primary Key</p><p>A primary key says:</p><p>This column uniquely identifies rows in this table.</p><p>Example:</p><p>products.product_id</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>product_id is the main ID for products.</p><p>Foreign Key</p><p>A foreign key says:</p><p>This column points to a row in another table.</p><p>Example:</p><p>orders.product_id</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Each product_id in orders points back to products.</p><p>Simple visual</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products.product_id\n        ▲\n        │\n        │ foreign key relationship\n        │\norders.product_id</pre><p>Or:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products\n+------------+--------------+\nproduct_id  product_name\n+------------+--------------+\n1   Iced Latte\n+------------+--------------+\n      ▲\n      │\n      │\norders\n+----------+------------+----------+\norder_id    product_id  quantity\n+----------+------------+----------+\n1   1   2\n5   1   1\n10  1   3\n+----------+------------+----------+</pre><p>One product. Many order rows.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What Happens If We Delete a Product?\"><h3>What Happens If We Delete a Product?</h3><p>Try this:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to remove rows selected by WHERE for <code>products</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>DELETE FROM</code><strong>DELETE FROM products WHERE product_id = 1;</strong><p>Remove rows selected by where.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DELETE FROM products\nWHERE product_id = 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>Foreign-key protection blocks the deletion</strong></div><p>MySQL returns a foreign-key constraint error because order rows still reference <code>product_id = 1</code>. The product and its orders remain unchanged.</p></aside><p>This should fail.</p><p>Why?</p><p>Because product 1 is used in the orders table.</p><p>The database is protecting your historical sales records.</p><p>That is good.</p><p>Imagine deleting Iced Latte from products.</p><p>Then all these orders would point to nothing:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Those would become broken records.</p><p>The foreign key prevents that.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Professional Analytics Mindset\"><h3>Professional Analytics Mindset</h3><p>A data analyst needs to trust the data.</p><p>Bad database design creates bad analytics.</p><p>Example:</p><p>If you join on product name:</p><p>ON o.product_name = p.product_name</p><p>You are trusting text.</p><p>That is risky.</p><p>If you join on product ID:</p><p>ON o.product_id = p.product_id</p><p>You are trusting a controlled unique identifier.</p><p>That is much safer.</p><p>Professional analysts care about questions like:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Analytics Question</th><th>Why Good Design Helps</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Which product made the most revenue?</td><td>Product IDs prevent name spelling issues</td></tr><tr><td>Which category performs best?</td><td>Category lives in one official place</td></tr><tr><td>Which products have no sales?</td><td>Product table is the official product list</td></tr><tr><td>Were discounts given?</td><td>Orders store historical sale price</td></tr><tr><td>Did any order use an invalid product?</td><td>Foreign key prevents that</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Why This Design Is Better", "PRIMARY KEY vs FOREIGN KEY", "What Happens If We Delete a Product?", "Professional Analytics Mindset"]}, {"title": "Completeness Reports and Design Rules", "time": 18, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 3 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Completeness Reports and Design Rules</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain completeness reports and design rules, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Integrity and Professional Database Behavior.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A normalized design must also represent absence correctly. Outer joins reveal products with no sales, and table-grain rules guide future schema decisions.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Products With No Sales\"><h3>Products With No Sales</h3><p>Right now, all products have sales.</p><p>But this query is still important.</p><p>Business question:</p><p>Which menu items have not sold?</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then keep rows where <code>o.order_id IS NULL</code>, then return <code>p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category, p.price</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>LEFT JOIN</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Connect rows using p.product_id = o.product_id.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>o.order_id IS NULL</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category, p.price</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_id = o.product_id\nWHERE o.order_id IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>Expected result right now:</p><p>No rows.</p><p>That means every product has at least one sale.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Full Product Performance Report\"><h3>Full Product Performance Report</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Show every product, even if it has zero sales.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS items_sold,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 0) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_id = o.product_id\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td><td>4</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This is a strong beginner analytics query.</p><p>It uses:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>Used here?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SELECT</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>LEFT JOIN</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>GROUP BY</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>SUM()</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>calculated column</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>COALESCE()</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>ORDER BY</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>primary key</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>foreign key</td><td>Yes</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That is real progress 💪</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Add One New Product With No Orders\"><h3>Add One New Product With No Orders</h3><p>Let’s prove the LEFT JOIN works.</p><p>Add a new product:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_name, category, price)\nVALUES (&#x27;Blueberry Muffin&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1.900);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>Now run:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected new product:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>7</td><td>Blueberry Muffin</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.900</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now run the product performance report again:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS items_sold,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 0) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_id = o.product_id\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Now you should see:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>7</td><td>Blueberry Muffin</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.900</td><td>0</td><td>0.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That is why LEFT JOIN is powerful.</p><p>An INNER JOIN would hide products with no sales.</p><p>A LEFT JOIN shows them.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Important Database Design Rule\"><h3>Important Database Design Rule</h3><p>A professional design usually follows this rule:</p><p>Store each fact in one place.</p><p>Product name is a product fact.</p><p>So it belongs in:</p><p>products</p><p>Not in:</p><p>orders</p><p>Category is a product fact.</p><p>So it belongs in:</p><p>products</p><p>Not in:</p><p>orders</p><p>Quantity is an order fact.</p><p>So it belongs in:</p><p>orders</p><p>Order date is an order fact.</p><p>So it belongs in:</p><p>orders</p><p>Sale price is an order fact because it happened at a specific time.</p><p>So it belongs in:</p><p>orders</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Beginner Rule: Ask “What Does This Table Represent?”\"><h3>Beginner Rule: Ask “What Does This Table Represent?”</h3><p>This is one of the best database design questions.</p><p>products</p><p>What does one row represent?</p><p>One menu item.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>One row = one product.</p><p>orders</p><p>What does one row represent?</p><p>One product sold on one order row.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>One row = one sale line.</p><p>Later, in more advanced database design, we may split this even further into:</p><p>orders<br>order_items<br>products</p><p>Like this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders\n├── order_id\n└── order_date\norder_items\n├── order_item_id\n├── order_id\n├── product_id\n├── quantity\n└── unit_price\nproducts\n├── product_id\n├── product_name\n├── category\n└── price</pre><p>That is even more professional.</p><p>But for now, our two-table version is perfect for learning keys.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common Beginner Mistakes\"><h3>Common Beginner Mistakes</h3><p>Mistake 1 — Joining on names instead of IDs</p><p>Less ideal:</p><p>ON o.product_name = p.product_name</p><p>Better:</p><p>ON o.product_id = p.product_id</p><p>Mistake 2 — Manually inserting auto IDs</p><p>Avoid this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_id, product_name, category, price)\nVALUES (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>Prefer this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_name, category, price)\nVALUES (&#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 1 affected row in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><p>Let MySQL create the ID.</p><p>Mistake 3 — Forgetting to insert parent data first</p><p>Because orders.product_id references products.product_id, you must insert products first.</p><p>Correct order:</p><p>1. Insert products<br>2. Insert orders</p><p>Wrong order:</p><p>1. Insert orders<br>2. Insert products</p><p>The wrong order may fail because the product does not exist yet.</p><p>Mistake 4 — Dropping tables in the wrong order</p><p>Because orders depends on products, drop the child table first.</p><p>Correct:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><p>Why?</p><p>Because orders points to products.</p><p>So remove orders first.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Products With No Sales", "Full Product Performance Report", "Add One New Product With No Orders", "Important Database Design Rule", "Beginner Rule: Ask “What Does This Table Represent?”", "Common Beginner Mistakes"]}, {"title": "Normalization Lab", "time": 18, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 3 · SECTION 6</p><h2>Normalization Lab</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain normalization lab, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Completeness Reports and Design Rules.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">These exercises revisit the full reporting workflow on the key-based schema. Confirm relationship cardinality and revenue reconciliation in every solution.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Show all products.\"><h3>Practice 1: Show all products.</h3><p>Try these yourself 👇</p><p>Show all products.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then return <code>*</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>*</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Show all orders.\"><h3>Practice 2: Show all orders.</h3><p>Show all orders.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Show each order with product name and revenue.\"><h3>Practice 3: Show each order with product name and revenue.</h3><p>Show each order with product name and revenue.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.unit_price,\n    o.quantity * o.unit_price AS revenue,\n    o.order_date\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_id = p.product_id\nORDER BY o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Find revenue by product.\"><h3>Practice 4: Find revenue by product.</h3><p>Find revenue by product.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_name,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.product_name\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Find revenue by category.\"><h3>Practice 5: Find revenue by category.</h3><p>Find revenue by category.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 6: Find products with no sales.\"><h3>Practice 6: Find products with no sales.</h3><p>Find products with no sales.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_id = o.product_id\nWHERE o.order_id IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Show all products.", "Practice 2: Show all orders.", "Practice 3: Show each order with product name and revenue.", "Practice 4: Find revenue by product.", "Practice 5: Find revenue by category.", "Practice 6: Find products with no sales."]}, {"title": "Chapter Synthesis and Rebuild Script", "time": 10, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 3 · SECTION 7</p><h2>Chapter Synthesis and Rebuild Script</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain chapter synthesis and rebuild script, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Normalization Lab.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The final model, chapter review, and clean script bring design and analysis together. You should be able to recreate the schema and explain why each fact belongs where it does.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 7 Final Mental Model\"><h3>Segment 7 Final Mental Model</h3><p>Before Segment 7, your database was like this:</p><p>orders table says:<br>&quot;I sold an Iced Latte.&quot;</p><p>After Segment 7, your database says:</p><p>orders table says:<br>&quot;I sold product 1.&quot;</p><p>products table says:<br>&quot;Product 1 is Iced Latte.&quot;</p><p>That is the professional mindset.</p><p>The order table stores the event.</p><p>The product table stores the product details.</p><p>The ID connects them.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What You Learned\"><h3>What You Learned</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>PRIMARY KEY</td><td>Unique ID for each row in a table</td></tr><tr><td>FOREIGN KEY</td><td>A column that points to another table’s primary key</td></tr><tr><td>AUTO_INCREMENT</td><td>MySQL automatically generates the next ID</td></tr><tr><td>NOT NULL</td><td>A column must have a value</td></tr><tr><td>Parent table</td><td>The table being referenced, like products</td></tr><tr><td>Child table</td><td>The table doing the referencing, like orders</td></tr><tr><td>One-to-many</td><td>One product can appear in many orders</td></tr><tr><td>Referential integrity</td><td>The database protects relationships from bad data</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Clean Segment 7 Full Script\"><h3>Clean Segment 7 Full Script</h3><p>Here is the full clean version you can save and rerun:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to create a database container for <code>IF</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE DATABASE</code><strong>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</strong><p>Create a database container.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products (\n    product_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n    category VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL,\n    PRIMARY KEY (product_id)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE orders (\n    order_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    product_id INT NOT NULL,\n    quantity INT NOT NULL,\n    unit_price DECIMAL(6,3) NOT NULL,\n    order_date DATE NOT NULL,\n    PRIMARY KEY (order_id),\n    FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products(product_id)\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>orders</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE orders;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO products (product_name, category, price)\nVALUES\n    (&#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2.750),\n    (&#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3.000),\n    (&#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1.500),\n    (&#x27;Brownie&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;, 1.750),\n    (&#x27;Matcha Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, 2.900),\n    (&#x27;Americano&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1.250);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 6 affected rows in <code>products</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO orders (product_id, quantity, unit_price, order_date)\nVALUES\n    (1, 2, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (2, 1, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (3, 3, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (4, 2, 1.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (1, 1, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (5, 2, 2.900, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (6, 4, 1.250, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (2, 2, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (3, 1, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (1, 3, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-23&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 10 affected rows in <code>orders</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS items_sold,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 0) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_id = o.product_id\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Segment 7 Summary</p><p>You just learned one of the most important database design lessons:</p><p>Do not connect important business data using names when you can connect it using IDs.</p><p>Names are for humans.</p><p>IDs are for databases.</p><p>For analytics, this gives you cleaner, safer, more trustworthy reports ☕📈</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Segment 7 Final Mental Model", "What You Learned", "Clean Segment 7 Full Script"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 3</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Chapter Synthesis and Rebuild Script.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A primary key uniquely and reliably identifies each row.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What must a primary key be?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Unique and non-NULL</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Text only</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Repeated in every row</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"A foreign key prevents references to nonexistent parent keys.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>What does a foreign key protect?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Font selection</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Referential integrity</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Sort direction</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"The current catalog price may change; the order must retain what was charged.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Why retain order unit_price?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">To preserve the historical sale price</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">To replace product_id</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">To count rows</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Normalize a sales design", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 3</p><h2>Normalize a sales design</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Stable keys and constraints keep relationships trustworthy as datasets grow and change.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>A draft order table repeats product names and categories on every sale row.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Create products and order_items with primary and foreign keys.</li><li>Keep historical unit_price in order_items.</li><li>Insert valid sample rows and demonstrate that an invalid product reference is rejected.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Each table has a clear grain</li><li>Keys and relationship are enforced</li><li>Repeated product attributes are removed from order_items</li><li>The expected failing statement is clearly labeled and not run with setup</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products_norm (\n  product_id INT PRIMARY KEY, product_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n  category VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL, current_price DECIMAL(8,3) NOT NULL\n);\nCREATE TABLE order_items_norm (\n  order_item_id INT PRIMARY KEY, product_id INT NOT NULL, quantity INT NOT NULL,\n  unit_price DECIMAL(8,3) NOT NULL, order_date DATE NOT NULL,\n  CONSTRAINT fk_item_product FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products_norm(product_id)\n);\n-- Expected to fail after setup: INSERT INTO order_items_norm VALUES (1, 999, 1, 2.000, &#x27;2026-06-24&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>CREATE TABLE products_norm ( product_id INT PRIMARY KEY, product_name…</code></strong><span>Creates the table definition; the new table initially has zero rows.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>CREATE TABLE order_items_norm ( order_item_id INT PRIMARY KEY, produc…</code></strong><span>Creates the table definition; the new table initially has zero rows.</span></li><li><strong>3. <code>-- Expected to fail after setup: INSERT INTO order_items_norm VALUES…</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li></ol></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 7, "workflow_number": 3}, {"title": "Data Cleaning", "desc": "Profile, standardize, validate, and safely correct unreliable source data.", "lessons": [{"title": "Profiling Data Before Changing It", "time": 24, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 4 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Profiling Data Before Changing It</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain profiling data before changing it, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>A correct query on unreliable data still produces an unreliable answer; profiling and safe cleaning protect decisions.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Cleaning begins with evidence. We measure completeness, boolean quality failures, blanks, inconsistent categories, duplicates, and invalid numeric ranges before defining any correction.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Analysis is only trustworthy when source values are complete, consistent, and valid. This segment uses diagnostic queries first and controlled corrections second.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Profile before changing data\"><h3>Profile before changing data</h3><p>Start by measuring the table.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then return <code>COUNT(*) AS row_count, COUNT(product_name) AS names_present, COUNT(*) - COUNT(pro…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>COUNT(*) AS row_count, COUNT(product_name) AS names_present, COUNT(*) - COUNT(pro…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    COUNT(*) AS row_count,\n    COUNT(product_name) AS names_present,\n    COUNT(*) - COUNT(product_name) AS names_missing,\n    COUNT(DISTINCT category) AS distinct_categories\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>row_count</th><th>names_present</th><th>names_missing</th><th>distinct_categories</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">0</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>COUNT(column) ignores NULL; COUNT(*) counts rows.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Count quality failures with boolean expressions\"><h3>Count quality failures with boolean expressions</h3><p>In MySQL, a true condition can behave like 1 and a false condition can behave like 0 inside SUM. That makes compact quality profiles possible.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    COUNT(*) AS item_rows,\n    SUM(quantity IS NULL) AS null_quantity_rows,\n    SUM(quantity &lt;= 0) AS non_positive_quantity_rows,\n    SUM(unit_price IS NULL) AS null_price_rows,\n    SUM(unit_price &lt; 0) AS negative_price_rows\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>Read each SUM as &quot;count rows where this condition is true.&quot; This is useful for profiling, but CASE is more portable across database systems if you later move outside MySQL.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Find NULL values\"><h3>Find NULL values</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products\nWHERE product_name IS NULL\n   OR category IS NULL\n   OR price IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>Use IS NULL, not = NULL.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Find blanks and whitespace\"><h3>Find blanks and whitespace</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_id,\n    product_name,\n    category\nFROM products\nWHERE TRIM(COALESCE(product_name, &#x27;&#x27;)) = &#x27;&#x27;\n   OR TRIM(COALESCE(category, &#x27;&#x27;)) = &#x27;&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>This catches NULL, empty strings, and strings containing only spaces.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Find inconsistent categories\"><h3>Find inconsistent categories</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    category,\n    COUNT(*) AS product_count\nFROM products\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_count</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Review distinct values before deciding how they should be standardized.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Detect duplicate business values\"><h3>Detect duplicate business values</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    LOWER(TRIM(product_name)) AS normalized_name,\n    COUNT(*) AS duplicate_count\nFROM products\nGROUP BY LOWER(TRIM(product_name))\nHAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>The normalized expression helps detect spelling differences caused only by case or outside spaces.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Validate numeric ranges\"><h3>Validate numeric ranges</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products\nWHERE price &lt;= 0;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE quantity &lt;= 0\n   OR unit_price &lt; 0;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>Validity rules come from the business. Write them down before cleaning.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-11-cleaning.webp\" alt=\"Messy product records being profiled, cleaned, validated, and converted into trusted data.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>Cleaning starts by finding issues, applies written business rules, and validates results before committing changes. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "Profile before changing data", "Count quality failures with boolean expressions", "Find NULL values", "Find blanks and whitespace", "Find inconsistent categories", "Detect duplicate business values", "Validate numeric ranges"]}, {"title": "Safe Corrections and Preventive Rules", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 4 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Safe Corrections and Preventive Rules</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain safe corrections and preventive rules, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>A correct query on unreliable data still produces an unreliable answer; profiling and safe cleaning protect decisions.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Profiling Data Before Changing It.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A correction should be previewed, reversible, and validated. Transactions, staging tables, constraints, and quality reports turn one-time cleanup into a controlled process.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Preview an UPDATE\"><h3>Preview an UPDATE</h3><p>Run a SELECT with the same WHERE condition before changing rows.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then keep rows where <code>LOWER(TRIM(category)) IN (&#x27;coffee&#x27;, &#x27;coffees&#x27;)</code>, then return <code>product_id, category AS old_category, &#x27;Coffee&#x27; AS new_category</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>LOWER(TRIM(category)) IN (&#x27;coffee&#x27;, &#x27;coffees&#x27;)</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_id, category AS old_category, &#x27;Coffee&#x27; AS new_category</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_id,\n    category AS old_category,\n    &#x27;Coffee&#x27; AS new_category\nFROM products\nWHERE LOWER(TRIM(category)) IN (&#x27;coffee&#x27;, &#x27;coffees&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>old_category</th><th>new_category</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Confirm the target rows first.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Update safely inside a transaction\"><h3>Update safely inside a transaction</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>START TRANSACTION;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Transaction started</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later supported data changes remain pending until COMMIT and can be undone with ROLLBACK.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>UPDATE products\nSET category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nWHERE LOWER(TRIM(category)) IN (&#x27;coffee&#x27;, &#x27;coffees&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Matching rows evaluated and updated</strong></div><p>UPDATE returns an affected-row message, not a result grid. Preview the same WHERE condition, then use the following SELECT to verify exact values before COMMIT.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT * FROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>ROLLBACK;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Uncommitted changes undone</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. The product rows return to their values from before START TRANSACTION.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use COMMIT instead of ROLLBACK only after validating the changed rows. Transaction support depends on the table&#x27;s storage engine; InnoDB supports it.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>Use COMMIT instead of ROLLBACK only after validating the changed rows…</code></strong><span>Selects the active database; no result grid.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>InnoDB supports it.</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li></ol></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Preserve raw data with a staging table\"><h3>Preserve raw data with a staging table</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS products_staging;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products_staging AS\nSELECT *\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products_staging</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products_staging;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>A staging copy supports experimentation, but CREATE TABLE ... AS SELECT does not copy every index or constraint automatically.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Add preventive constraints\"><h3>Add preventive constraints</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>ALTER TABLE products\nADD CONSTRAINT chk_product_price_positive CHECK (price &gt; 0);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Constraint or structure change applied</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports success only if existing rows satisfy the new rule; <code>SHOW CREATE TABLE</code> verifies the resulting definition.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>ALTER TABLE orders\nADD CONSTRAINT chk_order_quantity_positive CHECK (quantity &gt; 0);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Constraint or structure change applied</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports success only if existing rows satisfy the new rule; <code>SHOW CREATE TABLE</code> verifies the resulting definition.</p></aside><p>Clean existing violations before adding constraints.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Preview an UPDATE", "Update safely inside a transaction", "Preserve raw data with a staging table", "Add preventive constraints"]}, {"title": "Quality Rules, Tests, and Relationships", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 4 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Quality Rules, Tests, and Relationships</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain quality rules, tests, and relationships, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>A correct query on unreliable data still produces an unreliable answer; profiling and safe cleaning protect decisions.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Safe Corrections and Preventive Rules.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Professional data cleaning converts business rules into repeatable tests: completeness, uniqueness, accepted values, relationship integrity, freshness, and distribution.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Build a data-quality report\"><h3>Build a data-quality report</h3><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then calculate the nested query first and use its answer in the outer query, then keep rows where <code>category IS NULL OR TRIM(category) = &#x27;&#x27; UNION ALL SELECT &#x27;orders with invalid qua…</code>, then return <code>&#x27;products missing category&#x27; AS quality_check, COUNT(*) AS issue_count</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>category IS NULL OR TRIM(category) = &#x27;&#x27; UNION ALL SELECT &#x27;orders with invalid qua…</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>&#x27;products missing category&#x27; AS quality_check, COUNT(*) AS issue_count</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    &#x27;products missing category&#x27; AS quality_check,\n    COUNT(*) AS issue_count\nFROM products\nWHERE category IS NULL OR TRIM(category) = &#x27;&#x27;\nUNION ALL\nSELECT\n    &#x27;orders with invalid quantity&#x27;,\n    COUNT(*)\nFROM orders\nWHERE quantity &lt;= 0;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>quality_check</th><th>issue_count</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">products missing category</td><td class=\"\">0</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">orders with invalid quantity</td><td class=\"\">0</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>UNION ALL stacks compatible result sets without removing duplicates.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Think in data-quality dimensions\"><h3>Think in data-quality dimensions</h3><p>A professional cleaning review is not one generic question: &quot;is the data clean?&quot; It is several smaller questions.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Question</th><th>Example SQL habit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Completeness</td><td>Are required values present?</td><td>Count NULLs and blanks</td></tr><tr><td>Uniqueness</td><td>Should this value appear once?</td><td>GROUP BY the business key</td></tr><tr><td>Validity</td><td>Is the value allowed?</td><td>Check ranges and accepted values</td></tr><tr><td>Consistency</td><td>Do labels and formats agree?</td><td>TRIM, LOWER, mapping tables</td></tr><tr><td>Integrity</td><td>Do relationships connect?</td><td>Find missing parent keys</td></tr><tr><td>Freshness</td><td>Is the data recent enough?</td><td>Check latest expected date</td></tr><tr><td>Distribution</td><td>Does the shape look plausible?</td><td>Compare min, max, average, and category counts</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Do not try to clean everything at once. Identify which dimension failed, write the rule, then write the SQL that proves the failure.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Raw, staging, and clean layers\"><h3>Raw, staging, and clean layers</h3><p>Keep three mental layers:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Rule</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>raw</td><td>Untouched import</td><td>Never overwrite it</td></tr><tr><td>staging</td><td>Profiling and experiments</td><td>Allowed to transform and test</td></tr><tr><td>clean</td><td>Trusted analytical table or view</td><td>Only approved rules enter here</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS products_clean;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE products_clean AS\nSELECT\n    product_id,\n    TRIM(product_name) AS product_name,\n    CASE\n        WHEN LOWER(TRIM(category)) IN (&#x27;coffee&#x27;, &#x27;coffees&#x27;) THEN &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n        WHEN LOWER(TRIM(category)) IN (&#x27;tea&#x27;, &#x27;teas&#x27;) THEN &#x27;Tea&#x27;\n        ELSE TRIM(category)\n    END AS category,\n    price\nFROM products_staging;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>products_clean</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE products_clean;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><p>This creates a clean version without pretending the raw data never had problems.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Turn rules into tests\"><h3>Turn rules into tests</h3><p>Data-quality tools often use a few generic test ideas. You can write the same thinking in plain SQL.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Test idea</th><th>Business meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>not_null</td><td>Required field is present</td></tr><tr><td>unique</td><td>A key appears only once</td></tr><tr><td>accepted_values</td><td>Only approved labels appear</td></tr><tr><td>relationships</td><td>A child value exists in the parent table</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Example quality tests:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT &#x27;product_id not null&#x27; AS test_name, COUNT(*) AS failures\nFROM products_clean\nWHERE product_id IS NULL\nUNION ALL\nSELECT &#x27;product_id unique&#x27;, COUNT(*) AS failures\nFROM (\n    SELECT product_id\n    FROM products_clean\n    GROUP BY product_id\n    HAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 1\n) AS duplicate_ids\nUNION ALL\nSELECT &#x27;category accepted values&#x27;, COUNT(*) AS failures\nFROM products_clean\nWHERE category NOT IN (&#x27;Coffee&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>A good test query returns the rows or count that failed. Zero failures is the target, but a nonzero result is useful evidence, not a reason to hide the issue.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Build a data-quality report", "Think in data-quality dimensions", "Raw, staging, and clean layers", "Turn rules into tests"]}, {"title": "Deduplication, Audit Logs, and Reconciliation", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 4 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Deduplication, Audit Logs, and Reconciliation</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain deduplication, audit logs, and reconciliation, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>A correct query on unreliable data still produces an unreliable answer; profiling and safe cleaning protect decisions.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Quality Rules, Tests, and Relationships.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Cleaning decisions must be explainable. We mark duplicate candidates with survivor rules, log changes, reconcile totals, and avoid destructive shortcuts.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Test relationships between tables\"><h3>Test relationships between tables</h3><p>A relationship test asks:</p><p>Does every child row point to a real parent row?</p><p>For orders and products:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then keep rows where <code>p.product_id IS NULL</code>, then return <code>o.order_id, o.product_id</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>LEFT JOIN</code><strong>products</strong><p>Connect rows using p.product_id = o.product_id.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>p.product_id IS NULL</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>o.order_id, o.product_id</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_id\nFROM orders AS o\nLEFT JOIN products AS p\n    ON p.product_id = o.product_id\nWHERE p.product_id IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>If this returns rows, those order rows reference products that do not exist in the product table. That threatens joins, revenue by product, and product-level dashboards.</p><p>If the table has a real foreign key, MySQL can prevent this issue. If you are cleaning imported files before constraints exist, you still need the test query.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Deduplicate safely\"><h3>Deduplicate safely</h3><p>Duplicate handling requires a survivor rule. Do not delete duplicates just because COUNT(*) is greater than one.</p><p>Ask:</p><ul><li>What makes two rows duplicates?</li><li>Which row should survive?</li><li>What evidence proves the deleted row is not a legitimate separate record?</li></ul><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use ROW_NUMBER to mark candidates before deleting anything:\nWITH ranked_products AS (\n    SELECT\n        product_id,\n        product_name,\n        category,\n        price,\n        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (\n            PARTITION BY LOWER(TRIM(product_name))\n            ORDER BY product_id\n        ) AS duplicate_rank\n    FROM products_clean\n)\nSELECT *\nFROM ranked_products\nWHERE duplicate_rank &gt; 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>ROW_NUMBER</code>.</p></aside><p>This query only identifies possible duplicate rows. The ORDER BY chooses the survivor. If the survivor rule is wrong, the cleaning rule is wrong.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Keep a cleaning log\"><h3>Keep a cleaning log</h3><p>A cleaning log explains what changed and why. It protects your future self and lets another analyst review your decisions.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS cleaning_log (\n    log_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,\n    table_name VARCHAR(100),\n    rule_name VARCHAR(100),\n    issue_count_before INT,\n    action_taken VARCHAR(255),\n    checked_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO cleaning_log (\n    table_name,\n    rule_name,\n    issue_count_before,\n    action_taken\n)\nSELECT\n    &#x27;products_clean&#x27;,\n    &#x27;standardize category labels&#x27;,\n    COUNT(*),\n    &#x27;Mapped coffee/coffees to Coffee and tea/teas to Tea&#x27;\nFROM products_staging\nWHERE LOWER(TRIM(category)) IN (&#x27;coffee&#x27;, &#x27;coffees&#x27;, &#x27;tea&#x27;, &#x27;teas&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside><p>The log does not replace the SQL script. It summarizes the decision, affected population, and reason.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Reconcile before trusting analysis\"><h3>Reconcile before trusting analysis</h3><p>After cleaning, compare important totals against the source. Cleaning should explain changes, not silently change the business story.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    &#x27;raw products&#x27; AS check_name,\n    COUNT(*) AS row_count\nFROM products\nUNION ALL\nSELECT\n    &#x27;clean products&#x27;,\n    COUNT(*)\nFROM products_clean;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>For sales data, reconcile revenue before and after cleaning:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS source_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS clean_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>In this small teaching database those totals should match. In a real dataset, any difference must be explained by a documented rule, such as excluding cancelled orders.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Freshness and distribution checks\"><h3>Freshness and distribution checks</h3><p>Freshness asks whether the data is current enough for the decision.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    MAX(order_date) AS latest_order_date,\n    DATEDIFF(CURRENT_DATE, MAX(order_date)) AS days_since_latest_order\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>Distribution checks ask whether values look plausible.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    category,\n    COUNT(*) AS product_count,\n    MIN(price) AS min_price,\n    MAX(price) AS max_price,\n    ROUND(AVG(price), 3) AS avg_price\nFROM products_clean\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>Freshness and distribution checks do not always prove a value is wrong. They tell you where to investigate.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Test relationships between tables", "Deduplicate safely", "Keep a cleaning log", "Reconcile before trusting analysis", "Freshness and distribution checks"]}, {"title": "Data Quality Lab and Chapter Summary", "time": 24, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 4 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Data Quality Lab and Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain data quality lab and chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>A correct query on unreliable data still produces an unreliable answer; profiling and safe cleaning protect decisions.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Deduplication, Audit Logs, and Reconciliation.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">These exercises ask you to detect issues and preview transformations without destroying source evidence. Use the checklist as an ordered cleaning workflow.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common mistakes\"><h3>Common mistakes</h3><p>Do not update data before profiling it, clean without a written rule, confuse NULL with blank text, treat boolean SUM checks as portable to every SQL database, delete duplicates without identifying the correct survivor, assume a backup copied constraints, or commit before validating affected rows.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Find missing or blank categories\"><h3>Practice 1: Find missing or blank categories</h3><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then keep rows where <code>category IS NULL OR TRIM(category) = &#x27;&#x27;</code>, then return <code>*</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>category IS NULL OR TRIM(category) = &#x27;&#x27;</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>*</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM products\nWHERE category IS NULL\n   OR TRIM(category) = &#x27;&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Find possible duplicate product names\"><h3>Practice 2: Find possible duplicate product names</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    LOWER(TRIM(product_name)) AS normalized_name,\n    COUNT(*) AS duplicate_count\nFROM products\nGROUP BY LOWER(TRIM(product_name))\nHAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Preview trimmed product names\"><h3>Practice 3: Preview trimmed product names</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_id,\n    product_name AS original_name,\n    TRIM(product_name) AS cleaned_name\nFROM products\nWHERE product_name &lt;&gt; TRIM(product_name);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Report invalid order values\"><h3>Practice 4: Report invalid order values</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_id,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price,\n    CASE\n        WHEN quantity &lt;= 0 THEN &#x27;Invalid quantity&#x27;\n        WHEN unit_price &lt; 0 THEN &#x27;Invalid price&#x27;\n        ELSE &#x27;Valid&#x27;\n    END AS validation_result\nFROM orders\nWHERE quantity &lt;= 0 OR unit_price &lt; 0;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Find products outside accepted categories\"><h3>Practice 5: Find products outside accepted categories</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_id,\n    product_name,\n    category\nFROM products_clean\nWHERE category NOT IN (&#x27;Coffee&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;)\n   OR category IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 6: Find relationship failures between orders and products\"><h3>Practice 6: Find relationship failures between orders and products</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_id\nFROM orders AS o\nLEFT JOIN products AS p\n    ON p.product_id = o.product_id\nWHERE p.product_id IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 11 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 11 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Task</th><th>Pattern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Count missing values</td><td>COUNT(*) - COUNT(column)</td></tr><tr><td>Find NULL</td><td>IS NULL</td></tr><tr><td>Find blank text</td><td>TRIM(COALESCE(column, &#x27;&#x27;)) = &#x27;&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>Find duplicates</td><td>GROUP BY ... HAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 1</td></tr><tr><td>Choose duplicate survivor</td><td>ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY ... ORDER BY ...)</td></tr><tr><td>Preview changes</td><td>SELECT with the intended WHERE</td></tr><tr><td>Test changes safely</td><td>START TRANSACTION ... ROLLBACK</td></tr><tr><td>Prevent bad values</td><td>CHECK, NOT NULL, keys</td></tr><tr><td>Test accepted values</td><td>WHERE column NOT IN (...)</td></tr><tr><td>Test relationships</td><td>LEFT JOIN parent ... WHERE parent.key IS NULL</td></tr><tr><td>Track cleaning decisions</td><td>cleaning_log table</td></tr><tr><td>Reconcile after cleaning</td><td>Compare counts and totals before analysis</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Common mistakes", "Practice 1: Find missing or blank categories", "Practice 2: Find possible duplicate product names", "Practice 3: Preview trimmed product names", "Practice 4: Report invalid order values", "Practice 5: Find products outside accepted categories", "Practice 6: Find relationship failures between orders and products", "Segment 11 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 4</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>A correct query on unreliable data still produces an unreliable answer; profiling and safe cleaning protect decisions.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Data Quality Lab and Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"Previewing the same condition reduces the risk of changing unintended rows.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What should happen before UPDATE?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Preview affected rows with SELECT</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Delete the backup</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Disable constraints</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A transaction allows inspection and ROLLBACK before changes become permanent.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Why use a transaction for cleaning?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">It supports validation before COMMIT</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">It changes VARCHAR to DATE</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">It removes every duplicate</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"Blank text is a stored string; NULL represents a missing value.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Are blank text and NULL identical?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Yes</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">No</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Only in ORDER BY</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Safe product cleanup", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 4</p><h2>Safe product cleanup</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>A correct query on unreliable data still produces an unreliable answer; profiling and safe cleaning protect decisions.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>An imported staging table contains whitespace, blank categories, invalid prices, and duplicates.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Profile each issue with SELECT queries.</li><li>Write documented cleaning rules and preview transformed values.</li><li>Apply safe fixes inside a transaction, validate, then choose COMMIT or ROLLBACK.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Original problems are measured before changes</li><li>Rules do not invent unknown business facts</li><li>UPDATE conditions are narrow</li><li>Validation occurs before transaction completion</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT COUNT(*) AS rows_total,\n       SUM(category IS NULL OR TRIM(category) = &#x27;&#x27;) AS missing_category,\n       SUM(price &lt;= 0 OR price IS NULL) AS invalid_price\nFROM products_staging;\nSELECT LOWER(TRIM(product_name)) AS normalized_name, COUNT(*)\nFROM products_staging GROUP BY normalized_name HAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 1;\nSTART TRANSACTION;\nUPDATE products_staging SET product_name = TRIM(product_name)\nWHERE product_name &lt;&gt; TRIM(product_name);\nSELECT * FROM products_staging;\n-- COMMIT only after the validation queries pass; otherwise ROLLBACK;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>SELECT COUNT(*) AS rows_total, SUM(category IS NULL OR TRIM(category)…</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>SELECT LOWER(TRIM(product_name)) AS normalized_name, COUNT(*) FROM pr…</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li><li><strong>3. <code>START TRANSACTION</code></strong><span>Starts a transaction; no result grid.</span></li><li><strong>4. <code>UPDATE products_staging SET product_name = TRIM(product_name) WHERE p…</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li><li><strong>5. <code>SELECT * FROM products_staging</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li><li><strong>6. <code>-- COMMIT only after the validation queries pass</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li><li><strong>7. <code>otherwise ROLLBACK</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li></ol></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 11, "workflow_number": 4}, {"title": "CASE, Dates & Text", "desc": "Create business labels, calendar dimensions, and clean reporting text.", "lessons": [{"title": "Turning Facts into Business Categories", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 5 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Turning Facts into Business Categories</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain turning facts into business categories, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>CASE, date, and text expressions convert stored values into dimensions people can use in reports.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">CASE applies ordered business rules inside a query. We use it both to label individual rows and to count conditional populations within an aggregate.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Real business data needs labels, calendar groupings, and cleaned text. This segment teaches the functions analysts use to turn stored values into reporting dimensions.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"CASE creates business categories\"><h3>CASE creates business categories</h3><p>CASE evaluates conditions from top to bottom and returns the value from the first true condition.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then return <code>product_name, price, CASE WHEN price &gt;= 3.000 THEN &#x27;Premium&#x27; WHEN price &gt;= 2.000…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, price, CASE WHEN price &gt;= 3.000 THEN &#x27;Premium&#x27; WHEN price &gt;= 2.000…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>price DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    price,\n    CASE\n        WHEN price &gt;= 3.000 THEN &#x27;Premium&#x27;\n        WHEN price &gt;= 2.000 THEN &#x27;Standard&#x27;\n        ELSE &#x27;Value&#x27;\n    END AS price_band\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th><th>price_band</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">Premium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">Standard</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">Standard</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">Value</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">Value</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">Value</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Order the conditions from most restrictive to least restrictive. CASE stops after its first match.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"CASE inside an aggregate\"><h3>CASE inside an aggregate</h3><p>Conditional aggregation counts or sums only rows that meet a condition.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    SUM(CASE WHEN quantity &gt;= 3 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS large_order_rows,\n    SUM(CASE WHEN quantity &lt; 3 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS smaller_order_rows\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>large_order_rows</th><th>smaller_order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">7</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Each CASE produces 1 or 0 for every row; SUM adds those flags.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-10-functions.webp\" alt=\"Order receipts moving through CASE labeling, date extraction, and text-cleaning stations.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>CASE, date functions, and text functions turn stored facts into useful reporting dimensions. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "CASE creates business categories", "CASE inside an aggregate"]}, {"title": "Working with Dates, Text, and Safe Ratios", "time": 30, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 5 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Working with Dates, Text, and Safe Ratios</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain working with dates, text, and safe ratios, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>CASE, date, and text expressions convert stored values into dimensions people can use in reports.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Turning Facts into Business Categories.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Dates, text, and NULL-aware expressions often require transformation before reporting. We extract calendar parts, format labels, measure intervals, build rolling windows, standardize text, combine fields, handle missing display values, and protect ratio calculations.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Extracting calendar parts\"><h3>Extracting calendar parts</h3><p>YEAR, MONTH, and DAY extract calendar components from a date.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>order_date, YEAR(order_date) AS order_year, MONTH(order_date) AS order_month, DAY…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>order_date, YEAR(order_date) AS order_year, MONTH(order_date) AS order_month, DAY…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>order_date</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_date,\n    YEAR(order_date) AS order_year,\n    MONTH(order_date) AS order_month,\n    DAY(order_date) AS order_day\nFROM orders\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>order_year</th><th>order_month</th><th>order_day</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>These functions are useful for labeling, but date ranges are often better for filtering because indexes can be used more effectively.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Formatting dates for reports\"><h3>Formatting dates for reports</h3><p>DATE_FORMAT converts a date into a display label.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_date,\n    DATE_FORMAT(order_date, &#x27;%Y-%m&#x27;) AS sales_month,\n    DATE_FORMAT(order_date, &#x27;%W&#x27;) AS weekday_name\nFROM orders\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>sales_month</th><th>weekday_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Saturday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Saturday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Saturday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Sunday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Sunday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Sunday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Monday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Monday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Monday</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Tuesday</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Formatting changes the result display, not the stored DATE value.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Casting datetimes to dates with DATE\"><h3>Casting datetimes to dates with DATE</h3><p>DATE extracts the date portion from a date or datetime value.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_date,\n    DATE(order_date) AS order_day\nFROM orders\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>This is useful when a timestamp includes hours, minutes, and seconds but the report needs calendar-day grain. Be careful in filters: applying DATE() to a column inside WHERE can make an index less useful. For date-range filters, compare the raw column to start and end boundaries when possible.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Measuring time with DATEDIFF\"><h3>Measuring time with DATEDIFF</h3><p>DATEDIFF returns the number of days between two dates.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    MIN(order_date) AS first_order_date,\n    MAX(order_date) AS last_order_date,\n    DATEDIFF(MAX(order_date), MIN(order_date)) AS days_between\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>first_order_date</th><th>last_order_date</th><th>days_between</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>The later date is the first argument. Reversing the arguments produces a negative result.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Measuring larger intervals with TIMESTAMPDIFF\"><h3>Measuring larger intervals with TIMESTAMPDIFF</h3><p>TIMESTAMPDIFF measures the difference between two date or datetime values in a unit you choose.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    MIN(order_date) AS first_order_date,\n    MAX(order_date) AS last_order_date,\n    TIMESTAMPDIFF(DAY, MIN(order_date), MAX(order_date)) AS days_between,\n    TIMESTAMPDIFF(MONTH, MIN(order_date), MAX(order_date)) AS whole_months_between\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>The unit comes first. Unlike DATEDIFF, TIMESTAMPDIFF can measure units such as DAY, MONTH, YEAR, HOUR, or MINUTE. It is useful for ages, customer tenure, and time-between-event questions.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Finding rolling windows with DATE_SUB\"><h3>Finding rolling windows with DATE_SUB</h3><p>DATE_SUB subtracts an interval from a date.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    MAX(order_date) AS latest_order_date,\n    DATE_SUB(MAX(order_date), INTERVAL 45 DAY) AS window_start_date\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>Analysts use this pattern for questions such as &quot;customers with no completed purchase in the latest 45 days.&quot; The interval unit can be DAY, MONTH, YEAR, HOUR, or another supported MySQL interval unit.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Cleaning text with TRIM\"><h3>Cleaning text with TRIM</h3><p>TRIM removes leading and trailing spaces.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    TRIM(product_name) AS cleaned_product_name\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>cleaned_product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>TRIM does not normally remove repeated spaces inside a string.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Standardizing letter case\"><h3>Standardizing letter case</h3><p>LOWER and UPPER create consistent comparison or display values.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    LOWER(product_name) AS lowercase_name,\n    UPPER(category) AS uppercase_category\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>lowercase_name</th><th>uppercase_category</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">iced latte</td><td class=\"\">COFFEE</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">cold brew</td><td class=\"\">COFFEE</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">croissant</td><td class=\"\">PASTRY</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">brownie</td><td class=\"\">DESSERT</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">matcha latte</td><td class=\"\">TEA</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">americano</td><td class=\"\">COFFEE</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Do not permanently change stored text merely for presentation unless the business rule requires it.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Combining text with CONCAT\"><h3>Combining text with CONCAT</h3><p>CONCAT joins values into one string.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_id,\n    CONCAT(product_name, &#x27; — &#x27;, category) AS product_label\nFROM products\nORDER BY product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_label</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte — Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew — Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant — Pastry</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie — Dessert</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte — Tea</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano — Coffee</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>If any CONCAT argument is NULL, MySQL returns NULL. CONCAT_WS can skip NULL arguments.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Handling missing display values\"><h3>Handling missing display values</h3><p>COALESCE returns the first non-NULL value.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    COALESCE(category, &#x27;Uncategorized&#x27;) AS display_category\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>display_category</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>COALESCE is for missing values. An empty string is not NULL and must be handled separately.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Extracting calendar parts", "Formatting dates for reports", "Casting datetimes to dates with DATE", "Measuring time with DATEDIFF", "Measuring larger intervals with TIMESTAMPDIFF", "Finding rolling windows with DATE_SUB", "Cleaning text with TRIM", "Standardizing letter case", "Combining text with CONCAT", "Handling missing display values"]}, {"title": "Project Metric Definitions", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 5 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Project Metric Definitions</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain project metric definitions, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>CASE, date, and text expressions convert stored values into dimensions people can use in reports.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Working with Dates, Text, and Safe Ratios.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A useful report combines transformations without obscuring their meaning. We connect gross revenue, net revenue, refunds, inventory rules, monthly reporting, and common mistakes to explicit business definitions.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Avoiding divide-by-zero with NULLIF\"><h3>Avoiding divide-by-zero with NULLIF</h3><p>NULLIF returns NULL when its two arguments are equal. Analysts often use it to prevent divide-by-zero errors in percentage calculations.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue, SUM(quantity) AS units_sold, ROUND(SUM(qua…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue, SUM(quantity) AS units_sold, ROUND(SUM(qua…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue,\n    SUM(quantity) AS units_sold,\n    ROUND(SUM(quantity * unit_price) / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0), 3) AS revenue_per_unit\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>If SUM(quantity) is 0, NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0) returns NULL instead of 0. Dividing by NULL returns NULL, which is safer than producing an error or a misleading number.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Gross, net, refunds, and inventory rules\"><h3>Gross, net, refunds, and inventory rules</h3><p>Some project metrics are business definitions, not new SQL syntax.</p><p>Gross revenue usually means revenue before refunds or other adjustments. Net revenue usually means revenue after subtracting agreed adjustments such as refunds. Inventory risk is a stock rule, such as on_hand_quantity below reorder_point.</p><p>Refund timing is also a definition. Some teams subtract refunds in the month the return happened. Other teams subtract refunds from the original sale month. Neither choice is automatically correct; the report must state which rule it uses.</p><p>Before writing a query, ask the business owner:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Question to define</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Gross revenue</td><td>Before or after discounts?</td></tr><tr><td>Net revenue</td><td>Which refunds or adjustments are subtracted?</td></tr><tr><td>Return rate</td><td>Return rows, returned units, or refund value?</td></tr><tr><td>Inventory risk</td><td>Below reorder point, zero stock, or days of supply?</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Once the definition is clear, the SQL is built from tools you already know: joins, filters, aggregates, CASE labels, CTEs, and window functions.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Building a monthly category report\"><h3>Building a monthly category report</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    DATE_FORMAT(o.order_date, &#x27;%Y-%m&#x27;) AS sales_month,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue,\n    CASE\n        WHEN SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) &gt;= 20 THEN &#x27;High&#x27;\n        WHEN SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) &gt;= 10 THEN &#x27;Medium&#x27;\n        ELSE &#x27;Low&#x27;\n    END AS performance_band\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p ON p.product_id = o.product_id\nGROUP BY DATE_FORMAT(o.order_date, &#x27;%Y-%m&#x27;), p.category\nORDER BY sales_month, revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>sales_month</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>performance_band</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">13</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td><td class=\"\">High</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">Low</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">Low</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">Low</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>CASE can classify an aggregate because grouping is completed before the grouped SELECT expression is evaluated.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Avoiding divide-by-zero with NULLIF", "Gross, net, refunds, and inventory rules", "Building a monthly category report"]}, {"title": "Functions Lab and Chapter Summary", "time": 18, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 5 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Functions Lab and Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain functions lab and chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>CASE, date, and text expressions convert stored values into dimensions people can use in reports.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Project Metric Definitions.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The exercises combine CASE, weekday reporting, cleaned labels, and grouped revenue bands. Use the summary to distinguish formatting from permanent data cleaning.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common mistakes\"><h3>Common mistakes</h3><p>Common mistakes include placing broad CASE conditions before narrow ones, confusing display formatting with stored values, filtering dates by formatted text, applying DATE() in WHERE when a raw range would be more index-friendly, forgetting that CONCAT returns NULL when an argument is NULL, treating empty strings as NULL, dividing by zero in ratio calculations, and using gross or net revenue without defining which adjustments are included.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Label order rows by size\"><h3>Practice 1: Label order rows by size</h3><p>Return order_id and quantity. Label quantities of 3 or more Large and the rest Regular.</p><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>order_id, quantity, CASE WHEN quantity &gt;= 3 THEN &#x27;Large&#x27; ELSE &#x27;Regular&#x27; END AS or…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>order_id, quantity, CASE WHEN quantity &gt;= 3 THEN &#x27;Large&#x27; ELSE &#x27;Regular&#x27; END AS or…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>order_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_id,\n    quantity,\n    CASE WHEN quantity &gt;= 3 THEN &#x27;Large&#x27; ELSE &#x27;Regular&#x27; END AS order_size\nFROM orders\nORDER BY order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>quantity</th><th>order_size</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Regular</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Regular</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Large</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Regular</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Regular</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Regular</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Large</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Regular</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Regular</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Large</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Revenue by weekday\"><h3>Practice 2: Revenue by weekday</h3><p>Return weekday name and revenue, ordered by revenue descending.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    DATE_FORMAT(order_date, &#x27;%W&#x27;) AS weekday_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY DATE_FORMAT(order_date, &#x27;%W&#x27;)\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>weekday_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Saturday</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Monday</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Sunday</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tuesday</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Clean product labels\"><h3>Practice 3: Clean product labels</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Create an uppercase label combining trimmed product_name and category.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_id,\n    UPPER(CONCAT(TRIM(product_name), &#x27; — &#x27;, TRIM(category))) AS product_label\nFROM products\nORDER BY product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_label</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">ICED LATTE — COFFEE</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">COLD BREW — COFFEE</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">CROISSANT — PASTRY</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">BROWNIE — DESSERT</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">MATCHA LATTE — TEA</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">AMERICANO — COFFEE</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Product revenue bands\"><h3>Practice 4: Product revenue bands</h3><p>Calculate revenue by product and label revenue of at least 9.000 High, at least 5.000 Medium, otherwise Low.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    p.product_name,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue,\n    CASE\n        WHEN SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) &gt;= 9.000 THEN &#x27;High&#x27;\n        WHEN SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) &gt;= 5.000 THEN &#x27;Medium&#x27;\n        ELSE &#x27;Low&#x27;\n    END AS revenue_band\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>revenue_band</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">High</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">High</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">Low</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 10 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 10 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Function</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Create business labels</td><td>CASE ... WHEN ... END</td></tr><tr><td>Extract date parts</td><td>YEAR(), MONTH(), DAY()</td></tr><tr><td>Cast datetime to date</td><td>DATE()</td></tr><tr><td>Create date labels</td><td>DATE_FORMAT()</td></tr><tr><td>Measure days</td><td>DATEDIFF()</td></tr><tr><td>Measure flexible intervals</td><td>TIMESTAMPDIFF()</td></tr><tr><td>Build rolling date windows</td><td>DATE_SUB(..., INTERVAL ...)</td></tr><tr><td>Remove outside spaces</td><td>TRIM()</td></tr><tr><td>Standardize case</td><td>LOWER(), UPPER()</td></tr><tr><td>Combine text</td><td>CONCAT(), CONCAT_WS()</td></tr><tr><td>Replace NULL for display</td><td>COALESCE()</td></tr><tr><td>Prevent zero denominators</td><td>NULLIF()</td></tr><tr><td>Define adjusted metrics</td><td>Gross, net, refund, and inventory rules</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Common mistakes", "Practice 1: Label order rows by size", "Practice 2: Revenue by weekday", "Practice 3: Clean product labels", "Practice 4: Product revenue bands", "Segment 10 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 5</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>CASE, date, and text expressions convert stored values into dimensions people can use in reports.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Functions Lab and Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"CASE maps conditions to output values inside a query.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What does CASE produce?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">A derived value based on conditions</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">A new server</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">An index automatically</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"COALESCE returns the first non-NULL argument.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Which function can replace NULL with a fallback?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">COALESCE</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">RANK</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">DROP</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A half-open range avoids accidentally excluding times late on the final day.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Why use an exclusive upper date bound for timestamps?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">It safely includes the full prior period</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">It sorts faster in every case</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Dates cannot use equality</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Presentation-ready sales labels", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 5</p><h2>Presentation-ready sales labels</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>CASE, date, and text expressions convert stored values into dimensions people can use in reports.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>A report needs consistent product labels, calendar fields, and revenue bands.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Create a cleaned uppercase product label.</li><li>Return year, month, and weekday from order_date.</li><li>Classify row revenue into low, medium, and high bands with CASE.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Text output is consistently formatted</li><li>Date functions use order_date</li><li>CASE conditions are ordered without overlap</li><li>Aliases are report-friendly</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT UPPER(TRIM(p.product_name)) AS product_label,\n       YEAR(o.order_date) AS order_year, MONTH(o.order_date) AS order_month,\n       DAYNAME(o.order_date) AS weekday, o.quantity * o.unit_price AS row_revenue,\n       CASE WHEN o.quantity * o.unit_price &gt;= 6 THEN &#x27;High&#x27;\n            WHEN o.quantity * o.unit_price &gt;= 3 THEN &#x27;Medium&#x27; ELSE &#x27;Low&#x27; END AS revenue_band\nFROM orders o JOIN products p ON p.product_id = o.product_id\nORDER BY o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_label</th><th>order_year</th><th>order_month</th><th>weekday</th><th>row_revenue</th><th>revenue_band</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">ICED LATTE</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Saturday</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">COLD BREW</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Saturday</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">CROISSANT</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Saturday</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">BROWNIE</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Sunday</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">ICED LATTE</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Sunday</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">Low</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">MATCHA LATTE</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Sunday</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">AMERICANO</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Monday</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">Medium</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">COLD BREW</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Monday</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">High</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">CROISSANT</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Monday</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">Low</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">ICED LATTE</td><td class=\"\">2026</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Tuesday</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">High</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 10, "workflow_number": 5}, {"title": "Orders & KPIs", "desc": "Create orders and calculate revenue, aggregates, KPIs, and filtered metrics.", "lessons": [{"title": "Modeling Sales Events", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 6 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Modeling Sales Events</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain modeling sales events, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><section class=\"concept-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">BUILD THE MENTAL MODEL</p><div><span>CORE IDEA</span><p>Transactional rows record events. Metrics are deliberate calculations over those rows, and different calculations answer different questions.</p></div><div><span>CONCRETE EXAMPLE</span><p>Ten order lines contain 21 units and 45.800 revenue. Row count, unit count, and money are three different KPIs.</p></div><div><span>EXPLAIN IT BACK</span><p>Is the requested metric counting rows, adding units, or calculating money?</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A products table describes the menu; it cannot tell us what sold. We define the grain of an order row and decide which event facts must be recorded before calculating any metric.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Creating an orders Table + Doing Your First Real Analytics 📊🔥</p><p>Now we’re going to make your database feel like an actual data analyst project.</p><p>Right now, you have this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">coffee_shop\n│\n└── products</pre><p>But a product list by itself does not answer the most important business questions.</p><p>A data analyst usually needs to answer questions like:</p><p>How many orders did we get?<br>How much revenue did we make?<br>Which product sold the most?<br>What was the average order-row revenue?<br>Which day made the most money?</p><p>To answer those, we need an orders table.</p><p>By the end of this segment, your database will look like this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">coffee_shop\n│\n├── products\n└── orders</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why We Need an orders Table\"><h3>Why We Need an orders Table</h3><p>Your products table tells us what the coffee shop sells.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>But it does not tell us what customers bought.</p><p>For that, we need order data.</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now we can start asking analyst questions.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Products Table vs Orders Table\"><h3>Products Table vs Orders Table</h3><p>Think of it like this:</p><p>products table<br>=<br>Menu items<br>orders table<br>=<br>What customers actually bought</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">products table\n┌────────────┬──────────────┬──────────┬───────┐\n│ product_id │ product_name │ category │ price │\n└────────────┴──────────────┴──────────┴───────┘\norders table\n┌──────────┬──────────────┬──────────┬────────────┬────────────┐\n│ order_id │ product_name │ quantity │ unit_price │ order_date │\n└──────────┴──────────────┴──────────┴────────────┴────────────┘</pre><p>The products table is about items.</p><p>The orders table is about transactions.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What Columns Should orders Have?\"><h3>What Columns Should orders Have?</h3><p>For now, we’ll keep the orders table beginner-friendly.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><caption>Table name: orders</caption><thead><tr><th>Column</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>order_id</td><td>Unique number for each order row</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>product_name</td><td>Product that was purchased</td><td>&#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>category</td><td>Product category</td><td>&#x27;Coffee&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>quantity</td><td>How many were bought</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>unit_price</td><td>Price of one item</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>order_date</td><td>Date of the order</td><td>&#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><p>orders table blueprint</p><pre class=\"diagram\">┌──────────────┬────────────────────────────┐\n│ Column       │ What it stores             │\n├──────────────┼────────────────────────────┤\n│ order_id     │ Order row ID               │\n│ product_name │ Item bought                │\n│ category     │ Item category              │\n│ quantity     │ Number of items bought     │\n│ unit_price   │ Price for one item         │\n│ order_date   │ Date of purchase           │\n└──────────────┴────────────────────────────┘</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why Are We Repeating Product Name and Price?\"><h3>Why Are We Repeating Product Name and Price?</h3><p>You may notice something:</p><p>product_name<br>category<br>unit_price</p><p>already exist in the products table.</p><p>So why put them in orders too?</p><p>Great analyst question 👏</p><p>For now, we are doing this because you are learning beginner SQL analytics.</p><p>It lets you practice:</p><p>COUNT<br>SUM<br>AVG<br>MIN<br>MAX<br>GROUP BY<br>ORDER BY</p><p>without making the database too complicated yet.</p><p>Later, we will improve the design using:</p><p>JOIN</p><p>That lets one table connect to another table.</p><p>For now, the goal is:</p><p>Learn how analysts calculate numbers from rows.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-03-kpis.webp\" alt=\"Order rows passing through a revenue calculation and producing business KPI cards.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>Row-level revenue is quantity multiplied by unit price. Aggregates combine those rows into useful KPIs. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "Why We Need an orders Table", "Products Table vs Orders Table", "What Columns Should orders Have?", "Why Are We Repeating Product Name and Price?"]}, {"title": "Building and Loading the Orders Table", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 6 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Building and Loading the Orders Table</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain building and loading the orders table, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Modeling Sales Events.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The order schema introduces dates and repeated sale-line facts. We create it, load a fixed dataset, inspect the rows, and preserve a reset script for repeatable analysis.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Creating the orders Table\"><h3>Creating the orders Table</h3><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to select the active database for <code>this</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>USE THIS</code><strong>Use this SQL: CREATE TABLE orders ( order_id INT, product_name VARCHAR(100), category VARCHAR(50),…</strong><p>Select the active database.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use this SQL:\nCREATE TABLE orders (\n    order_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    quantity INT,\n    unit_price DECIMAL(6,3),\n    order_date DATE\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>this</code>.</p></aside><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders\n│\n├── order_id       INT\n├── product_name   VARCHAR(100)\n├── category       VARCHAR(50)\n├── quantity       INT\n├── unit_price     DECIMAL(6,3)\n└── order_date     DATE</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Understanding the New Data Type: DATE\"><h3>Understanding the New Data Type: DATE</h3><p>We used a new data type:</p><p>DATE</p><p>A MySQL DATE stores a calendar date.</p><p>The format is:</p><p>YYYY-MM-DD</p><p>Example:</p><p>&#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">2026-06-20\n│    │  │\n│    │  └── Day\n│    └───── Month\n└────────── Year</pre><p>Correct:</p><p>&#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;</p><p>Incorrect:</p><p>&#x27;06-20-2026&#x27;</p><p>Incorrect:</p><p>&#x27;20-06-2026&#x27;</p><p>For MySQL, use:</p><p>Year-Month-Day</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Insert Order Data\"><h3>Insert Order Data</h3><p>Now we add rows into the orders table.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use this:\nINSERT INTO orders (order_id, product_name, category, quantity, unit_price, order_date)\nVALUES\n    (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (2, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (3, &#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 3, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (4, &#x27;Brownie&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;, 2, 1.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (5, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (6, &#x27;Matcha Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, 2, 2.900, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (7, &#x27;Americano&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 4, 1.250, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (8, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (9, &#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (10, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-23&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>this</code>.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"View the Orders Table\"><h3>View the Orders Table</h3><p>Now run:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2</td><td>2.900</td><td>2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Full Clean Reset Script for Segment 3\"><h3>Full Clean Reset Script for Segment 3</h3><p>If your table already exists, use this clean script.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Database container created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL reports success; <code>SHOW DATABASES LIKE 'coffee_shop';</code> returns one row afterward.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>USE coffee_shop;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>coffee_shop</code>.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE TABLE orders (\n    order_id INT,\n    product_name VARCHAR(100),\n    category VARCHAR(50),\n    quantity INT,\n    unit_price DECIMAL(6,3),\n    order_date DATE\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Table structure created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>orders</code>; run <code>DESCRIBE orders;</code> to verify its columns and constraints.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>INSERT INTO orders (order_id, product_name, category, quantity, unit_price, order_date)\nVALUES\n    (1, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (2, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (3, &#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 3, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;),\n    (4, &#x27;Brownie&#x27;, &#x27;Dessert&#x27;, 2, 1.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (5, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 1, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (6, &#x27;Matcha Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;, 2, 2.900, &#x27;2026-06-21&#x27;),\n    (7, &#x27;Americano&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 4, 1.250, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (8, &#x27;Cold Brew&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 2, 3.000, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (9, &#x27;Croissant&#x27;, &#x27;Pastry&#x27;, 1, 1.500, &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;),\n    (10, &#x27;Iced Latte&#x27;, &#x27;Coffee&#x27;, 3, 2.750, &#x27;2026-06-23&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Rows inserted</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. MySQL reports 10 affected rows in <code>orders</code>. Run the following lesson SELECT to verify stored values.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Creating the orders Table", "Understanding the New Data Type: DATE", "Insert Order Data", "View the Orders Table", "Full Clean Reset Script for Segment 3"]}, {"title": "Calculated Columns and Aliases", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 6 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Calculated Columns and Aliases</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain calculated columns and aliases, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Building and Loading the Orders Table.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Row-level arithmetic creates a value for each source row. We calculate revenue, name it with an alias, and distinguish a temporary result expression from a permanent table change.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Your First Calculated Column\"><h3>Your First Calculated Column</h3><p>Now we start doing analytics.</p><p>Each order row has:</p><p>quantity<br>unit_price</p><p>To calculate revenue for each row:</p><p>quantity × unit_price</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Because:</p><p>2 × 2.750 = 5.500</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>product_name, quantity, unit_price, quantity * unit_price</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, quantity, unit_price, quantity * unit_price</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price,\n    quantity * unit_price\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>quantity * unit_price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>quantity * unit_price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>4.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Naming a Calculated Column with AS\"><h3>Naming a Calculated Column with AS</h3><p>The column name quantity * unit_price looks ugly.</p><p>We can rename it using:</p><p>AS</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price,\n    quantity * unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>4.500</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">quantity * unit_price\n        ↓\nAS revenue\n        ↓\nclean column name</pre><p>AS creates a temporary display name.</p><p>It does not permanently change the table.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Calculated Columns Do Not Change the Table\"><h3>Calculated Columns Do Not Change the Table</h3><p>This query:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    quantity * unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>does not add a real column to the table.</p><p>It only creates the result while the query runs.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders table\n      ↓\nSQL calculation\n      ↓\ntemporary result table</pre><p>The original table still looks like this:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class=\"empty-result\"><td colspan=\"6\">No data rows</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>The result can look like this:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class=\"empty-result\"><td colspan=\"2\">No data rows</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That result is temporary.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Your First Calculated Column", "Naming a Calculated Column with AS", "Calculated Columns Do Not Change the Table"]}, {"title": "Aggregate Functions and KPI Foundations", "time": 27, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 6 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Aggregate Functions and KPI Foundations</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain aggregate functions and kpi foundations, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Calculated Columns and Aliases.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Aggregate functions reduce many rows to summary evidence. COUNT, SUM, AVG, MIN, and MAX answer different questions, so we connect each calculation to its exact business meaning.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"First Real Analyst Question: Total Revenue\"><h3>First Real Analyst Question: Total Revenue</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>How much money did the coffee shop make?</p><p>To answer this, we need to add up every row’s revenue.</p><p>We use:</p><p>SUM()</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Let’s calculate it visually.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>4.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>3.500</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.900</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>Croissant</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Add the revenue column:</p><p>5.500<br>+ 3.000<br>+ 4.500<br>+ 3.500<br>+ 2.750<br>+ 5.800<br>+ 5.000<br>+ 6.000<br>+ 1.500<br>+ 8.250<br>= 45.800</p><p>Expected result:</p><p>total_revenue<br>45.800</p><p>That is your first real analytics metric 🎉</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What Is an Aggregate Function?\"><h3>What Is an Aggregate Function?</h3><p>An aggregate function takes many rows and returns one answer.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Many rows\n   ↓\nAggregate function\n   ↓\nOne result</pre><p>Common aggregate functions:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>COUNT()</td><td>Count rows</td></tr><tr><td>SUM()</td><td>Add values</td></tr><tr><td>AVG()</td><td>Average values</td></tr><tr><td>MIN()</td><td>Smallest value</td></tr><tr><td>MAX()</td><td>Largest value</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Counting Rows with COUNT\"><h3>Counting Rows with COUNT</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>How many order rows are in the table?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    COUNT(*) AS total_order_rows\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">10</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>total_order_rows<br>10</p><p>Important:</p><p>COUNT(*) counts rows.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders table\n│\n├── row 1\n├── row 2\n├── row 3\n├── row 4\n├── row 5\n├── row 6\n├── row 7\n├── row 8\n├── row 9\n└── row 10</pre><p>COUNT(*) = 10</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Total Items Sold\"><h3>Total Items Sold</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>How many individual items did we sell?</p><p>This is different from total orders.</p><p>Look at this row:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That is:</p><p>1 order row<br>but 2 items sold</p><p>To count all items sold, use:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity) AS total_items_sold\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">21</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>total_items_sold<br>21</p><p>Visual:</p><p>quantity column</p><p>2<br>1<br>3<br>2<br>1<br>2<br>4<br>2<br>1<br>3<br>─<br>21</p><p>This is important.</p><p>COUNT(*) counts order rows.<br>SUM(quantity) counts items sold.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"COUNT(*) vs SUM(quantity)\"><h3>COUNT(*) vs SUM(quantity)</h3><p>This is a big beginner concept.</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>SQL</th><th>Answer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>How many order rows?</td><td>COUNT(*)</td><td>10</td></tr><tr><td>How many items sold?</td><td>SUM(quantity)</td><td>21</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><p>One row can contain multiple items.</p><p>order_id 1<br>quantity = 2</p><p>COUNT(*) sees:<br>1 row</p><p>SUM(quantity) sees:<br>2 items</p><p>So:</p><p>COUNT(*) ≠ total items sold</p><p>Unless every row has quantity 1.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Average Order Row Revenue\"><h3>Average Order Row Revenue</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>What is the average revenue per order row?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    AVG(quantity * unit_price) AS average_order_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>average_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">4.5800000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>average_order_revenue<br>4.5800000</p><p>That means the average row brings in:</p><p>4.580</p><p>The math:</p><p>total revenue ÷ number of order rows</p><p>45.800 ÷ 10 = 4.580</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Making Decimal Results Cleaner with ROUND\"><h3>Making Decimal Results Cleaner with ROUND</h3><p>Sometimes MySQL gives many decimal places.</p><p>Example:</p><p>4.5800000</p><p>We can make it cleaner:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    ROUND(AVG(quantity * unit_price), 3) AS average_order_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>average_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">4.580</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>average_order_revenue<br>4.580</p><p>ROUND(value, 3) means:</p><p>Round to 3 decimal places</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">ROUND(4.5800000, 3)\n        ↓\n4.580</pre><p>For money in Kuwait, 3 decimal places makes sense because KWD commonly uses three decimal places.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Highest Revenue Order Row\"><h3>Highest Revenue Order Row</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Which order row made the most revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_id,\n    product_name,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price,\n    quantity * unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders\nORDER BY revenue DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Calculate revenue\n      ↓\nSort highest to lowest\n      ↓\nKeep top 1</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Lowest Revenue Order Row\"><h3>Lowest Revenue Order Row</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Which order row made the least revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_id,\n    product_name,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price,\n    quantity * unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders\nORDER BY revenue ASC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>9</td><td>Croissant</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>1.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["First Real Analyst Question: Total Revenue", "What Is an Aggregate Function?", "Counting Rows with COUNT", "Total Items Sold", "COUNT(*) vs SUM(quantity)", "Average Order Row Revenue", "Making Decimal Results Cleaner with ROUND", "Highest Revenue Order Row", "Lowest Revenue Order Row"]}, {"title": "Filtering the Input to a Metric", "time": 24, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 6 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Filtering the Input to a Metric</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain filtering the input to a metric, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Aggregate Functions and KPI Foundations.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">WHERE controls which detail rows enter a calculation. We combine category, quantity, and date conditions while keeping filter logic separate from the aggregate itself.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Filtering Before Calculating\"><h3>Filtering Before Calculating</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>How much revenue came from Coffee only?</p><p>We need to:</p><p>1. Keep only Coffee rows<br>2. Calculate quantity × unit_price<br>3. Add the results</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then keep rows where <code>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</code>, then return <code>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS coffee_revenue</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS coffee_revenue</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS coffee_revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>coffee_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Coffee rows:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Expected result:</p><p>coffee_revenue<br>30.500</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">All orders\n   ↓\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n   ↓\nCoffee rows only\n   ↓\nSUM(quantity * unit_price)\n   ↓\n30.500</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue From Non-Coffee Items\"><h3>Revenue From Non-Coffee Items</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>How much revenue came from everything except Coffee?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS non_coffee_revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE category &lt;&gt; &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>non_coffee_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">15.300</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>&lt;&gt; means:</p><p>not equal to</p><p>Expected result:</p><p>non_coffee_revenue<br>15.300</p><p>Visual:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE category &lt;&gt; &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Keep:<br>Pastry<br>Dessert<br>Tea</p><p>Remove:<br>Coffee</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Using AND\"><h3>Using AND</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Which Coffee orders had quantity greater than 1?</p><p>We need two conditions:</p><p>category = Coffee<br>quantity &gt; 1</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_id,\n    product_name,\n    category,\n    quantity\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n  AND quantity &gt; 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><p>Condition 1: category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;<br>Condition 2: quantity &gt; 1</p><pre class=\"diagram\">AND means both must be true.\nCoffee?     Quantity &gt; 1?     Keep?\nYes         Yes               ✅\nYes         No                ❌\nNo          Yes               ❌\nNo          No                ❌</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Using OR\"><h3>Using OR</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Show orders that are either Coffee or Tea.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_id,\n    product_name,\n    category\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n   OR category = &#x27;Tea&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>7 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual:</p><p>OR means at least one condition must be true.</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Coffee?     Tea?      Keep?\nYes         No        ✅\nNo          Yes       ✅\nNo          No        ❌</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Cleaner OR with IN\"><h3>Cleaner OR with IN</h3><p>This query:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_id,\n    product_name,\n    category\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n   OR category = &#x27;Tea&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>7 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Can be written cleaner with:</p><p>IN</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_id,\n    product_name,\n    category\nFROM orders\nWHERE category IN (&#x27;Coffee&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>7 rows returned.</p></aside><p>This means:</p><p>Show rows where category is Coffee or Tea.</p><p>Visual:</p><p>category IN (&#x27;Coffee&#x27;, &#x27;Tea&#x27;)</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Keep these:\nCoffee ✅\nTea ✅\nRemove these:\nPastry ❌\nDessert ❌</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Filtering Dates\"><h3>Filtering Dates</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Show orders from June 22, 2026.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date = &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Date Ranges with BETWEEN\"><h3>Date Ranges with BETWEEN</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>Show orders from June 20 through June 22.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>9 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>Rows from:</p><p>2026-06-20<br>2026-06-21<br>2026-06-22</p><p>Important:</p><p>BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;</p><p>includes both dates.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">2026-06-20 ✅ included\n2026-06-21 ✅ included\n2026-06-22 ✅ included\n2026-06-23 ❌ not included</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue for a Date Range\"><h3>Revenue for a Date Range</h3><p>Business question:</p><p>How much revenue did we make from June 20 through June 22?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue_june_20_to_22\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>revenue_june_20_to_22</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">37.550</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>revenue_june_20_to_22<br>37.550</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">All orders\n   ↓\nKeep dates 2026-06-20 to 2026-06-22\n   ↓\nCalculate revenue\n   ↓\nAdd it up\n   ↓\n37.550</pre></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Filtering Before Calculating", "Revenue From Non-Coffee Items", "Using AND", "Using OR", "Cleaner OR with IN", "Filtering Dates", "Date Ranges with BETWEEN", "Revenue for a Date Range"]}, {"title": "Designing a Small KPI Report", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 6 · SECTION 6</p><h2>Designing a Small KPI Report</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain designing a small kpi report, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Filtering the Input to a Metric.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A dashboard is a set of consistently defined metrics, not merely several numbers. We combine the recurring query pattern and document what each KPI counts or calculates.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The Big Analyst Query Pattern\"><h3>The Big Analyst Query Pattern</h3><p>A lot of beginner analytics queries follow this shape:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    calculation AS metric_name\nFROM table_name\nWHERE condition;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside><p>Examples:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>COUNT(*) AS total_order_rows</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>COUNT(*) AS total_order_rows</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    COUNT(*) AS total_order_rows\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">10</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity) AS total_items_sold\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">21</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    AVG(quantity * unit_price) AS average_order_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>average_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">4.5800000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">SELECT      → What metric do you want?\nFROM        → Which table has the data?\nWHERE       → Which rows should count?</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Mini Dashboard Metrics\"><h3>Mini Dashboard Metrics</h3><p>A data analyst often creates dashboard metrics.</p><p>From our tiny orders table, we can create these:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>SQL</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Total order rows</td><td>COUNT(*)</td></tr><tr><td>Total items sold</td><td>SUM(quantity)</td></tr><tr><td>Total revenue</td><td>SUM(quantity * unit_price)</td></tr><tr><td>Average order revenue</td><td>AVG(quantity * unit_price)</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>You can run this as one query:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    COUNT(*) AS total_order_rows,\n    SUM(quantity) AS total_items_sold,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue,\n    ROUND(AVG(quantity * unit_price), 3) AS avg_order_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_order_rows</th><th>total_items_sold</th><th>total_revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">21</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td><td class=\"\">4.580</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_order_rows</th><th>total_items_sold</th><th>total_revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>10</td><td>21</td><td>45.800</td><td>4.580</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This is a very important moment.</p><p>You just made a basic analytics KPI table.</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders table\n      ↓\nSQL calculations\n      ↓\nKPI result\n┌──────────────┬──────────────────┬───────────────┬───────────────────┐\n│ total_order_rows │ total_items_sold │ total_revenue │ avg_order_revenue │\n└──────────────┴──────────────────┴───────────────┴───────────────────┘</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What Is a KPI?\"><h3>What Is a KPI?</h3><p>KPI means:</p><p>Key Performance Indicator</p><p>A KPI is an important number that helps measure performance.</p><p>For a coffee shop, KPIs could be:</p><p>Total revenue<br>Number of orders<br>average order-row revenue<br>Items sold<br>Best-selling product<br>Revenue by day<br>Revenue by category</p><p>A dashboard is usually just a collection of KPIs and charts.</p><p>SQL helps create those numbers.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["The Big Analyst Query Pattern", "Mini Dashboard Metrics", "What Is a KPI?"]}, {"title": "Sales Analysis Lab and Review", "time": 39, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 6 · SECTION 7</p><h2>Sales Analysis Lab and Review</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain sales analysis lab and review, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Designing a Small KPI Report.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">These exercises move from row inspection to filtered revenue metrics. Treat the challenge and debugging sections as a closed-book check of both syntax and metric meaning.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Show all orders\"><h3>Practice 1: Show all orders</h3><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to select the active database for <code>your</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>USE YOUR</code><strong>Use your orders table. SELECT * FROM orders;</strong><p>Select the active database.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use your orders table.\nSELECT *\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>your</code>.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Show product name, quantity, and order date\"><h3>Practice 2: Show product name, quantity, and order date</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    quantity,\n    order_date\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Show revenue for each order row\"><h3>Practice 3: Show revenue for each order row</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_id,\n    product_name,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price,\n    quantity * unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Show total revenue\"><h3>Practice 4: Show total revenue</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Show total items sold\"><h3>Practice 5: Show total items sold</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity) AS total_items_sold\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">21</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 6: Show average order revenue\"><h3>Practice 6: Show average order revenue</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    ROUND(AVG(quantity * unit_price), 3) AS avg_order_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">4.580</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 7: Show only Coffee orders\"><h3>Practice 7: Show only Coffee orders</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 8: Show total Coffee revenue\"><h3>Practice 8: Show total Coffee revenue</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS coffee_revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>coffee_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 9: Show orders where quantity is greater than 2\"><h3>Practice 9: Show orders where quantity is greater than 2</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE quantity &gt; 2;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 10: Show revenue from June 22 only\"><h3>Practice 10: Show revenue from June 22 only</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue_june_22\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date = &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>revenue_june_22</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>revenue_june_22<br>12.500</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Challenge Question 🧠\"><h3>Challenge Question 🧠</h3><p>Write a query that answers this:</p><p>How much revenue came from Coffee orders<br>between June 20 and June 22?</p><p>Think through the logic first.</p><p>Need table:<br>orders</p><p>Need calculation:<br>SUM(quantity * unit_price)</p><p>Need filters:<br>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;<br>order_date between 2026-06-20 and 2026-06-22</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS coffee_revenue_june_20_to_22\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n  AND order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>coffee_revenue_june_20_to_22</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">22.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><p>coffee_revenue_june_20_to_22<br>22.250</p><p>Visual:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">All orders\n   ↓\nKeep category = Coffee\n   ↓\nKeep date between June 20 and June 22\n   ↓\nCalculate revenue\n   ↓\nAdd it up\n   ↓\n22.250</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Debugging Common Errors 🔧\"><h3>Debugging Common Errors 🔧</h3><p>Error: table already exists</p><p>If you see:</p><p>Table &#x27;orders&#x27; already exists</p><p>That means you already created it.</p><p>Use:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP TABLE IF EXISTS orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><p>before creating it again.</p><p>Error: unknown column</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>MySQL rejects this example</strong></div><p><code>ERROR 1054 (42S22) at line 1: Unknown column &#x27;product&#x27; in &#x27;field list&#x27;</code></p></aside><p>But the column is actually:</p><p>product_name</p><p>Correct:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Error: date written wrong</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE order_date = &#x27;06-22-2026&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Correct:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE order_date = &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Use:</p><p>YYYY-MM-DD<br>Error: forgot quotes around text</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE category = Coffee;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Correct:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Error: using SUM incorrectly</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT quantity * unit_price AS total_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>That gives revenue for each row.</p><p>Correct for total revenue:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Visual:</p><p>quantity * unit_price<br>=<br>row-by-row calculation</p><p>SUM(quantity * unit_price)<br>=<br>add all row calculations together</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 3 Checklist ✅\"><h3>Segment 3 Checklist ✅</h3><p>You should now understand:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>SQL</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Create an orders table</td><td>CREATE TABLE orders (...)</td></tr><tr><td>Store dates</td><td>DATE</td></tr><tr><td>Insert order rows</td><td>INSERT INTO orders ...</td></tr><tr><td>Calculate revenue per row</td><td>quantity * unit_price</td></tr><tr><td>Rename result columns</td><td>AS revenue</td></tr><tr><td>Count rows</td><td>COUNT(*)</td></tr><tr><td>Add numbers</td><td>SUM()</td></tr><tr><td>Average numbers</td><td>AVG()</td></tr><tr><td>Round decimals</td><td>ROUND()</td></tr><tr><td>Filter with multiple conditions</td><td>AND</td></tr><tr><td>Filter either/or conditions</td><td>OR, IN</td></tr><tr><td>Filter date ranges</td><td>BETWEEN</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Show all orders", "Practice 2: Show product name, quantity, and order date", "Practice 3: Show revenue for each order row", "Practice 4: Show total revenue", "Practice 5: Show total items sold", "Practice 6: Show average order revenue", "Practice 7: Show only Coffee orders", "Practice 8: Show total Coffee revenue", "Practice 9: Show orders where quantity is greater than 2", "Practice 10: Show revenue from June 22 only", "Challenge Question 🧠", "Debugging Common Errors 🔧", "Segment 3 Checklist ✅"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 6</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Sales Analysis Lab and Review.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"COUNT(*) counts rows; SUM(quantity) counts units.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What does COUNT(*) measure in orders?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Units</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Order rows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Revenue</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"Each line&#x27;s revenue is its quantity multiplied by its sale price.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>What is row revenue?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">quantity + unit_price</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">quantity * unit_price</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">AVG(unit_price)</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"WHERE controls which detail rows participate in the calculation.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>When does WHERE act?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Before an aggregate reads rows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">After ORDER BY</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Only during INSERT</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Four-day sales snapshot", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 6</p><h2>Four-day sales snapshot</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Employers expect analysts to distinguish transaction rows, units, revenue, and averages before reporting KPIs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>An owner wants a defensible headline summary of the teaching dataset.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Calculate order rows, units, revenue, and average row revenue.</li><li>Calculate Coffee revenue separately.</li><li>State two findings and distinguish rows from units.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Expected totals are 10 rows, 21 units, and 45.800 revenue</li><li>Coffee revenue is 30.500</li><li>Aliases name metrics precisely</li><li>Narrative does not call rows customer orders</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT COUNT(*) AS order_rows, SUM(quantity) AS units_sold,\n       SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue,\n       ROUND(AVG(quantity * unit_price), 3) AS avg_row_revenue\nFROM orders;\n\nSELECT SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS coffee_revenue\nFROM orders WHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>SELECT COUNT(*) AS order_rows, SUM(quantity) AS units_sold, SUM(quant…</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>SELECT SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS coffee_revenue FROM orders WHERE…</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li></ol></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 3, "workflow_number": 6}, {"title": "JOINS", "desc": "Connect products and orders with INNER JOIN and LEFT JOIN reports.", "lessons": [{"title": "Why Relational Questions Need Joins", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Why Relational Questions Need Joins</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Answer “Why Relational Questions Need Joins” in your own words and demonstrate the idea with SQL.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Separate tables reduce repetition but no longer contain the complete answer by themselves. A join reconnects related facts through an explicit matching rule.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Segment 6 — JOINS</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why do we need JOINS?\"><h3>Why do we need JOINS?</h3><p>So far, we have two tables:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">coffee_shop\n│\n├── products\n└── orders</pre><p>The products table tells us what the shop sells:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>The orders table tells us what customers bought:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>2026-06-20</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Right now, the orders table already repeats some product information:</p><p>product_name<br>category<br>unit_price</p><p>That is okay for learning, but in real databases, we usually try not to repeat too much information.</p><p>A JOIN lets us connect tables together.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The main idea\"><h3>The main idea</h3><p>A JOIN answers this kind of question:</p><p>Take rows from one table<br>and match them with rows from another table.</p><p>Visual idea:</p><p>orders table                         products table<br>------------                         --------------<br>Iced Latte        ───────────────▶   Iced Latte<br>Cold Brew         ───────────────▶   Cold Brew<br>Croissant         ───────────────▶   Croissant</p><p>The matching rule is:</p><p>orders.product_name = products.product_name</p><p>That means:</p><p>Match an order row to the product row with the same product name.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Basic JOIN shape\"><h3>Basic JOIN shape</h3><p>The basic structure is:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>table_1</code>, then return <code>columns</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>table_1</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>INNER JOIN</code><strong>table_2</strong><p>Connect rows using table_1.matching_column = table_2.matching_column.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>columns</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    columns\nFROM table_1\nJOIN table_2\nON table_1.matching_column = table_2.matching_column;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>For our database:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    *\nFROM orders\nJOIN products\nON orders.product_name = products.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>This says:</p><p>Start with orders.<br>Join products.<br>Match rows where the product names are equal.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-06-joins.webp\" alt=\"Products and orders connected by matching product identifiers to create combined result rows.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>A JOIN matches related rows. The result can contain selected columns from both connected tables. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "Why do we need JOINS?", "The main idea", "Basic JOIN shape"]}, {"title": "Inner Joins, Qualification, and Aliases", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Inner Joins, Qualification, and Aliases</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain inner joins, qualification, and aliases, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Why Relational Questions Need Joins.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">We begin with a clean INNER JOIN, then make every shared column unambiguous using table names and aliases. The ON condition determines which row pairs can appear.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"First clean JOIN\"><h3>First clean JOIN</h3><p>Instead of selecting everything, let’s choose the columns we actually want.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>orders.order_id, orders.product_name, orders.quantity, orders.unit_price, product…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>INNER JOIN</code><strong>products</strong><p>Connect rows using orders.product_name = products.product_name.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>orders.order_id, orders.product_name, orders.quantity, orders.unit_price, product…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    orders.order_id,\n    orders.product_name,\n    orders.quantity,\n    orders.unit_price,\n    products.product_id,\n    products.price\nFROM orders\nJOIN products\nON orders.product_name = products.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>product_id</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected idea:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>product_id</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>4</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.900</td><td>5</td><td>2.900</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>6</td><td>1.250</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>Croissant</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Notice what happened:</p><p>Each order now has product table information attached to it.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why do we write table names before columns?\"><h3>Why do we write table names before columns?</h3><p>This part matters.</p><p>Both tables have a column called:</p><p>product_name</p><p>Both tables also have:</p><p>category</p><p>So if you write:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name\nFROM orders\nJOIN products\nON orders.product_name = products.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>MySQL rejects this example</strong></div><p><code>ERROR 1052 (23000) at line 1: Column &#x27;product_name&#x27; in field list is ambiguous</code></p></aside><p>MySQL may get confused because it does not know which product_name you mean.</p><p>Do you mean:</p><p>orders.product_name</p><p>or:</p><p>products.product_name</p><p>So we write the table name before the column:</p><p>orders.product_name<br>products.product_name</p><p>This removes confusion.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Table aliases\"><h3>Table aliases</h3><p>Writing full table names gets annoying.</p><p>Instead of this:</p><p>orders.product_name<br>products.product_name</p><p>We can use aliases.</p><p>orders AS o<br>products AS p</p><p>Now:</p><p>o = orders<br>p = products</p><p>Clean version:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.unit_price,\n    p.product_id,\n    p.price\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>product_id</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Same result, but easier to read.</p><p>This is very common in real SQL.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Visual: what the join is doing\"><h3>Visual: what the join is doing</h3><p>Take this order:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>MySQL looks in the products table:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Then it combines them:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That is a join.</p><p>Order information + product information = richer analytics row</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"INNER JOIN\"><h3>INNER JOIN</h3><p>When people say JOIN, they usually mean INNER JOIN.</p><p>These two are the same in MySQL:</p><p>JOIN<br>INNER JOIN</p><p>So this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    p.product_id\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>product_id</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Is the same as this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    p.product_id\nFROM orders AS o\nINNER JOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>product_id</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>What does INNER JOIN mean?</p><p>It only keeps matching rows.</p><p>Keep the order only if it has a matching product.</p><p>Visual:</p><p>orders                         products<br>------                         --------<br>Iced Latte       match         Iced Latte       kept<br>Cold Brew        match         Cold Brew        kept<br>Muffin           no match      —                removed</p><p>In our current data, all order products exist in the products table, so all 10 order rows match.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["First clean JOIN", "Why do we write table names before columns?", "Table aliases", "Visual: what the join is doing", "INNER JOIN"]}, {"title": "Analyzing Matched Rows", "time": 24, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Analyzing Matched Rows</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain analyzing matched rows, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Inner Joins, Qualification, and Aliases.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Once the relationship is correct, joined rows can support product, category, date, and price-comparison reports. We validate the join before trusting its aggregates.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue with a join\"><h3>Revenue with a join</h3><p>Now let’s do analytics using both tables.</p><p>Question<br>Show each order with product ID and revenue.</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>o.order_id, p.product_id, o.product_name, o.quantity, o.unit_price, o.quantity *…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>INNER JOIN</code><strong>products</strong><p>Connect rows using o.product_name = p.product_name.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>o.order_id, p.product_id, o.product_name, o.quantity, o.unit_price, o.quantity *…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>o.order_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    p.product_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.unit_price,\n    o.quantity * o.unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nORDER BY o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td><td>4.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td><td>3.500</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.900</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>4</td><td>1.250</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>2</td><td>3.000</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>1</td><td>1.500</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue by product using JOIN\"><h3>Revenue by product using JOIN</h3><p>This is where Segment 4 and Segment 6 combine.</p><p>Question<br>How much revenue did each product make, including product ID and category?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>4</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This is stronger than grouping the orders table alone because now we can include product details from the products table.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why group by multiple columns?\"><h3>Why group by multiple columns?</h3><p>In the previous query, we used:</p><p>GROUP BY <br>    p.product_id,<br>    p.product_name,<br>    p.category</p><p>Why?</p><p>Because our SELECT has these non-aggregate columns:</p><p>p.product_id<br>p.product_name<br>p.category</p><p>And these aggregate columns:</p><p>SUM(o.quantity)<br>SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price)</p><p>Rule:</p><p>If a column appears in SELECT and is not inside SUM, COUNT, AVG, MIN, or MAX,<br>it usually belongs in GROUP BY.</p><p>Good:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Bad:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY p.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>That may cause errors depending on your MySQL settings.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue by category using product table category\"><h3>Revenue by category using product table category</h3><p>We already have category in orders, but let’s practice using the category from products.</p><p>Question<br>How much revenue did each product category make?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nGROUP BY p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>30.500</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This result matches what we did before, but now the category comes from the products table.</p><p>That is important because in a real business, the product table is often the cleaner “source of truth” for product details.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Best-selling product using JOIN\"><h3>Best-selling product using JOIN</h3><p>Question<br>Which product sold the most units?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category\nORDER BY items_sold DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Answer:</p><p>Iced Latte sold the most units.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Best revenue product using JOIN\"><h3>Best revenue product using JOIN</h3><p>Question<br>Which product made the most revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>16.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Answer:</p><p>Iced Latte made the most revenue.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Orders by day with product details\"><h3>Orders by day with product details</h3><p>Question<br>How much revenue did each day make, using product-matched order rows?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_date,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nGROUP BY o.order_date\nORDER BY o.order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>13.000</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>12.050</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>12.500</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-23</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This gives the same revenue by day as before.</p><p>But now we know every order row was connected to a known product.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Checking for price differences\"><h3>Checking for price differences</h3><p>This is a very useful analyst query.</p><p>The orders table has:</p><p>unit_price</p><p>The products table has:</p><p>price</p><p>In this fixed teaching dataset, these should match. In real sales data they may differ because of discounts or price changes.</p><p>Question<br>Did any order use a different price than the product table price?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    o.unit_price,\n    p.price AS listed_price,\n    o.unit_price - p.price AS price_difference\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nWHERE o.unit_price &lt;&gt; p.price;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>unit_price</th><th>listed_price</th><th>price_difference</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class=\"empty-result\"><td colspan=\"5\">No data rows</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>You should get no rows.</p><p>That means:</p><p>No order price differences were found.</p><p>This is a real data quality check. Very important in analytics. 🔍</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Revenue with a join", "Revenue by product using JOIN", "Why group by multiple columns?", "Revenue by category using product table category", "Best-selling product using JOIN", "Best revenue product using JOIN", "Orders by day with product details", "Checking for price differences"]}, {"title": "Outer Joins and Missing Relationships", "time": 21, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Outer Joins and Missing Relationships</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain outer joins and missing relationships, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Analyzing Matched Rows.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">LEFT JOIN preserves a chosen population even when no match exists. NULL tests and COALESCE then help us distinguish missing relationships from zero activity.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"LEFT JOIN\"><h3>LEFT JOIN</h3><p>Now let’s learn a second type of join.</p><p>An INNER JOIN only keeps matching rows.</p><p>A LEFT JOIN keeps everything from the left table, even if there is no match on the right table.</p><p>Basic shape:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    columns\nFROM left_table\nLEFT JOIN right_table\nON left_table.column = right_table.column;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside><p>Visual:</p><p>LEFT JOIN</p><p>left table                         right table<br>----------                         -----------<br>keep all rows       match if possible</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"LEFT JOIN from orders to products\"><h3>LEFT JOIN from orders to products</h3><p>Question<br>Show every order, even if the product is missing from the products table.</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>o.order_id, o.product_name, o.quantity, p.product_id, p.price</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>LEFT JOIN</code><strong>products</strong><p>Connect rows using o.product_name = p.product_name.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>o.order_id, o.product_name, o.quantity, p.product_id, p.price</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>o.order_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    o.quantity,\n    p.product_id,\n    p.price\nFROM orders AS o\nLEFT JOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nORDER BY o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>product_id</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>In our current data, every order has a matching product, so it will look similar to the inner join.</p><p>But if an order had a product that was missing from the products table, you would see something like:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>product_id</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>11</td><td>Muffin</td><td>2</td><td>NULL</td><td>NULL</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>NULL means:</p><p>No matching value was found.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Finding orders with missing products\"><h3>Finding orders with missing products</h3><p>This is another real analyst data quality check.</p><p>Question<br>Are there any orders for products that do not exist in the products table?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.order_date\nFROM orders AS o\nLEFT JOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nWHERE p.product_id IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class=\"empty-result\"><td colspan=\"4\">No data rows</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>You should get no rows.</p><p>That means:</p><p>Every ordered product exists in the products table.</p><p>Important syntax:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE p.product_id IS NULL</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Do not write:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE p.product_id = NULL</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>For NULL, use:</p><p>IS NULL</p><p>or:</p><p>IS NOT NULL</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"LEFT JOIN from products to orders\"><h3>LEFT JOIN from products to orders</h3><p>Now reverse the direction.</p><p>Question<br>Show every product, even if it has never been ordered.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    o.order_id,\n    o.quantity\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nORDER BY p.product_id, o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>order_id</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>This keeps all rows from products.</p><p>In our current data, every product has been ordered at least once.</p><p>But if the product table had a product like:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>7</td><td>Chai Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.600</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>and nobody ordered it, a LEFT JOIN would show:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>order_id</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>7</td><td>Chai Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>NULL</td><td>NULL</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>That tells you:</p><p>This product exists, but has no orders.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Finding products with no sales\"><h3>Finding products with no sales</h3><p>Question<br>Which products have never been sold?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nWHERE o.order_id IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>Expected result with your current data:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class=\"empty-result\"><td colspan=\"4\">No data rows</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>You should get no rows.</p><p>That means:</p><p>Every product has at least one order.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Product performance report with LEFT JOIN\"><h3>Product performance report with LEFT JOIN</h3><p>Now let’s build a report that would still work even if some products had no sales.</p><p>Question<br>Show every product with total items sold and revenue.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS items_sold,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 0) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2.750</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3.000</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>1.500</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>2.900</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1.250</td><td>4</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1.750</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What is COALESCE()?\"><h3>What is COALESCE()?</h3><p>COALESCE() replaces NULL with another value.</p><p>Example:</p><p>COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0)</p><p>Means:</p><p>If SUM(o.quantity) is NULL, show 0 instead.</p><p>Why does this matter?</p><p>If a product has no orders, then:</p><p>SUM(o.quantity)</p><p>would be:</p><p>NULL</p><p>But for analytics, we usually want:</p><p>0 items sold</p><p>So this:</p><p>COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS items_sold</p><p>is cleaner than showing NULL.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["LEFT JOIN", "LEFT JOIN from orders to products", "Finding orders with missing products", "LEFT JOIN from products to orders", "Finding products with no sales", "Product performance report with LEFT JOIN", "What is COALESCE()?"]}, {"title": "Combining Joins with Grouped Analysis", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Combining Joins with Grouped Analysis</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain combining joins with grouped analysis, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Outer Joins and Missing Relationships.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Real reports combine relationships, grouping, thresholds, and validation. This section develops that pipeline and identifies fragile name-based joins.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Combining JOIN, GROUP BY, and HAVING\"><h3>Combining JOIN, GROUP BY, and HAVING</h3><p>Now let’s use everything together.</p><p>Question<br>Show products that made at least 6.000 in revenue.</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then form one group per <code>p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category</code>, then return <code>p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category, SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS reven…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>INNER JOIN</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Connect rows using p.product_name = o.product_name.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>HAVING</code><strong>revenue &gt;= 6.000</strong><p>Remove completed groups whose aggregate result fails this condition.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category, SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS reven…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>6</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>revenue DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category\nHAVING revenue &gt;= 6.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This query uses:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>SQL part</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>JOIN</td><td>Connect orders to products</td></tr><tr><td>GROUP BY</td><td>Summarize by product</td></tr><tr><td>SUM()</td><td>Calculate revenue</td></tr><tr><td>HAVING</td><td>Keep only products above revenue target</td></tr><tr><td>ORDER BY</td><td>Sort best to worst</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Important real-world note: joining by name is not ideal\"><h3>Important real-world note: joining by name is not ideal</h3><p>Right now we are joining using:</p><p>ON o.product_name = p.product_name</p><p>That works for this beginner dataset.</p><p>But in real databases, joining by names can be risky.</p><p>Why?</p><p>Because names can change or be typed differently.</p><p>Example:</p><p>Iced Latte<br>Iced latte<br>Ice Latte<br>Iced Latte Large</p><p>These may all refer to similar things, but SQL sees them as different text values.</p><p>Better real-world design:</p><p>products table<br>product_id | product_name | category | price</p><p>orders table<br>order_id | product_id | quantity | unit_price | order_date</p><p>Then the join would be:</p><p>ON orders.product_id = products.product_id</p><p>That is much cleaner.</p><p>We will eventually improve the database structure, but for now, using product_name is fine for learning joins.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Mini analyst report\"><h3>Mini analyst report</h3><p>Let’s make a real-looking product performance report.</p><p>Question<br>For each product, show:<br>- product ID<br>- product name<br>- category<br>- order rows<br>- items sold<br>- revenue<br>- average revenue per order row</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    COUNT(o.order_id) AS order_rows,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue,\n    ROUND(AVG(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 3) AS avg_order_revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>3</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td><td>4.500</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>2</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>Tea</td><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Americano</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>4</td><td>5.000</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This is a proper beginner analytics report. 🔥</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common beginner mistakes\"><h3>Common beginner mistakes</h3><p>Mistake 1: forgetting the ON</p><p>Wrong:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    *\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>60 rows returned. The first 12 rows are shown.</p></aside><p>This can create a bad result because MySQL does not know how to match the tables.</p><p>Correct:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    *\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Mistake 2: joining on the wrong column</p><p>Wrong:</p><p>ON o.category = p.category</p><p>Why is this bad?</p><p>Because many products can share the same category.</p><p>Example:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Coffee\n├── Iced Latte\n├── Cold Brew\n└── Americano</pre><p>If you join orders to products by category, one coffee order could match multiple coffee products.</p><p>That creates duplicate rows and wrong totals.</p><p>Correct:</p><p>ON o.product_name = p.product_name</p><p>For our current database.</p><p>Even better in a future design:</p><p>ON o.product_id = p.product_id<br>Mistake 3: not using table aliases</p><p>This works:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    orders.order_id,\n    orders.product_name,\n    products.price\nFROM orders\nJOIN products\nON orders.product_name = products.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>But this is easier to read:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    p.price\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Aliases are your friend.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Combining JOIN, GROUP BY, and HAVING", "Important real-world note: joining by name is not ideal", "Mini analyst report", "Common beginner mistakes"]}, {"title": "Join Lab and Chapter Summary", "time": 18, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 6</p><h2>Join Lab and Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain join lab and chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Combining Joins with Grouped Analysis.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The exercises cover matched rows, unmatched rows, aggregate reports, and price-quality checks. Always write the expected join cardinality before running the query.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Show every order with its product ID.\"><h3>Practice 1: Show every order with its product ID.</h3><p>Try these one at a time.</p><p>Question:</p><p>Show every order with its product ID.</p><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>o.order_id, p.product_id, o.product_name, o.quantity, o.order_date</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>INNER JOIN</code><strong>products</strong><p>Connect rows using o.product_name = p.product_name.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>o.order_id, p.product_id, o.product_name, o.quantity, o.order_date</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>o.order_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    p.product_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.order_date\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nORDER BY o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Show revenue by product using the products table.\"><h3>Practice 2: Show revenue by product using the products table.</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Show revenue by product using the products table.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nGROUP BY \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Show revenue by category using the products table category.\"><h3>Practice 3: Show revenue by category using the products table category.</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Show revenue by category using the products table category.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nGROUP BY p.category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Find products that have never been ordered.\"><h3>Practice 4: Find products that have never been ordered.</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Find products that have never been ordered.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    p.price\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o\nON p.product_name = o.product_name\nWHERE o.order_id IS NULL;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Find orders where the order unit price does not match the product table price.\"><h3>Practice 5: Find orders where the order unit price does not match the product table price.</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Find orders where the order unit price does not match the product table price.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    o.order_id,\n    o.product_name,\n    o.unit_price,\n    p.price AS listed_price,\n    o.unit_price - p.price AS price_difference\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p\nON o.product_name = p.product_name\nWHERE o.unit_price &lt;&gt; p.price;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 6 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 6 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>SQL pattern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Connect two tables</td><td>JOIN ... ON ...</td></tr><tr><td>Match orders to products</td><td>ON o.product_name = p.product_name</td></tr><tr><td>Keep only matching rows</td><td>INNER JOIN</td></tr><tr><td>Keep all rows from the left table</td><td>LEFT JOIN</td></tr><tr><td>Find missing matches</td><td>WHERE right_table.id IS NULL</td></tr><tr><td>Avoid confusing columns</td><td>Use table aliases like o. and p.</td></tr><tr><td>Replace NULL with 0</td><td>COALESCE(value, 0)</td></tr><tr><td>Join + summarize</td><td>JOIN + GROUP BY</td></tr><tr><td>Join + filter groups</td><td>JOIN + GROUP BY + HAVING</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Segment 6 Summary</p><p>You learned that JOINS let tables work together.</p><p>The biggest ideas:</p><p>JOIN connects rows from two tables.</p><p>ON tells MySQL how the tables match.</p><p>INNER JOIN keeps only matching rows.</p><p>LEFT JOIN keeps all rows from the left table.</p><p>Aliases make SQL easier to read.</p><p>JOIN + GROUP BY lets you build real analytics reports.</p><p>You can now answer stronger business questions like:</p><p>Which product ID made the most revenue?<br>Which category made the most money?<br>Are there orders for products missing from the product table?<br>Are there products with no sales?<br>Did any order use the wrong price?</p><p>Next up should be:</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Show every order with its product ID.", "Practice 2: Show revenue by product using the products table.", "Practice 3: Show revenue by category using the products table category.", "Practice 4: Find products that have never been ordered.", "Practice 5: Find orders where the order unit price does not match the product table price.", "Segment 6 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "RIGHT JOIN and readable join direction", "time": 7, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 7</p><h2>RIGHT JOIN and readable join direction</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain right join and readable join direction, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Join Lab and Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">This join pattern extends the chapter model. Read the relationship in words, identify which rows must survive, and then verify the output grain.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"RIGHT JOIN and readable join direction\"><h3>Pattern, example, and interpretation</h3><p>A RIGHT JOIN returns every row from its right table and matching rows from its left table. Unmatched left-side columns become NULL. It is valid MySQL, but teams often rewrite it as a LEFT JOIN so the preserved table appears first.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>p.product_name, o.order_id</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>RIGHT JOIN</code><strong>products</strong><p>Connect rows using p.product_name = o.product_name.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>p.product_name, o.order_id</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>p.product_id, o.order_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>MYSQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT p.product_name, o.order_id\nFROM orders o\nRIGHT JOIN products p\n  ON p.product_name = o.product_name\nORDER BY p.product_id, o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>order_id</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">10</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">8</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">9</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">7</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><div class=\"diagram\">orders (left)  → matching names ←  products (right, all preserved)\nNo matching order means order_id is NULL.</div><p>The equivalent, usually clearer form is <code>FROM products p LEFT JOIN orders o</code> with the same ON condition. Choose direction for readability, not because one keyword is more advanced.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"RIGHT JOIN preserves every row from the table written to its right.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK</span><h3>Which table is preserved in this query?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">orders</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">products</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Neither table</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section></section></div>", "source_titles": ["RIGHT JOIN and readable join direction"]}, {"title": "Self joins for relationships inside one table", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 7 · SECTION 8</p><h2>Self joins for relationships inside one table</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain self joins for relationships inside one table, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: RIGHT JOIN and readable join direction.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">This join pattern extends the chapter model. Read the relationship in words, identify which rows must survive, and then verify the output grain.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Self joins for relationships inside one table\"><h3>Pattern, example, and interpretation</h3><p>A self join is not a separate JOIN keyword. Reference the same table twice with different aliases. A common use is an employee hierarchy where each employee row may point to another employee row as manager.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will first build <code>employees</code> from <code>an earlier result</code>, then read rows from <code>employees</code>, then return <code>e.employee_name AS employee, m.employee_name AS manager</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One row per matching row combination. Confirm the join does not multiply facts unexpectedly.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Columns from both tables appear on one result row only when the ON relationship produces that row. Repeated matches can increase row count.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CTE employees</code><strong>employees</strong><p>Read an earlier result. This intermediate result exists only for this statement.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>employees</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>LEFT JOIN</code><strong>employees</strong><p>Connect rows using m.employee_id = e.manager_id.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>e.employee_name AS employee, m.employee_name AS manager</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>e.employee_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>MYSQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH employees AS (\n  SELECT 1 AS employee_id, 'Maya' AS employee_name, NULL AS manager_id\n  UNION ALL SELECT 2, 'Omar', 1\n  UNION ALL SELECT 3, 'Layla', 1\n)\nSELECT e.employee_name AS employee,\n       m.employee_name AS manager\nFROM employees e\nLEFT JOIN employees m\n  ON m.employee_id = e.manager_id\nORDER BY e.employee_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>employee</th><th>manager</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Maya</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Omar</td><td class=\"\">Maya</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Layla</td><td class=\"\">Maya</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><div class=\"query-visual\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"One employee table used in employee and manager roles\"><div class=\"query-visual-title\"><span>VISUAL WALKTHROUGH</span><strong>One table, two aliases</strong></div><div class=\"query-flow\"><div class=\"flow-step\"><span>1</span><strong>employees e</strong><small>The row being reported</small></div><div class=\"flow-step\"><span>2</span><strong>Match manager_id</strong><small>Connect it to an employee_id</small></div><div class=\"flow-step\"><span>3</span><strong>employees m</strong><small>The matching row in manager role</small></div></div></div><p>Use LEFT JOIN when top-level employees with no manager must remain. Always qualify shared column names with aliases.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"LEFT JOIN preserves Maya even though her manager_id is NULL.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK</span><h3>Why use LEFT JOIN in this hierarchy?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Keep employees without managers</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Remove every NULL</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Create duplicate employees</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Self joins for relationships inside one table"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 7</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Self joins for relationships inside one table.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"INNER JOIN returns only rows satisfying the ON condition.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What does INNER JOIN exclude?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Matched rows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Unmatched rows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Selected columns</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"LEFT JOIN preserves all left rows and supplies NULLs when no match exists.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Which join preserves every left-table row?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">LEFT JOIN</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">INNER JOIN</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">CROSS JOIN</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"ON states how rows from the joined tables correspond.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Where should table relationships be written?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">ON</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">LIMIT</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">AS</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Catalog coverage audit", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 7</p><h2>Catalog coverage audit</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Business facts usually live in multiple tables, so accurate joins and cardinality checks are essential.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>The product manager wants sales totals and visibility for products that never sold.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Start from products and LEFT JOIN orders using the current product_name field.</li><li>Return every product with units and revenue; show zero for missing sales.</li><li>Add a second query that returns only products with no orders, then explain why names are a fragile relationship.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>All products remain in the first result</li><li>Join matches the fields available at this course stage</li><li>COALESCE converts missing totals to zero</li><li>Write-up recommends stable IDs for the later redesign</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name,\n       COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS units_sold,\n       COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 0) AS revenue\nFROM products p\nLEFT JOIN orders o ON o.product_name = p.product_name\nGROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name;\n\nSELECT p.product_id, p.product_name\nFROM products p\nLEFT JOIN orders o ON o.product_name = p.product_name\nWHERE o.order_id IS NULL;\n-- This works for the teaching schema but names can change or collide.\n-- Segment 7 replaces this fragile relationship with product_id.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name, COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS…</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name FROM products p LEFT JOIN orders…</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li><li><strong>3. <code>-- This works for the teaching schema but names can change or collide…</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li></ol></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 6, "workflow_number": 7}, {"title": "GROUP BY", "desc": "Build product, category, and daily performance reports from grouped data.", "lessons": [{"title": "Why Grouping Changes the Question", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 8 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Why Grouping Changes the Question</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Answer “Why Grouping Changes the Question” in your own words and demonstrate the idea with SQL.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>GROUP BY controls report grain: it decides what one summary row represents.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">An aggregate without GROUP BY answers one question about the entire input. GROUP BY divides that input into meaningful buckets so the same calculation can answer one question per product, category, or date.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What problem does GROUP BY solve?\"><h3>What problem does GROUP BY solve?</h3><p>So far, you learned how to answer questions like:</p><p>What is the total revenue?<br>How many items were sold?<br>How many orders exist?</p><p>Those give one big answer.</p><p>Example:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then return <code>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Remove one selected column, predict the new result shape, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><p>total_revenue<br>45.800</p><p>That is useful, but analysts usually need more detail.</p><p>Now we want answers like:</p><p>How much revenue did each product make?<br>How much revenue did each category make?<br>How many items did each product sell?<br>How much revenue happened each day?</p><p>That means we need to split the table into groups.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Visual idea of GROUP BY\"><h3>Visual idea of GROUP BY</h3><p>Think of GROUP BY like sorting receipts into baskets.</p><p>Your orders table has many rows:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Croissant</td><td>Pastry</td><td>3</td><td>1.500</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Brownie</td><td>Dessert</td><td>2</td><td>1.750</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>Coffee</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Without GROUP BY, MySQL sees this as one big pile.</p><pre class=\"diagram\">ALL ORDERS\n│\n├── Iced Latte\n├── Cold Brew\n├── Croissant\n├── Brownie\n├── Iced Latte\n└── ...</pre><p>With GROUP BY product_name, MySQL creates product baskets:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>GROUP BY product_name</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><pre class=\"diagram\">Iced Latte basket\n├── order 1\n├── order 5\n└── order 10\nCold Brew basket\n├── order 2\n└── order 8\nCroissant basket\n├── order 3\n└── order 9</pre><p>Then we can calculate totals inside each basket.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Basic GROUP BY shape\"><h3>Basic GROUP BY shape</h3><p>The basic structure is:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    group_column,\n    aggregate_function(column_or_calculation) AS result_name\nFROM table_name\nGROUP BY group_column;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>30.500</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>3.500</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-04-group-by.webp\" alt=\"Mixed order cards separated into product buckets and summarized into one row per group.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>GROUP BY creates a bucket for each distinct value, and aggregate functions calculate within each bucket. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "What problem does GROUP BY solve?", "Visual idea of GROUP BY", "Basic GROUP BY shape"]}, {"title": "Product and Category Summaries", "time": 18, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 8 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Product and Category Summaries</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain product and category summaries, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>GROUP BY controls report grain: it decides what one summary row represents.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Why Grouping Changes the Question.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">We build grouped reports in small steps: calculate revenue, sort it, keep a leader, and compare monetary performance with unit volume at two business grains.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue by product\"><h3>Revenue by product</h3><p>Analytics question<br>How much money did each product make?</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>product_name</code>, then return <code>product_name, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct product_name value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same product_name value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>product_name</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one product_name value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Americano</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>3.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>What happened?</p><p>MySQL grouped all matching product names together.</p><p>For Iced Latte:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>2</td><td>2.750</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>1</td><td>2.750</td><td>2.750</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>3</td><td>2.750</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Then MySQL adds:</p><p>5.500 + 2.750 + 8.250 = 16.500</p><p>So the final row is:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Sort the result with ORDER BY\"><h3>Sort the result with ORDER BY</h3><p>The previous result works, but it is not sorted by performance.</p><p>As an analyst, you usually want the biggest number first.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now we can answer:</p><p>The highest-revenue product is Iced Latte.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Best revenue product\"><h3>Best revenue product</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which product made the most money?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nORDER BY revenue DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Important idea:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>ORDER BY revenue DESC</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>puts the largest revenue first.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>LIMIT 1</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>keeps only the top row.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Items sold by product\"><h3>Items sold by product</h3><p>Revenue is money.</p><p>But sometimes we want quantity.</p><p>Analytics question<br>How many units of each product were sold?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nORDER BY items_sold DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This tells us:</p><p>Iced Latte sold the most units.</p><p>Notice something interesting:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Product</th><th>Items Sold</th><th>Revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Americano</td><td>4</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Even though Americano sold more units, Matcha Latte made more revenue because it has a higher price.</p><p>That is a very real data analytics insight. 📈</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue by category\"><h3>Revenue by category</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which category makes the most money?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>30.500</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now we can say:</p><p>Coffee is the strongest revenue category.</p><p>That makes sense because the coffee shop has many coffee orders.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Items sold by category\"><h3>Items sold by category</h3><p>Analytics question<br>How many total items were sold in each category?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY items_sold DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">13</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>13</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This tells us:</p><p>Coffee is also the best-selling category by quantity.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Revenue by product", "Sort the result with ORDER BY", "Best revenue product", "Items sold by product", "Revenue by category", "Items sold by category"]}, {"title": "Daily Reports and Multiple Metrics", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 8 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Daily Reports and Multiple Metrics</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain daily reports and multiple metrics, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>GROUP BY controls report grain: it decides what one summary row represents.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Product and Category Summaries.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Time-based grouping turns transactions into a daily series. Several aggregates can be calculated from the same daily bucket when their names and meanings remain distinct.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Orders by day\"><h3>Orders by day</h3><p>Now let’s group by date.</p><p>Analytics question<br>How many order rows happened each day?</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>order_date</code>, then return <code>order_date, COUNT(*) AS order_rows</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct order_date value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same order_date value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>order_date</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>order_date, COUNT(*) AS order_rows</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>order_date</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one order_date value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    COUNT(*) AS order_rows\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-23</td><td>1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Important detail:</p><p>COUNT(*) counts rows.</p><p>It does not count total items sold.</p><p>For example, this row:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>quantity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>7</td><td>Americano</td><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Counts as:</p><p>1 order row</p><p>But:</p><p>4 items sold</p><p>That difference matters a lot.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Items sold by day\"><h3>Items sold by day</h3><p>Analytics question<br>How many total items were sold each day?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">7</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>5</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>7</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-23</td><td>3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now we can see:</p><p>June 22 sold the most items.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Revenue by day\"><h3>Revenue by day</h3><p>Analytics question<br>How much money did the shop make each day?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>13.000</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>12.050</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>12.500</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-23</td><td>8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This tells us:</p><p>June 20 had the highest revenue.</p><p>Even though June 22 sold more items, June 20 made more money.</p><p>That is another great analyst insight:</p><p>Most items sold does not always mean most revenue.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Best revenue day\"><h3>Best revenue day</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which day made the most money?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nORDER BY revenue DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>13.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Answer:</p><p>The best revenue day was June 20, 2026.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Multiple calculations in one grouped query\"><h3>Multiple calculations in one grouped query</h3><p>You can calculate several KPIs per group.</p><p>Analytics question<br>For each product, show items sold, revenue, and average revenue per order row.</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue,\n    ROUND(AVG(quantity * unit_price), 3) AS avg_order_revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td><td>5.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td><td>4.500</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>4</td><td>5.000</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This is starting to look like a real analytics report. 🔥</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Orders by day", "Items sold by day", "Revenue by day", "Best revenue day", "Multiple calculations in one grouped query"]}, {"title": "Controlling Grouped Result Grain", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 8 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Controlling Grouped Result Grain</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain controlling grouped result grain, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>GROUP BY controls report grain: it decides what one summary row represents.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Daily Reports and Multiple Metrics.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Every nonaggregated selected column must be compatible with the grouping grain. We use multiple grouping columns and pre-group filters to construct a reliable analyst report.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Very important GROUP BY rule\"><h3>Very important GROUP BY rule</h3><p>When using GROUP BY, your SELECT section usually contains:</p><p>1. The grouped column<br>2. Aggregate calculations</p><p>Good:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>category</code>, then return <code>category, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct category value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same category value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>category</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>category, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one category value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">13</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Bad:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>MySQL rejects this example</strong></div><p><code>ERROR 1055 (42000) at line 1: Expression #2 of SELECT list is not in GROUP BY clause and contains nonaggregated column &#x27;coffee_shop.orders.product_name&#x27; which is not functionally dependent on columns in GROUP BY clause; this is incompatible with sql_mode=only_full_group_by</code></p></aside><p>Why is that bad?</p><p>Because MySQL is grouping by category, but product_name has many possible values inside each category.</p><p>For example:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">Coffee category\n├── Iced Latte\n├── Cold Brew\n└── Americano</pre><p>So if you group by category, which product_name should MySQL show?</p><p>It is unclear.</p><p>Better version:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category, product_name\nORDER BY category, items_sold DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>Americano</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>Croissant</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now MySQL groups by both:</p><p>category + product_name</p><p>So each result row is more specific.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Grouping by multiple columns\"><h3>Grouping by multiple columns</h3><p>Analytics question<br>How much revenue did each product make inside each category?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category, product_name\nORDER BY category, revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>Americano</td><td>5.000</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>Brownie</td><td>3.500</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>Croissant</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Visual idea:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>GROUP BY category, product_name</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><pre class=\"diagram\">Coffee\n├── Iced Latte\n├── Cold Brew\n└── Americano\nPastry\n└── Croissant\nDessert\n└── Brownie\nTea\n└── Matcha Latte</pre></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"WHERE with GROUP BY\"><h3>WHERE with GROUP BY</h3><p>You can filter rows before grouping.</p><p>Analytics question<br>For coffee products only, how much revenue did each product make?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nGROUP BY product_name\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>5.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Important order:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\nFROM\nWHERE\nGROUP BY\nORDER BY\nLIMIT</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><p>Think of it like this:</p><p>1. FROM       choose table<br>2. WHERE      filter rows<br>3. GROUP BY   create groups<br>4. SELECT     calculate result<br>5. ORDER BY   sort result<br>6. LIMIT      keep top rows</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Mini analyst report query\"><h3>Mini analyst report query</h3><p>Now let’s create a useful report.</p><p>Question<br>Show each category with:<br>- number of order rows<br>- total items sold<br>- total revenue<br>- average revenue per order row</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    COUNT(*) AS order_rows,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue,\n    ROUND(AVG(quantity * unit_price), 3) AS avg_order_revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">13</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td><td class=\"\">5.083</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>6</td><td>13</td><td>30.500</td><td>5.083</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>2</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>5.800</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>3.500</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This is the kind of query a data analyst would use for a dashboard.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Very important GROUP BY rule", "Grouping by multiple columns", "WHERE with GROUP BY", "Mini analyst report query"]}, {"title": "Grouping Lab and Chapter Summary", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 8 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Grouping Lab and Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain grouping lab and chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>GROUP BY controls report grain: it decides what one summary row represents.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Controlling Grouped Result Grain.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The exercises ask you to define the output grain before writing the aggregate. Use the chapter summary only after attempting each report from memory.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Which product sold the most units?\"><h3>Practice 1: Which product sold the most units?</h3><p>Try these one at a time.</p><p>Question:</p><p>Which product sold the most units?</p><p>Hint:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SUM(quantity)\nGROUP BY product_name\nORDER BY items_sold DESC\nLIMIT 1</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>product_name</code>, then return <code>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct product_name value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same product_name value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>product_name</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>items_sold DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>LIMIT</code><strong>1</strong><p>Keep only this many rows after sorting.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one product_name value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nORDER BY items_sold DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Which category had the most order rows?\"><h3>Practice 2: Which category had the most order rows?</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Which category had the most order rows?</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    COUNT(*) AS order_rows\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY order_rows DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>6</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Which day sold the most items?\"><h3>Practice 3: Which day sold the most items?</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Which day sold the most items?</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nORDER BY items_sold DESC\nLIMIT 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">7</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>7</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: How much revenue did each category make between June 20 and June 22?\"><h3>Practice 4: How much revenue did each category make between June 20 and June 22?</h3><p>Question:</p><p>How much revenue did each category make between June 20 and June 22?</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">22.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>22.250</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Dessert</td><td>3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 4 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 4 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>SQL pattern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Revenue by product</td><td>GROUP BY product_name</td></tr><tr><td>Revenue by category</td><td>GROUP BY category</td></tr><tr><td>Items sold by product</td><td>SUM(quantity) GROUP BY product_name</td></tr><tr><td>Orders by day</td><td>COUNT(*) GROUP BY order_date</td></tr><tr><td>Revenue by day</td><td>SUM(quantity * unit_price) GROUP BY order_date</td></tr><tr><td>Best product</td><td>ORDER BY revenue DESC LIMIT 1</td></tr><tr><td>Best day</td><td>ORDER BY revenue DESC LIMIT 1</td></tr><tr><td>Group by two things</td><td>GROUP BY category, product_name</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Segment 4 Summary</p><p>You learned that GROUP BY lets you turn many detailed rows into summarized analytics.</p><p>The biggest ideas:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>GROUP BY creates buckets.\nAggregate functions calculate inside each bucket.\nORDER BY sorts the grouped results.\nLIMIT can find the top result.\nWHERE filters rows before grouping.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>You can now answer real business questions like:</p><p>What is our top product?<br>Which category makes the most money?<br>Which day performed best?<br>Are we selling more coffee or non-coffee items?<br>Which product has high revenue but low quantity?</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Which product sold the most units?", "Practice 2: Which category had the most order rows?", "Practice 3: Which day sold the most items?", "Practice 4: How much revenue did each category make between June 20 and June 22?", "Segment 4 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 8</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>GROUP BY controls report grain: it decides what one summary row represents.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Grouping Lab and Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"Each distinct combination of grouping values becomes one result group.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What determines one output row in a grouped query?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">The GROUP BY values</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">The table name</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">The LIMIT value</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"Revenue combines quantity and price, so its ranking can differ from unit volume.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Can units and revenue rank products differently?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">No</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Yes, because prices differ</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Only with NULL dates</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"ORDER BY sorts the completed result rows.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Which clause sorts grouped results?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">ORDER BY</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">WHERE</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">FROM</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Category performance report", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 8</p><h2>Category performance report</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>GROUP BY controls report grain: it decides what one summary row represents.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>Management needs one row per category for a weekly review.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Return category, order rows, units, and revenue.</li><li>Sort by revenue descending with a stable tie-breaker.</li><li>Identify the revenue leader and explain one difference between volume and revenue.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Grain is one row per category</li><li>All metrics use the correct aggregate</li><li>Sort is deterministic</li><li>Interpretation matches output</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT category, COUNT(*) AS order_rows, SUM(quantity) AS units_sold,\n       SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY revenue DESC, category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th><th>units_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">13</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 4, "workflow_number": 8}, {"title": "HAVING", "desc": "Filter grouped summaries and combine row-level and group-level conditions.", "lessons": [{"title": "Filtering Rows Versus Filtering Groups", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 9 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Filtering Rows Versus Filtering Groups</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain filtering rows versus filtering groups, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>HAVING lets analysts keep only meaningful summary groups without filtering away source rows too early.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">WHERE and HAVING both remove data from a result, but they act at different stages. This section establishes the logical boundary between source-row conditions and aggregate conditions.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What does HAVING do?\"><h3>What does HAVING do?</h3><p>In Segment 4, you learned that GROUP BY creates summary rows.</p><p>Example:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>product_name</code>, then return <code>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct product_name value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same product_name value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>product_name</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one product_name value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Now the question becomes:</p><p>What if I only want products that sold more than 3 items?</p><p>That means we are not filtering the original rows anymore.</p><p>We are filtering the grouped summary results.</p><p>That is what HAVING does.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Simple definition\"><h3>Simple definition</h3><p>WHERE filters rows before grouping.</p><p>HAVING filters groups after grouping.</p><p>Visual idea:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">orders table\n│\n├── WHERE filters raw rows\n│\n├── GROUP BY creates summary groups\n│\n└── HAVING filters those summary groups</pre><p>Think of it like this:</p><p>WHERE = filter individual receipts</p><p>HAVING = filter the final report</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"SQL order with HAVING\"><h3>SQL order with HAVING</h3><p>The structure is:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    group_column,\n    aggregate_function(...) AS result_name\nFROM table_name\nWHERE condition_on_raw_rows\nGROUP BY group_column\nHAVING condition_on_grouped_results\nORDER BY result_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Syntax template—not runnable yet</strong></div><p>Replace the placeholder table, column, expression, and condition names. The completed query then returns the columns and rows requested by those replacements.</p></aside><p>The common order is:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\nFROM\nWHERE\nGROUP BY\nHAVING\nORDER BY\nLIMIT</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside><p>Visually:</p><p>1. FROM       choose the table<br>2. WHERE      filter raw rows<br>3. GROUP BY   create groups<br>4. HAVING     filter grouped results<br>5. SELECT     show columns/calculations<br>6. ORDER BY   sort results<br>7. LIMIT      keep only some rows</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-05-having.webp\" alt=\"Two-stage SQL filtering with WHERE before grouping and HAVING after grouping.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>WHERE removes raw rows before groups are formed. HAVING removes completed summary groups afterward. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "What does HAVING do?", "Simple definition", "SQL order with HAVING"]}, {"title": "Building Aggregate Thresholds", "time": 21, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 9 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Building Aggregate Thresholds</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain building aggregate thresholds, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>HAVING lets analysts keep only meaningful summary groups without filtering away source rows too early.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Filtering Rows Versus Filtering Groups.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Starting with units and revenue, we develop HAVING conditions carefully and examine how boundary choices such as greater-than versus at-least change the answer.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"First HAVING example\"><h3>First HAVING example</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which products sold more than 3 items?</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>product_name</code>, then return <code>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct product_name value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same product_name value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>product_name</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>HAVING</code><strong>items_sold &gt; 3</strong><p>Remove completed groups whose aggregate result fails this condition.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>items_sold DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one product_name value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING items_sold &gt; 3\nORDER BY items_sold DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Why?</p><p>Because these are the only products where:</p><p>SUM(quantity) &gt; 3</p><p>Products removed by HAVING:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>Why removed?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td><td>Not greater than 3</td></tr><tr><td>Brownie</td><td>2</td><td>Not greater than 3</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>2</td><td>Not greater than 3</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why not use WHERE?\"><h3>Why not use WHERE?</h3><p>You might think this would work:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nWHERE SUM(quantity) &gt; 3\nGROUP BY product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result error\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED ERROR</span><strong>MySQL rejects this example</strong></div><p><code>ERROR 1111 (HY000) at line 1: Invalid use of group function</code></p></aside><p>But this is wrong.</p><p>Why?</p><p>Because WHERE happens before the grouping.</p><p>At the WHERE stage, MySQL has not calculated:</p><p>SUM(quantity)</p><p>yet.</p><p>So this is the rule:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Want to filter...</th><th>Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Raw rows</td><td>WHERE</td></tr><tr><td>Grouped totals</td><td>HAVING</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"HAVING with revenue by product\"><h3>HAVING with revenue by product</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which products made more than 5.000 in revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING revenue &gt; 5.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Notice that Americano is not included.</p><p>Americano made exactly:</p><p>5.000</p><p>But the condition is:</p><p>HAVING revenue &gt; 5.000</p><p>That means greater than 5.000, not equal to 5.000.</p><p>To include Americano, you would use:</p><p>HAVING revenue &gt;= 5.000</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Greater than vs greater than or equal to\"><h3>Greater than vs greater than or equal to</h3><p>This detail matters a lot in analytics.</p><p>More than 5<br>HAVING revenue &gt; 5.000</p><p>Means:</p><p>5.001 and above<br>At least 5<br>HAVING revenue &gt;= 5.000</p><p>Means:</p><p>5.000 and above</p><p>Example:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING revenue &gt;= 5.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>5 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Matcha Latte</td><td>5.800</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>5.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"HAVING with revenue by category\"><h3>HAVING with revenue by category</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which categories made more than 5.000 in revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING revenue &gt; 5.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>30.500</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Dessert is removed because it made:</p><p>3.500</p><p>which is not more than 5.000.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"HAVING with orders by day\"><h3>HAVING with orders by day</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which days had more than 2 order rows?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    COUNT(*) AS order_rows\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nHAVING order_rows &gt; 2\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>June 23 is removed because it only had:</p><p>1 order row</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"HAVING with revenue by day\"><h3>HAVING with revenue by day</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Which days made more than 10.000 in revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nHAVING revenue &gt; 10.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>13.000</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>12.500</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>12.050</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>June 23 is removed because it made:</p><p>8.250</p><p>This tells us:</p><p>Three days made more than 10.000 in revenue.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["First HAVING example", "Why not use WHERE?", "HAVING with revenue by product", "Greater than vs greater than or equal to", "HAVING with revenue by category", "HAVING with orders by day", "HAVING with revenue by day"]}, {"title": "Combining WHERE and HAVING", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 9 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Combining WHERE and HAVING</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain combining where and having, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>HAVING lets analysts keep only meaningful summary groups without filtering away source rows too early.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Building Aggregate Thresholds.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Many reports need both a population rule and a performance threshold. We filter the source first, form groups second, and then apply one or more conditions to the calculated summaries.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"WHERE and HAVING together\"><h3>WHERE and HAVING together</h3><p>This is very important.</p><p>You can use both in the same query.</p><p>Analytics question<br>For Coffee products only, which products made more than 8.000 in revenue?</p><p>Here is the logic:</p><p>Step 1: Keep only Coffee rows.<br>Step 2: Group by product.<br>Step 3: Calculate revenue per product.<br>Step 4: Keep only products with revenue greater than 8.000.</p><p>SQL:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then keep rows where <code>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</code>, then form one group per <code>product_name</code>, then return <code>product_name, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct product_name value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same product_name value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>product_name</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>HAVING</code><strong>revenue &gt; 8.000</strong><p>Remove completed groups whose aggregate result fails this condition.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>6</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>revenue DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one product_name value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING revenue &gt; 8.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Americano is removed because its revenue is:</p><p>5.000</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Visual difference: WHERE vs HAVING\"><h3>Visual difference: WHERE vs HAVING</h3><p>Using this query:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING revenue &gt; 8.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The flow looks like this:</p><pre class=\"diagram\">START: all order rows\n│\n├── WHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n│   Keeps only Coffee rows\n│\n├── GROUP BY product_name\n│   Creates product groups\n│\n├── SUM(quantity * unit_price)\n│   Calculates revenue per product\n│\n├── HAVING revenue &gt; 8.000\n│   Keeps only strong revenue products\n│\n└── ORDER BY revenue DESC\n    Sorts highest to lowest</pre><p>That is real analyst thinking. 🔥</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Another WHERE + HAVING example\"><h3>Another WHERE + HAVING example</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Between June 20 and June 22, which categories made more than 5.000 in revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING revenue &gt; 5.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">22.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>22.250</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Dessert is removed because it made only:</p><p>3.500</p><p>inside that date range.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"HAVING with multiple conditions\"><h3>HAVING with multiple conditions</h3><p>You can use AND inside HAVING.</p><p>Analytics question<br>Which products sold more than 2 items AND made more than 5.000 in revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING items_sold &gt; 2\n   AND revenue &gt; 5.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Americano sold 4 items, but made exactly 5.000, so it fails:</p><p>revenue &gt; 5.000</p><p>If you wanted to include Americano, use:</p><p>revenue &gt;= 5.000</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"HAVING with OR\"><h3>HAVING with OR</h3><p>You can also use OR.</p><p>Analytics question<br>Which products sold more than 4 items OR made more than 8.000 in revenue?</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING items_sold &gt; 4\n    OR revenue &gt; 8.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Why?</p><p>Iced Latte passes both:</p><p>items_sold &gt; 4<br>revenue &gt; 8.000</p><p>Cold Brew passes because:</p><p>revenue &gt; 8.000</p><p>Even though it only sold 3 items.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["WHERE and HAVING together", "Visual difference: WHERE vs HAVING", "Another WHERE + HAVING example", "HAVING with multiple conditions", "HAVING with OR"]}, {"title": "Writing and Reviewing HAVING Reports", "time": 9, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 9 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Writing and Reviewing HAVING Reports</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain writing and reviewing having reports, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>HAVING lets analysts keep only meaningful summary groups without filtering away source rows too early.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Combining WHERE and HAVING.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Aliases, clause order, and aggregate placement are common sources of confusion. We correct the failure patterns and assemble a complete grouped report.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common beginner mistake\"><h3>Common beginner mistake</h3><p>Mistake<br>SELECT <br>    category,<br>    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue<br>FROM orders<br>WHERE revenue &gt; 5.000<br>GROUP BY category;</p><p>This is wrong.</p><p>Why?</p><p>Because revenue is created after grouping.</p><p>At the WHERE stage, this does not exist yet:</p><p>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</p><p>Correct version:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>category</code>, then return <code>category, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct category value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same category value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>category</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>HAVING</code><strong>revenue &gt; 5.000</strong><p>Remove completed groups whose aggregate result fails this condition.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>category, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one category value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING revenue &gt; 5.000;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Can HAVING use the alias?\"><h3>Can HAVING use the alias?</h3><p>In MySQL, yes.</p><p>This works:</p><p>HAVING revenue &gt; 5.000</p><p>Because revenue was created here:</p><p>SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue</p><p>Full query:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING revenue &gt; 5.000;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>You may also see people write it like this:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING SUM(quantity * unit_price) &gt; 5.000;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Both are okay in MySQL.</p><p>For learning, I recommend using the alias because it is easier to read:</p><p>HAVING revenue &gt; 5.000</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Mini analyst report with HAVING\"><h3>Mini analyst report with HAVING</h3><p>Analytics question<br>Show categories with at least 2 order rows, including:<br>- order rows<br>- items sold<br>- revenue<br>- average revenue per order row</p><p>SQL:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    COUNT(*) AS order_rows,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue,\n    ROUND(AVG(quantity * unit_price), 3) AS avg_order_revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING order_rows &gt;= 2\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">13</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td><td class=\"\">5.083</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>order_rows</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_order_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>6</td><td>13</td><td>30.500</td><td>5.083</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>2</td><td>4</td><td>6.000</td><td>3.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Tea and Dessert are removed because each only has:</p><p>1 order row</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Common beginner mistake", "Can HAVING use the alias?", "Mini analyst report with HAVING"]}, {"title": "HAVING Lab and Chapter Summary", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 9 · SECTION 5</p><h2>HAVING Lab and Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain having lab and chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>HAVING lets analysts keep only meaningful summary groups without filtering away source rows too early.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Writing and Reviewing HAVING Reports.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">These exercises require you to identify whether each condition belongs before or after grouping. State that reasoning before writing the SQL.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Show products that sold at least 4 items.\"><h3>Practice 1: Show products that sold at least 4 items.</h3><p>Try these one by one.</p><p>Question:</p><p>Show products that sold at least 4 items.</p><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then form one group per <code>product_name</code>, then return <code>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per distinct product_name value.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Rows sharing the same product_name value contribute to the same output row. Changing GROUP BY changes the report grain.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>GROUP BY</code><strong>product_name</strong><p>Create one bucket for each distinct grouping value.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>HAVING</code><strong>items_sold &gt;= 4</strong><p>Remove completed groups whose aggregate result fails this condition.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>items_sold DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Choose one product_name value and reproduce its aggregate manually from the detail rows.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING items_sold &gt;= 4\nORDER BY items_sold DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Show categories that made at least 5.000 in revenue.\"><h3>Practice 2: Show categories that made at least 5.000 in revenue.</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Show categories that made at least 5.000 in revenue.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    category,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING revenue &gt;= 5.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Coffee</td><td>30.500</td></tr><tr><td>Pastry</td><td>6.000</td></tr><tr><td>Tea</td><td>5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Show days where more than 5 items were sold.\"><h3>Practice 3: Show days where more than 5 items were sold.</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Show days where more than 5 items were sold.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nHAVING items_sold &gt; 5\nORDER BY items_sold DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">7</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>7</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>6</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Show Coffee products that sold at least 3 items.\"><h3>Practice 4: Show Coffee products that sold at least 3 items.</h3><p>Question:</p><p>Show Coffee products that sold at least 3 items.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT \n    product_name,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold\nFROM orders\nWHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nGROUP BY product_name\nHAVING items_sold &gt;= 3\nORDER BY items_sold DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>Americano</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 5 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 5 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Filter raw rows</td><td>WHERE</td></tr><tr><td>Filter grouped results</td><td>HAVING</td></tr><tr><td>Products with more than 3 sold</td><td>HAVING SUM(quantity) &gt; 3</td></tr><tr><td>Categories with revenue above 5</td><td>HAVING SUM(quantity * unit_price) &gt; 5</td></tr><tr><td>Days with more than 2 orders</td><td>HAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 2</td></tr><tr><td>Use both row and group filters</td><td>WHERE ... GROUP BY ... HAVING ...</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Segment 5 Summary</p><p>You learned that HAVING is used after GROUP BY.</p><p>The biggest rule:</p><p>WHERE filters before grouping.<br>HAVING filters after grouping.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use WHERE for conditions like:</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>WHERE</code>.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\nWHERE order_date = &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;\nWHERE quantity &gt; 1</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>Use HAVING for conditions like:</p><p>HAVING SUM(quantity) &gt; 3<br>HAVING SUM(quantity * unit_price) &gt; 5.000<br>HAVING COUNT(*) &gt;= 2</p><p>You can now answer business questions like:</p><p>Which products sold enough units to matter?<br>Which categories passed a revenue target?<br>Which days were strong sales days?<br>Which Coffee products performed above a threshold?</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Show products that sold at least 4 items.", "Practice 2: Show categories that made at least 5.000 in revenue.", "Practice 3: Show days where more than 5 items were sold.", "Practice 4: Show Coffee products that sold at least 3 items.", "Segment 5 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 9</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>HAVING lets analysts keep only meaningful summary groups without filtering away source rows too early.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: HAVING Lab and Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"WHERE filters rows before groups are formed.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>Which clause filters detail rows?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">HAVING</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">WHERE</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">ORDER BY</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"HAVING filters completed groups and may use aggregate expressions.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Which clause filters SUM(...) results?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">HAVING</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">FROM</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">LIMIT</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A date condition should remove irrelevant detail rows before grouping.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Where should a date range normally go?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">WHERE</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">HAVING</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">SELECT only</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Meaningful category shortlist", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 9</p><h2>Meaningful category shortlist</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>HAVING lets analysts keep only meaningful summary groups without filtering away source rows too early.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>A campaign can include only categories with enough sales activity.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Summarize units and revenue by category for June 20–22.</li><li>Keep categories with at least 4 units and revenue above 5.</li><li>Explain why each condition belongs in WHERE or HAVING.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Date range is in WHERE</li><li>Aggregate thresholds are in HAVING</li><li>Grouping grain is correct</li><li>Explanation describes logical order</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT category, SUM(quantity) AS units_sold,\n       SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;\nGROUP BY category\nHAVING SUM(quantity) &gt;= 4\n   AND SUM(quantity * unit_price) &gt; 5\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>units_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">22.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 5, "workflow_number": 9}, {"title": "Views & Reporting", "desc": "Package trusted SQL logic into reusable reporting views.", "lessons": [{"title": "Views as Saved Query Interfaces", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 10 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Views as Saved Query Interfaces</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain views as saved query interfaces, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Views package reviewed definitions into stable reporting interfaces that other analysts and dashboards can reuse.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A standard view stores a SELECT definition, not a copy of its result. We create, query, filter, group, and safely replace a reusable reporting interface.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Views save query definitions under stable names. They help analysts reuse trusted logic without copying long joins and calculations into every report.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What is a view?\"><h3>What is a view?</h3><p>A standard view stores a SELECT definition, not a separate copy of its result rows.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to save a SELECT definition for <code>order_details</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE VIEW</code><strong>CREATE VIEW order_details AS SELECT o.order_id, o.order_date, p.product_name, p.category, o.quantit…</strong><p>Save a select definition.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE VIEW order_details AS\nSELECT\n    o.order_id,\n    o.order_date,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.unit_price,\n    o.quantity * o.unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p ON p.product_id = o.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>View definition saved</strong></div><p>No rows are displayed by CREATE VIEW. MySQL saves <code>order_details</code>; querying that view returns the rows produced by its SELECT definition.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Query a view\"><h3>Query a view</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM order_details\nORDER BY order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>order_date</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The view behaves like a table in SELECT queries, while MySQL uses its saved definition to retrieve current underlying data.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Filter and group a view\"><h3>Filter and group a view</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    category,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(revenue) AS revenue\nFROM order_details\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;\nGROUP BY category\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">22.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Views can become a clean reporting layer above normalized tables.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Replace a view definition\"><h3>Replace a view definition</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW order_details AS\nSELECT\n    o.order_id,\n    o.order_date,\n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    o.quantity,\n    o.unit_price,\n    o.quantity * o.unit_price AS revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p ON p.product_id = o.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>View definition saved</strong></div><p>No rows are displayed by CREATE VIEW. MySQL saves <code>order_details</code>; querying that view returns the rows produced by its SELECT definition.</p></aside><p>Replacing a view changes future queries that depend on its columns, so treat its structure as an interface.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-12-views.webp\" alt=\"Products and orders flowing through a saved SQL view into several reusable reports.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>A view saves a query definition so multiple reports can reuse the same trusted logic. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "What is a view?", "Query a view", "Filter and group a view", "Replace a view definition"]}, {"title": "Designing Reporting Views", "time": 21, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 10 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Designing Reporting Views</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain designing reporting views, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Views package reviewed definitions into stable reporting interfaces that other analysts and dashboards can reuse.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Views as Saved Query Interfaces.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Good views have documented grain, stable names, deliberate security exposure, and understood limitations. We build KPI views, layer reports above them, and compare them with CTEs.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Create a KPI view\"><h3>Create a KPI view</h3><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to save a SELECT definition for <code>daily_sales</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE VIEW</code><strong>CREATE VIEW daily_sales AS SELECT order_date, COUNT(*) AS order_rows, SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,…</strong><p>Save a select definition.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE VIEW daily_sales AS\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    COUNT(*) AS order_rows,\n    SUM(quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>View definition saved</strong></div><p>No rows are displayed by CREATE VIEW. MySQL saves <code>daily_sales</code>; querying that view returns the rows produced by its SELECT definition.</p></aside><p>The view stores reusable daily grain.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Build reports from views\"><h3>Build reports from views</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_date,\n    revenue,\n    SUM(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS running_revenue\nFROM daily_sales\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th><th>running_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">25.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">37.550</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>A reporting query can add window calculations above a grouped view.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"View grain and naming\"><h3>View grain and naming</h3><p>Every view should have a documented grain. order_details has one row per order line; daily_sales has one row per date.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    COUNT(*) AS daily_rows,\n    MIN(order_date) AS first_date,\n    MAX(order_date) AS last_date\nFROM daily_sales;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>daily_rows</th><th>first_date</th><th>last_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Views and security\"><h3>Views and security</h3><p>A view can expose approved columns while hiding sensitive columns.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE VIEW product_catalog AS\nSELECT\n    product_id,\n    product_name,\n    category,\n    price\nFROM products;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>View definition saved</strong></div><p>No rows are displayed by CREATE VIEW. MySQL saves <code>product_catalog</code>; querying that view returns the rows produced by its SELECT definition.</p></aside><p>Actual security still requires appropriate database privileges.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"CTE versus view\"><h3>CTE versus view</h3><p>A CTE exists for one statement and is useful for query-specific steps. A view persists as a reusable database object and is useful for shared reporting logic.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH coffee_orders AS (\n    SELECT * FROM order_details WHERE category = &#x27;Coffee&#x27;\n)\nSELECT SUM(revenue) AS coffee_revenue\nFROM coffee_orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>coffee_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"View limitations\"><h3>View limitations</h3><p>Views do not automatically guarantee faster queries, their dependencies must remain compatible, complex views can hide expensive work, and some views are not directly updatable. Use EXPLAIN on queries that read views.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Drop a view safely\"><h3>Drop a view safely</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP VIEW IF EXISTS daily_sales;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><p>Dropping a view removes its saved definition but does not delete rows from the underlying tables.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Create a KPI view", "Build reports from views", "View grain and naming", "Views and security", "CTE versus view", "View limitations", "Drop a view safely"]}, {"title": "Views Lab", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 10 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Views Lab</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain views lab, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Views package reviewed definitions into stable reporting interfaces that other analysts and dashboards can reuse.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Designing Reporting Views.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The exercises create product and category reporting views, then use them for filters and percentage comparisons. Treat each view definition as a contract for downstream users.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Create a product sales view\"><h3>Practice 1: Create a product sales view</h3><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to save a SELECT definition for <code>product_sales</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE VIEW</code><strong>CREATE VIEW product_sales AS SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category, COALESCE(SUM(o.quanti…</strong><p>Save a select definition.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE VIEW product_sales AS\nSELECT\n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name,\n    p.category,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS items_sold,\n    COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 0) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nLEFT JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>View definition saved</strong></div><p>No rows are displayed by CREATE VIEW. MySQL saves <code>product_sales</code>; querying that view returns the rows produced by its SELECT definition.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Query high-revenue products\"><h3>Practice 2: Query high-revenue products</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM product_sales\nWHERE revenue &gt;= 6.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Create a category KPI view\"><h3>Practice 3: Create a category KPI view</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE VIEW category_sales AS\nSELECT\n    p.category,\n    SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.category;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>View definition saved</strong></div><p>No rows are displayed by CREATE VIEW. MySQL saves <code>category_sales</code>; querying that view returns the rows produced by its SELECT definition.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Compare each category with total revenue\"><h3>Practice 4: Compare each category with total revenue</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    category,\n    revenue,\n    ROUND(100 * revenue / SUM(revenue) OVER (), 2) AS revenue_percent\nFROM category_sales\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>revenue</th><th>revenue_percent</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td><td class=\"\">66.59</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">13.10</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">12.66</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">7.64</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Create a product sales view", "Practice 2: Query high-revenue products", "Practice 3: Create a category KPI view", "Practice 4: Compare each category with total revenue"]}, {"title": "Chapter Summary", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 10 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Views package reviewed definitions into stable reporting interfaces that other analysts and dashboards can reuse.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Views Lab.</p></div></section><section class=\"concept-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">BUILD THE MENTAL MODEL</p><div><span>CORE IDEA</span><p>A view is a saved query interface. It centralizes reviewed logic but normally stores no separate copy of the rows.</p></div><div><span>CONCRETE EXAMPLE</span><p>order_details can expose a trusted join and revenue definition that multiple reports query consistently.</p></div><div><span>EXPLAIN IT BACK</span><p>What is the view&#x27;s row grain, and which reports depend on its columns?</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Use the summary to decide when logic belongs in a one-query CTE, a reusable view, or the consuming report itself.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 12 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 12 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Statement</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Create reusable query</td><td>CREATE VIEW name AS SELECT ...</td></tr><tr><td>Change a view</td><td>CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW</td></tr><tr><td>Read a view</td><td>SELECT ... FROM view_name</td></tr><tr><td>Remove a view</td><td>DROP VIEW IF EXISTS</td></tr><tr><td>One-query intermediate result</td><td>WITH ... AS (...)</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Segment 12 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 10</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Views package reviewed definitions into stable reporting interfaces that other analysts and dashboards can reuse.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A normal MySQL view saves query logic, not a separate result copy.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>Does a standard view store its result rows?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Usually no; it stores a query definition</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Always</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Only after ORDER BY</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"Intentional columns make the view easier and safer for downstream consumers.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Why list view columns deliberately?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">To provide a stable reporting interface</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">To hide every row</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">To create foreign keys</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A view is an interface; changes can break or alter downstream reports.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>What should be checked after changing a view?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Dependent reports and results</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Only the font</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Nothing</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Trusted sales reporting view", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 10</p><h2>Trusted sales reporting view</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Views package reviewed definitions into stable reporting interfaces that other analysts and dashboards can reuse.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>Two reports need the same product-level sales logic without duplicating joins and calculations.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Create a view with product identity, category, units, and revenue.</li><li>Query the view for category totals and top products.</li><li>Document grain, definitions, NULL behavior, and one limitation.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>View has one documented row per product</li><li>Join and aggregation are correct</li><li>Downstream queries reuse the view</li><li>Documentation states dependencies and limitations</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW product_sales_v AS\nSELECT p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category,\n       COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity), 0) AS units_sold,\n       COALESCE(SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price), 0) AS revenue\nFROM products p LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category;\n\nSELECT category, SUM(revenue) AS revenue\nFROM product_sales_v GROUP BY category ORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW product_sales_v AS SELECT p.product_id, p.prod…</code></strong><span>MySQL reports success or an affected-row count; the statement itself returns no analysis grid.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>SELECT category, SUM(revenue) AS revenue FROM product_sales_v GROUP B…</code></strong><span>Returns the verification or analysis rows requested by this SELECT. Compare its row count and values with the stated project criteria.</span></li></ol></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 12, "workflow_number": 10}, {"title": "Subqueries & CTEs", "desc": "Build readable multi-step analyses with nested queries and named intermediate results.", "lessons": [{"title": "Thinking in Intermediate Results", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 11 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Thinking in Intermediate Results</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain thinking in intermediate results, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Complex SQL becomes understandable when each step has a clear grain and purpose. We begin with nested queries that produce one value for an outer comparison.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Complex analysis often needs more than one logical step. In this segment, you will learn how to use the result of one query inside another query without creating temporary tables manually.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why intermediate results matter\"><h3>Why intermediate results matter</h3><p>Suppose the business asks:</p><p>Which products earned more revenue than the average product?</p><p>You must first calculate revenue by product, then calculate the average of those product totals, and finally compare each product with that average. Subqueries and common table expressions let SQL express those steps clearly.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"What is a subquery?\"><h3>What is a subquery?</h3><p>A subquery is a query nested inside another SQL statement.</p><p>The inner query runs to produce a value or set of rows. The outer query uses that result.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then calculate the nested query first and use its answer in the outer query, then keep rows where <code>price &gt; ( SELECT AVG(price) FROM products )</code>, then return <code>product_name, price</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>price &gt; ( SELECT AVG(price) FROM products )</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, price</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_name, price\nFROM products\nWHERE price &gt; (\n    SELECT AVG(price)\n    FROM products\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The inner query returns the average menu price. The outer query returns products priced above it.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Scalar subqueries\"><h3>Scalar subqueries</h3><p>A scalar subquery must return exactly one value. Aggregate functions without GROUP BY are commonly used because they return one row.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    price,\n    (SELECT ROUND(AVG(price), 3) FROM products) AS average_menu_price\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th><th>average_menu_price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The average is repeated beside each product so every row can be compared with the benchmark.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-08-ctes.webp\" alt=\"Orders flowing through product sales and average sales CTE stages into an above-average result.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>CTEs give names to intermediate query results, making multi-step analysis easier to read and verify. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "Why intermediate results matter", "What is a subquery?", "Scalar subqueries"]}, {"title": "Membership, Existence, and Correlation", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 11 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Membership, Existence, and Correlation</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain membership, existence, and correlation, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Thinking in Intermediate Results.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">IN, EXISTS, NOT EXISTS, correlated subqueries, and derived tables solve different relationship problems. We compare what each inner query returns and how the outer query consumes it.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Subqueries with IN\"><h3>Subqueries with IN</h3><p>IN accepts a list of values, so its subquery may return several rows.</p><p>Question: Which products have appeared in orders?</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then calculate the nested query first and use its answer in the outer query, then keep rows where <code>product_id IN ( SELECT product_id FROM orders )</code>, then return <code>product_id, product_name</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>product_id IN ( SELECT product_id FROM orders )</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_id, product_name</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>product_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT product_id, product_name\nFROM products\nWHERE product_id IN (\n    SELECT product_id\n    FROM orders\n)\nORDER BY product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>DISTINCT is optional inside this subquery because IN only tests membership.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"EXISTS\"><h3>EXISTS</h3><p>EXISTS checks whether the subquery finds at least one matching row.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name\nFROM products AS p\nWHERE EXISTS (\n    SELECT 1\n    FROM orders AS o\n    WHERE o.product_id = p.product_id\n)\nORDER BY p.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_id</th><th>product_name</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT 1 is conventional: EXISTS only cares whether a row exists, not which columns it contains.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"NOT EXISTS\"><h3>NOT EXISTS</h3><p>NOT EXISTS is a safe way to find missing relationships.</p><p>Question: Which products have never sold?</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name\nFROM products AS p\nWHERE NOT EXISTS (\n    SELECT 1\n    FROM orders AS o\n    WHERE o.product_id = p.product_id\n)\nORDER BY p.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>With the original six products, this returns no data rows because every product has at least one sale.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Correlated subqueries\"><h3>Correlated subqueries</h3><p>A correlated subquery refers to the current row of the outer query. It runs logically once for each outer row.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    p.product_name,\n    p.price\nFROM products AS p\nWHERE p.price &gt; (\n    SELECT AVG(p2.price)\n    FROM products AS p2\n    WHERE p2.category = p.category\n)\nORDER BY p.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>This finds products priced above the average price of their own category. Correlated subqueries are useful, but a join or CTE can sometimes be easier to read and faster to optimize.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Derived tables in FROM\"><h3>Derived tables in FROM</h3><p>A subquery in FROM behaves like a temporary result table and must have an alias.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_sales.product_name,\n    product_sales.revenue\nFROM (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n) AS product_sales\nWHERE product_sales.revenue &gt; 5.000\nORDER BY product_sales.revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The outer query can filter the aggregate result without using HAVING because the derived table already contains detail rows representing products.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Subqueries with IN", "EXISTS", "NOT EXISTS", "Correlated subqueries", "Derived tables in FROM"]}, {"title": "Common Table Expressions", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 11 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Common Table Expressions</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain common table expressions, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Membership, Existence, and Correlation.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">A CTE names an intermediate result for the duration of one statement. We build single and multiple CTE pipelines, then use a one-row CROSS JOIN to supply a benchmark.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Introduction to CTEs\"><h3>Introduction to CTEs</h3><p>CTE means common table expression. A CTE gives a name to a query result for the duration of one statement.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will first build <code>product_sales</code> from <code>products</code> at one row per <code>p.product_id, p.product_name</code>, then read rows from <code>product_sales</code>, then return <code>product_name, revenue</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>SELECT creates a temporary result for analysis. It does not change the source table.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CTE product_sales</code><strong>product_sales</strong><p>Read products, create one row per p.product_id, p.product_name, and calculate SUM. This intermediate result exists only for this statement.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>product_sales</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, revenue</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>revenue DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Switch ASC and DESC, then predict the first row before running the query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_id,\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n)\nSELECT product_name, revenue\nFROM product_sales\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The WITH clause comes before the main SELECT.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Filtering a CTE\"><h3>Filtering a CTE</h3><p>Separating calculation from filtering makes multi-step logic easier to audit.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_id,\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n)\nSELECT product_name, revenue\nFROM product_sales\nWHERE revenue &gt;= 6.000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td></tr><tr><td>Croissant</td><td>6.000</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Multiple CTEs\"><h3>Multiple CTEs</h3><p>Separate CTEs can represent separate analytical steps. Separate them with commas and write WITH only once.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        product_id,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY product_id\n),\naverage_sales AS (\n    SELECT AVG(revenue) AS average_product_revenue\n    FROM product_sales\n)\nSELECT\n    p.product_name,\n    ps.revenue,\n    ROUND(a.average_product_revenue, 3) AS average_product_revenue\nFROM product_sales AS ps\nJOIN products AS p ON p.product_id = ps.product_id\nCROSS JOIN average_sales AS a\nWHERE ps.revenue &gt; a.average_product_revenue\nORDER BY ps.revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>average_product_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">7.633</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">7.633</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>average_product_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>16.500</td><td>7.633</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>9.000</td><td>7.633</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why CROSS JOIN works here\"><h3>Why CROSS JOIN works here</h3><p>average_sales contains exactly one row. CROSS JOIN attaches that single benchmark row to every product_sales row.</p><p>If the benchmark CTE returned several rows, a CROSS JOIN would multiply the results. Always verify the grain and expected row count of every CTE before joining it.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"CTEs do not store data\"><h3>CTEs do not store data</h3><p>A CTE exists only while its statement runs. It does not create a permanent table and cannot be queried by a later statement.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n)\nSELECT *\nFROM daily_sales;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Running SELECT * FROM daily_sales; afterward will fail because the CTE is out of scope.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Introduction to CTEs", "Filtering a CTE", "Multiple CTEs", "Why CROSS JOIN works here", "CTEs do not store data"]}, {"title": "Choosing and Validating a Multi-Step Pattern", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 11 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Choosing and Validating a Multi-Step Pattern</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain choosing and validating a multi-step pattern, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Common Table Expressions.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Readable syntax is not enough: NULL behavior, repeated evaluation, untested grain, and unsupported findings can still produce incorrect results. We establish criteria for choosing, debugging, and communicating each pattern.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Subquery or CTE?\"><h3>Subquery or CTE?</h3><p>Use a scalar subquery for one short benchmark. Use EXISTS for relationship checks. Use a CTE when the intermediate result needs a clear name, multiple logical steps, or easier debugging.</p><p>Neither form is automatically faster. MySQL&#x27;s optimizer and the actual execution plan determine performance. Start with correct, readable SQL and measure when performance matters.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"NULL and NOT IN\"><h3>NULL and NOT IN</h3><p>NOT IN can produce surprising results if its subquery contains NULL. A comparison with NULL is unknown rather than true or false.</p><p>For missing-relationship checks, prefer NOT EXISTS:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then calculate the nested query first and use its answer in the outer query, then keep rows where <code>NOT EXISTS ( SELECT 1 FROM orders AS o WHERE o.product_id = p.product_id )</code>, then return <code>p.product_id, p.product_name</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>NOT EXISTS ( SELECT 1 FROM orders AS o WHERE o.product_id = p.product_id )</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>p.product_id, p.product_name</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name\nFROM products AS p\nWHERE NOT EXISTS (\n    SELECT 1\n    FROM orders AS o\n    WHERE o.product_id = p.product_id\n);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside><p>This expresses the business question directly and handles NULL behavior safely.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Final analyst report\"><h3>Final analyst report</h3><p>Question: Which products produced above-average revenue, and how far above average were they?</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_id,\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity) AS items_sold,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n),\nbenchmark AS (\n    SELECT AVG(revenue) AS avg_revenue\n    FROM product_sales\n)\nSELECT\n    ps.product_name,\n    ps.items_sold,\n    ps.revenue,\n    ROUND(ps.revenue - b.avg_revenue, 3) AS amount_above_average\nFROM product_sales AS ps\nCROSS JOIN benchmark AS b\nWHERE ps.revenue &gt; b.avg_revenue\nORDER BY ps.revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>amount_above_average</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">8.867</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">1.367</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>items_sold</th><th>revenue</th><th>amount_above_average</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Iced Latte</td><td>6</td><td>16.500</td><td>8.867</td></tr><tr><td>Cold Brew</td><td>3</td><td>9.000</td><td>1.367</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Writing findings and recommendations\"><h3>Writing findings and recommendations</h3><p>An analyst report is not only SQL output. It turns verified query results into a short decision-ready explanation.</p><p>Use this structure:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Section</th><th>What to write</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Business question</td><td>What the stakeholder asked</td></tr><tr><td>Data used</td><td>Tables or views queried</td></tr><tr><td>Key definitions</td><td>Grain, filters, metric formulas, and time period</td></tr><tr><td>Quality notes</td><td>Known data issues and how you handled them</td></tr><tr><td>Main findings</td><td>The strongest result-backed observations</td></tr><tr><td>Recommendation</td><td>One action supported by the evidence</td></tr><tr><td>Limitations</td><td>What should be confirmed before production use</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Good findings are specific and tied to query evidence. Avoid vague statements such as &quot;sales changed.&quot; Prefer &quot;June revenue was lower than May because completed orders fell while revenue per order stayed stable,&quot; then cite the query result that proves it.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common mistakes\"><h3>Common mistakes</h3><p>Common errors include returning several rows from a scalar subquery, forgetting an alias for a derived table, referencing a CTE after its statement ends, using NOT IN without considering NULL, and losing track of the grain of an intermediate result.</p><p>Debug complex SQL one layer at a time. Run each inner query or CTE independently and verify its columns, row count, and grain before adding the next step.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Subquery or CTE?", "NULL and NOT IN", "Final analyst report", "Writing findings and recommendations", "Common mistakes"]}, {"title": "Subquery and CTE Lab", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 11 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Subquery and CTE Lab</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain subquery and cte lab, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Choosing and Validating a Multi-Step Pattern.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The exercises progress from scalar benchmarks to absence tests and share-of-total calculations. Run each intermediate result independently before composing the final statement.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Products above average price\"><h3>Practice 1: Products above average price</h3><p>Find products priced above the overall average menu price. Return product_name, price, and the average price benchmark.</p><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>products</code>, then calculate the nested query first and use its answer in the outer query, then keep rows where <code>price &gt; ( SELECT AVG(price) FROM products )</code>, then return <code>product_name, price, ROUND((SELECT AVG(price)</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One summary row because the query aggregates without GROUP BY.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>products</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>price &gt; ( SELECT AVG(price) FROM products )</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, price, ROUND((SELECT AVG(price)</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>price DESC, product_name</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    price,\n    ROUND((SELECT AVG(price) FROM products), 3) AS average_menu_price\nFROM products\nWHERE price &gt; (\n    SELECT AVG(price)\n    FROM products\n)\nORDER BY price DESC, product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th><th>average_menu_price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2.192</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Products with no orders\"><h3>Practice 2: Products with no orders</h3><p>Find products with no matching orders using NOT EXISTS. Return product_id and product_name.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    p.product_id,\n    p.product_name\nFROM products AS p\nWHERE NOT EXISTS (\n    SELECT 1\n    FROM orders AS o\n    WHERE o.product_id = p.product_id\n)\nORDER BY p.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Statement completes without a result grid</strong></div><p>MySQL returns no columns or data rows.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Days above average revenue\"><h3>Practice 3: Days above average revenue</h3><p>Build a daily_sales CTE and return only days whose revenue is above average daily revenue.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n),\naverage_daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT AVG(daily_revenue) AS average_daily_revenue\n    FROM daily_sales\n)\nSELECT\n    ds.order_date,\n    ds.daily_revenue,\n    ROUND(a.average_daily_revenue, 3) AS average_daily_revenue\nFROM daily_sales AS ds\nCROSS JOIN average_daily_sales AS a\nWHERE ds.daily_revenue &gt; a.average_daily_revenue\nORDER BY ds.daily_revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>average_daily_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">11.450</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">11.450</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">11.450</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Product share of category revenue\"><h3>Practice 4: Product share of category revenue</h3><p>Build product_sales and category_sales CTEs. Return each product&#x27;s revenue, its category revenue, and the product&#x27;s percentage of category revenue.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_id,\n        p.product_name,\n        p.category,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS product_revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o\n        ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category\n),\ncategory_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        category,\n        SUM(product_revenue) AS category_revenue\n    FROM product_sales\n    GROUP BY category\n)\nSELECT\n    ps.product_name,\n    ps.category,\n    ps.product_revenue,\n    cs.category_revenue,\n    ROUND(100 * ps.product_revenue / cs.category_revenue, 2) AS category_revenue_percent\nFROM product_sales AS ps\nJOIN category_sales AS cs\n    ON cs.category = ps.category\nORDER BY ps.category, ps.product_revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>category</th><th>product_revenue</th><th>category_revenue</th><th>category_revenue_percent</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td><td class=\"\">54.10</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td><td class=\"\">29.51</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td><td class=\"\">16.39</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Products above average price", "Practice 2: Products with no orders", "Practice 3: Days above average revenue", "Practice 4: Product share of category revenue"]}, {"title": "Chapter Summary", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 11 · SECTION 6</p><h2>Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Subquery and CTE Lab.</p></div></section><section class=\"concept-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">BUILD THE MENTAL MODEL</p><div><span>CORE IDEA</span><p>Complex analysis becomes reliable when it is separated into named, testable intermediate results.</p></div><div><span>CONCRETE EXAMPLE</span><p>A product_sales CTE can calculate one row per product; a later step can compare those rows with their average.</p></div><div><span>EXPLAIN IT BACK</span><p>Can you run and validate each intermediate step before combining them?</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Use this summary to compare the shape produced by scalar subqueries, IN, EXISTS, derived tables, and CTEs before moving to window functions.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 8 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 8 cheat sheet</h3><p>Core patterns:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Pattern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>One benchmark value</td><td>Scalar subquery</td></tr><tr><td>Test whether matches exist</td><td>EXISTS</td></tr><tr><td>Find missing matches</td><td>NOT EXISTS</td></tr><tr><td>Name an intermediate result</td><td>WITH ... AS (...)</td></tr><tr><td>Use several stages</td><td>Multiple comma-separated CTEs</td></tr><tr><td>Inspect a nested result</td><td>Run the inner query independently</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Segment 8 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 11</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A scalar subquery must produce a single value where one value is expected.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What can a scalar subquery return?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">One value</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Any number of columns and rows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Only table names</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"EXISTS answers a yes/no matching question and can stop at the first match.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>When is EXISTS useful?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Testing whether a match exists</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Renaming a column</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Sorting output</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A CTE makes multi-step query logic readable and independently testable.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Why use a CTE?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">To name and test an intermediate result</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">To permanently store rows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">To create a password</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Above-benchmark products", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 11</p><h2>Above-benchmark products</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Subqueries and CTEs make multi-step business logic testable, readable, and easier for teammates to review.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>A manager wants products whose revenue exceeds average product revenue.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Build product revenue in a CTE.</li><li>Calculate the benchmark from that result.</li><li>Return products above it with their revenue and the benchmark.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Aggregation occurs before the benchmark</li><li>Benchmark is calculated from product totals</li><li>Final result has one row per qualifying product</li><li>CTE names communicate purpose</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n  SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name,\n         SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n  FROM products p JOIN orders o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n  GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n), benchmark AS (\n  SELECT AVG(revenue) AS avg_product_revenue FROM product_sales\n)\nSELECT ps.product_name, ps.revenue, b.avg_product_revenue\nFROM product_sales ps CROSS JOIN benchmark b\nWHERE ps.revenue &gt; b.avg_product_revenue\nORDER BY ps.revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>avg_product_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">7.6333333</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">7.6333333</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 8, "workflow_number": 11}, {"title": "Window Functions", "desc": "Create rankings, running totals, period comparisons, and analytical windows.", "lessons": [{"title": "Analytical Windows and Preserved Detail", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 12 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Analytical Windows and Preserved Detail</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain analytical windows and preserved detail, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Window functions calculate across related rows without replacing them with one grouped row. OVER and PARTITION BY establish the set of rows available to each calculation.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Window functions calculate across related rows without collapsing them into one row per group. They are essential for rankings, running totals, period comparisons, and analytical reports.</p><p>These lessons require MySQL 8.0 or newer. Earlier MySQL versions do not support window functions or CTEs.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Why window functions matter\"><h3>Why window functions matter</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>GROUP BY reduces many detail rows into summary rows. Sometimes you need a summary and still need to keep each row.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><p>A window function looks across a defined set of rows while preserving the current result&#x27;s grain.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The OVER clause\"><h3>The OVER clause</h3><p>OVER turns a supported aggregate or ranking function into a window function.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then attach a window calculation without collapsing the result rows, then return <code>order_id, order_date, quantity * unit_price AS row_revenue, SUM(quantity * unit_p…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>The final source-row grain is preserved; the window value is attached as another column.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The window calculation adds analytical context while leaving the underlying result rows visible.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>OVER</code><strong></strong><p>Define which related rows the window function may inspect and in what order.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>order_id, order_date, quantity * unit_price AS row_revenue, SUM(quantity * unit_p…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>order_id</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Reverse or change the window order and predict which comparison or running value changes first.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_id,\n    order_date,\n    quantity * unit_price AS row_revenue,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) OVER () AS total_revenue\nFROM orders\nORDER BY order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>order_date</th><th>row_revenue</th><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>OVER () means the window contains every result row. The output still has one row per order line.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"GROUP BY versus window functions\"><h3>GROUP BY versus window functions</h3><p>This grouped query returns one row:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS total_revenue\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>total_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>The window query returns every order row plus the same 45.800 total beside each row.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>Use GROUP BY when you want one result row per group. Use a window function when you need calculations across rows without losing row-level detail.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Active database selected</strong></div><p>No result grid is returned. Later unqualified table names resolve inside <code>GROUP</code>.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"PARTITION BY\"><h3>PARTITION BY</h3><p>PARTITION BY creates independent windows.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    o.order_id,\n    p.category,\n    o.quantity * o.unit_price AS row_revenue,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) OVER (\n        PARTITION BY p.category\n    ) AS category_revenue\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p ON p.product_id = o.product_id\nORDER BY p.category, o.order_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>category</th><th>row_revenue</th><th>category_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">5.500</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">30.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">4.500</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Every Coffee row displays 30.500, while rows from other categories use their own category totals.</p></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-09-windows.webp\" alt=\"A window moving across dated rows while calculating running totals, ranks, and previous values.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>Window functions calculate across related rows while keeping the individual result rows visible. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "Why window functions matter", "The OVER clause", "GROUP BY versus window functions", "PARTITION BY"]}, {"title": "Running Totals and Rankings", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 12 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Running Totals and Rankings</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain running totals and rankings, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Analytical Windows and Preserved Detail.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Ordering inside a window gives rows analytical position. We develop running totals and three ranking functions, then use a CTE to filter a top-N-per-group result.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Running totals\"><h3>Running totals</h3><p>An ordered window can accumulate values over time.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will first build <code>daily_sales</code> from <code>orders</code> at one row per <code>order_date</code>, then read rows from <code>daily_sales</code>, then attach a window calculation without collapsing the result rows, then return <code>order_date, daily_revenue, SUM(daily_revenue) OVER ( ORDER BY order_date ROWS BET…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>The final source-row grain is preserved; the window value is attached as another column.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The window calculation adds analytical context while leaving the underlying result rows visible.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CTE daily_sales</code><strong>daily_sales</strong><p>Read orders, create one row per order_date, and calculate SUM. This intermediate result exists only for this statement.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>daily_sales</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>OVER</code><strong>ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW</strong><p>Define which related rows the window function may inspect and in what order.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>order_date, daily_revenue, SUM(daily_revenue) OVER ( ORDER BY order_date ROWS BET…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>order_date</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Reverse or change the window order and predict which comparison or running value changes first.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n)\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    daily_revenue,\n    SUM(daily_revenue) OVER (\n        ORDER BY order_date\n        ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW\n    ) AS running_revenue\nFROM daily_sales\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>running_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">25.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">37.550</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>running_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>13.000</td><td>13.000</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>12.050</td><td>25.050</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>12.500</td><td>37.550</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-23</td><td>8.250</td><td>45.800</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"ROW_NUMBER\"><h3>ROW_NUMBER</h3><p>ROW_NUMBER assigns a unique sequence based on the window order.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n)\nSELECT\n    product_name,\n    revenue,\n    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY revenue DESC) AS revenue_position\nFROM product_sales\nORDER BY revenue_position;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>revenue_position</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Add a stable tiebreaker such as product_name when deterministic ordering matters.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"RANK and DENSE_RANK\"><h3>RANK and DENSE_RANK</h3><p>RANK gives tied values the same rank and leaves gaps afterward. DENSE_RANK gives ties the same rank without gaps.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    price,\n    RANK() OVER (ORDER BY price DESC) AS price_rank,\n    DENSE_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY price DESC) AS dense_price_rank\nFROM products\nORDER BY price DESC, product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th><th>price_rank</th><th>dense_price_rank</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>ROW_NUMBER never ties. Choose the ranking function that matches the business meaning.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Ranking inside groups\"><h3>Ranking inside groups</h3><p>PARTITION BY restarts ranking for each category.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    category,\n    product_name,\n    price,\n    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (\n        PARTITION BY category\n        ORDER BY price DESC, product_id\n    ) AS category_price_position\nFROM products\nORDER BY category, category_price_position;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>price</th><th>category_price_position</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Each category begins again at position 1.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Top N per group\"><h3>Top N per group</h3><p>Window aliases cannot be filtered in the same SELECT&#x27;s WHERE clause because WHERE is evaluated before the window calculation. Put the ranking in a CTE, then filter it.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH ranked_products AS (\n    SELECT\n        category,\n        product_name,\n        price,\n        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (\n            PARTITION BY category\n            ORDER BY price DESC, product_id\n        ) AS category_position\n    FROM products\n)\nSELECT category, product_name, price\nFROM ranked_products\nWHERE category_position &lt;= 2\nORDER BY category, category_position;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>5 rows returned.</p></aside><p>This is the standard top-N-per-group pattern.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Running totals", "ROW_NUMBER", "RANK and DENSE_RANK", "Ranking inside groups", "Top N per group"]}, {"title": "Comparing Rows Across Time and Peers", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 12 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Comparing Rows Across Time and Peers</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain comparing rows across time and peers, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Running Totals and Rankings.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">LAG, LEAD, moving frames, and aggregate peer windows turn a daily series or peer group into comparisons. The partition, order, and frame determine which values participate.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"LAG\"><h3>LAG</h3><p>LAG reads a value from a previous row in the window order.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will first build <code>daily_sales</code> from <code>orders</code> at one row per <code>order_date</code>, then read rows from <code>daily_sales</code>, then attach a window calculation without collapsing the result rows, then return <code>order_date, daily_revenue, LAG(daily_revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS previ…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>The final source-row grain is preserved; the window value is attached as another column.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Each previous-value column comes from the row immediately before it in the window order. The first row is NULL because no earlier row exists.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CTE daily_sales</code><strong>daily_sales</strong><p>Read orders, create one row per order_date, and calculate SUM. This intermediate result exists only for this statement.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>daily_sales</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>OVER</code><strong>ORDER BY order_date</strong><p>Define which related rows the window function may inspect and in what order.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>order_date, daily_revenue, LAG(daily_revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS previ…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>order_date</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Reverse or change the window order and predict which comparison or running value changes first.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n)\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    daily_revenue,\n    LAG(daily_revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS previous_day_revenue\nFROM daily_sales\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>previous_day_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The first row returns NULL because no previous row exists.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Period-over-period change\"><h3>Period-over-period change</h3><p>Calculate LAG in one layer, then use the result in the outer query.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n),\nwith_previous AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        daily_revenue,\n        LAG(daily_revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS previous_revenue\n    FROM daily_sales\n)\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    daily_revenue,\n    previous_revenue,\n    daily_revenue - previous_revenue AS revenue_change\nFROM with_previous\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>previous_revenue</th><th>revenue_change</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">-0.950</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">0.450</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">-4.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Do not interpret the first NULL change as zero; there is no earlier period to compare.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"LEAD\"><h3>LEAD</h3><p>LEAD reads a value from a following row.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT order_date, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n)\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    daily_revenue,\n    LEAD(daily_revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS next_day_revenue\nFROM daily_sales\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>next_day_revenue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>LEAD is useful for comparing a row with what happens next.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Moving averages\"><h3>Moving averages</h3><p>A frame controls which neighboring rows participate in an ordered window.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT order_date, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n)\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    daily_revenue,\n    ROUND(AVG(daily_revenue) OVER (\n        ORDER BY order_date\n        ROWS BETWEEN 2 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW\n    ), 3) AS three_row_moving_average\nFROM daily_sales\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>three_row_moving_average</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">12.525</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">12.517</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">10.933</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>This is a three-row average, not necessarily a three-calendar-day average if dates are missing.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Peer averages with AVG OVER\"><h3>Peer averages with AVG OVER</h3><p>An aggregate window can compare each row with its peer group while keeping every row visible.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_month AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.category,\n        p.product_name,\n        DATE_FORMAT(o.order_date, &#x27;%Y-%m&#x27;) AS sales_month,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.category, p.product_id, p.product_name, DATE_FORMAT(o.order_date, &#x27;%Y-%m&#x27;)\n)\nSELECT\n    category,\n    product_name,\n    sales_month,\n    revenue,\n    ROUND(AVG(revenue) OVER (\n        PARTITION BY category, sales_month\n    ), 3) AS category_month_average,\n    ROUND(revenue - AVG(revenue) OVER (\n        PARTITION BY category, sales_month\n    ), 3) AS difference_from_category_average\nFROM product_month\nORDER BY sales_month, category, difference_from_category_average;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Script outcome</strong></div><p>Run the statements in order. Structure-changing statements report success without rows; the final verification SELECT displays the resulting records.</p></aside><p>This is the same pattern as a store-versus-region comparison. First create one row per business entity and period. Then use AVG(...) OVER (PARTITION BY peer_group, period) to attach the peer average beside each row.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["LAG", "Period-over-period change", "LEAD", "Moving averages", "Peer averages with AVG OVER"]}, {"title": "Shares, Ordering, and Layered Analysis", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 12 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Shares, Ordering, and Layered Analysis</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain shares, ordering, and layered analysis, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Comparing Rows Across Time and Peers.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Percentage-of-total and combined grouped/window reports show how analytical stages can be layered. We separate window order from final display order and review failure patterns.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Percentage of total\"><h3>Percentage of total</h3><p>Divide a row or grouped value by a window total.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will first build <code>product_sales</code> from <code>products</code> at one row per <code>p.product_id, p.product_name</code>, then read rows from <code>product_sales</code>, then attach a window calculation without collapsing the result rows, then return <code>product_name, revenue, ROUND(100 * revenue / SUM(revenue) OVER (), 2) AS revenue_…</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>The final source-row grain is preserved; the window value is attached as another column.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The window calculation adds analytical context while leaving the underlying result rows visible.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CTE product_sales</code><strong>product_sales</strong><p>Read products, create one row per p.product_id, p.product_name, and calculate SUM. This intermediate result exists only for this statement.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>product_sales</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>OVER</code><strong></strong><p>Define which related rows the window function may inspect and in what order.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, revenue, ROUND(100 * revenue / SUM(revenue) OVER (), 2) AS revenue_…</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>revenue DESC</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Reverse or change the window order and predict which comparison or running value changes first.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n)\nSELECT\n    product_name,\n    revenue,\n    ROUND(100 * revenue / SUM(revenue) OVER (), 2) AS revenue_percent\nFROM product_sales\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>revenue_percent</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">36.03</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">19.65</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">13.10</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">12.66</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">10.92</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">7.64</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>The percentages should total approximately 100, allowing for rounding.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Window ORDER BY versus result ORDER BY\"><h3>Window ORDER BY versus result ORDER BY</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>ORDER BY inside OVER controls the calculation. ORDER BY at the end controls how rows are displayed.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Clause fragment</strong></div><p>This is not a complete standalone statement. Its expected effect is demonstrated in the nearest complete query in this lesson.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    product_name,\n    price,\n    RANK() OVER (ORDER BY price DESC) AS price_rank\nFROM products\nORDER BY product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>price</th><th>price_rank</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Ranks are based on descending price even though the final rows are displayed alphabetically.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Combining grouping and windows\"><h3>Combining grouping and windows</h3><p>SQL can aggregate first and then apply a window function to the grouped result.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue,\n    RANK() OVER (\n        ORDER BY SUM(quantity * unit_price) DESC\n    ) AS revenue_rank\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date\nORDER BY revenue_rank;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>revenue_rank</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Expected result:</p><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>revenue_rank</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2026-06-20</td><td>13.000</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-22</td><td>12.500</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-21</td><td>12.050</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>2026-06-23</td><td>8.250</td><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common mistakes\"><h3>Common mistakes</h3><p>Common errors include expecting window functions to collapse rows, filtering a window alias in WHERE, omitting a deterministic tiebreaker, confusing calculation order with display order, partitioning by the wrong peer group, and assuming a row frame represents uninterrupted calendar time.</p><p>Always state the result grain, partition, ordering, and frame in plain language before trusting a window calculation.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Final analyst report\"><h3>Final analyst report</h3><p>Build a daily performance report containing revenue, running revenue, previous revenue, daily change, and revenue rank.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n),\ndaily_windows AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        daily_revenue,\n        SUM(daily_revenue) OVER (\n            ORDER BY order_date\n            ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW\n        ) AS running_revenue,\n        LAG(daily_revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS previous_revenue,\n        RANK() OVER (ORDER BY daily_revenue DESC) AS revenue_rank\n    FROM daily_sales\n)\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    daily_revenue,\n    running_revenue,\n    previous_revenue,\n    daily_revenue - previous_revenue AS daily_change,\n    revenue_rank\nFROM daily_windows\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>running_revenue</th><th>previous_revenue</th><th>daily_change</th><th>revenue_rank</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">25.050</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">-0.950</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">37.550</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">0.450</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">-4.250</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Percentage of total", "Window ORDER BY versus result ORDER BY", "Combining grouping and windows", "Common mistakes", "Final analyst report"]}, {"title": "Window Function Lab", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 12 · SECTION 5</p><h2>Window Function Lab</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain window function lab, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Shares, Ordering, and Layered Analysis.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">These exercises cover ranking, partitioning, top-N logic, revenue share, running totals, and change. State the partition and order in words before writing OVER.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Rank products by revenue\"><h3>Practice 1: Rank products by revenue</h3><p>Build product revenue totals, then rank products from highest to lowest revenue.</p><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will first build <code>product_sales</code> from <code>products</code> at one row per <code>p.product_id, p.product_name</code>, then read rows from <code>product_sales</code>, then attach a window calculation without collapsing the result rows, then return <code>product_name, revenue, RANK() OVER (ORDER BY revenue DESC) AS revenue_rank</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>The final source-row grain is preserved; the window value is attached as another column.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The window calculation adds analytical context while leaving the underlying result rows visible.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CTE product_sales</code><strong>product_sales</strong><p>Read products, create one row per p.product_id, p.product_name, and calculate SUM. This intermediate result exists only for this statement.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>product_sales</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>OVER</code><strong>ORDER BY revenue DESC</strong><p>Define which related rows the window function may inspect and in what order.</p></div></li><li><span>4</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>product_name, revenue, RANK() OVER (ORDER BY revenue DESC) AS revenue_rank</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li><li><span>5</span><div><code>ORDER BY</code><strong>revenue_rank, product_name</strong><p>Sort the completed result; sorting does not change the stored table.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Check column names, result grain, row count, NULLs, and one value calculated by hand.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Reverse or change the window order and predict which comparison or running value changes first.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_id,\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n)\nSELECT\n    product_name,\n    revenue,\n    RANK() OVER (ORDER BY revenue DESC) AS revenue_rank\nFROM product_sales\nORDER BY revenue_rank, product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>revenue_rank</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">5</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">6</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Rank prices inside categories\"><h3>Practice 2: Rank prices inside categories</h3><p>Rank products by price inside each category. Use a deterministic tiebreaker.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    category,\n    product_name,\n    price,\n    RANK() OVER (\n        PARTITION BY category\n        ORDER BY price DESC\n    ) AS price_rank,\n    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (\n        PARTITION BY category\n        ORDER BY price DESC, product_id\n    ) AS stable_position\nFROM products\nORDER BY category, stable_position;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>price</th><th>price_rank</th><th>stable_position</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Top two products per category\"><h3>Practice 3: Top two products per category</h3><p>Return the two highest-priced products per category by ranking in a CTE and filtering in the outer query.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH ranked_products AS (\n    SELECT\n        category,\n        product_name,\n        price,\n        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (\n            PARTITION BY category\n            ORDER BY price DESC, product_id\n        ) AS category_position\n    FROM products\n)\nSELECT\n    category,\n    product_name,\n    price\nFROM ranked_products\nWHERE category_position &lt;= 2\nORDER BY category, category_position;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>category</th><th>product_name</th><th>price</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Coffee</td><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Dessert</td><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Pastry</td><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Tea</td><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>5 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Percentage of total revenue\"><h3>Practice 4: Percentage of total revenue</h3><p>Calculate each product&#x27;s revenue and percentage of total revenue.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH product_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.product_id,\n        p.product_name,\n        SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\n    FROM products AS p\n    JOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\n    GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name\n)\nSELECT\n    product_name,\n    revenue,\n    ROUND(100 * revenue / SUM(revenue) OVER (), 2) AS revenue_percent\nFROM product_sales\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>product_name</th><th>revenue</th><th>revenue_percent</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">Iced Latte</td><td class=\"\">16.500</td><td class=\"\">36.03</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Cold Brew</td><td class=\"\">9.000</td><td class=\"\">19.65</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Croissant</td><td class=\"\">6.000</td><td class=\"\">13.10</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Matcha Latte</td><td class=\"\">5.800</td><td class=\"\">12.66</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Americano</td><td class=\"\">5.000</td><td class=\"\">10.92</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">Brownie</td><td class=\"\">3.500</td><td class=\"\">7.64</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>6 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Running revenue and daily change\"><h3>Practice 5: Running revenue and daily change</h3><p>Calculate daily revenue, running revenue, previous-day revenue, and day-over-day change.</p><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS daily_revenue\n    FROM orders\n    GROUP BY order_date\n),\ndaily_windows AS (\n    SELECT\n        order_date,\n        daily_revenue,\n        SUM(daily_revenue) OVER (\n            ORDER BY order_date\n            ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW\n        ) AS running_revenue,\n        LAG(daily_revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS previous_revenue\n    FROM daily_sales\n)\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    daily_revenue,\n    running_revenue,\n    previous_revenue,\n    daily_revenue - previous_revenue AS daily_change\nFROM daily_windows\nORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>daily_revenue</th><th>running_revenue</th><th>previous_revenue</th><th>daily_change</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">25.050</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">-0.950</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">37.550</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">0.450</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">-4.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Rank products by revenue", "Practice 2: Rank prices inside categories", "Practice 3: Top two products per category", "Practice 4: Percentage of total revenue", "Practice 5: Running revenue and daily change"]}, {"title": "Chapter Summary", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 12 · SECTION 6</p><h2>Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Window Function Lab.</p></div></section><section class=\"concept-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">BUILD THE MENTAL MODEL</p><div><span>CORE IDEA</span><p>A window function looks across related result rows without collapsing them. PARTITION BY defines groups and ORDER BY defines sequence.</p></div><div><span>CONCRETE EXAMPLE</span><p>LAG compares a day with the prior day while both daily rows remain visible.</p></div><div><span>EXPLAIN IT BACK</span><p>Which rows belong in the window, and what ordering makes previous or running meaningful?</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Use the summary to choose among grouping, ranking, navigation, and aggregate window functions based on the required output grain.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 9 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 9 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Window pattern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Keep detail plus a total</td><td>SUM(value) OVER ()</td></tr><tr><td>Restart by group</td><td>PARTITION BY</td></tr><tr><td>Compare against peers</td><td>AVG(value) OVER (PARTITION BY peer_group)</td></tr><tr><td>Unique sequence</td><td>ROW_NUMBER()</td></tr><tr><td>Ranking with ties</td><td>RANK() or DENSE_RANK()</td></tr><tr><td>Previous value</td><td>LAG()</td></tr><tr><td>Following value</td><td>LEAD()</td></tr><tr><td>Running total</td><td>ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW</td></tr><tr><td>Top N per group</td><td>Rank in a CTE, then filter</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Segment 9 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 12</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"Window functions attach analytical values while preserving the result grain.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>Do window functions normally collapse detail rows?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Yes</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">No</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Only on Mondays</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"PARTITION BY restarts the window calculation for each partition.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>What does PARTITION BY do?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Creates independent windows</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Deletes duplicates</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Limits output</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"LAG accesses a value from an earlier row in the window order.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Which function reads the previous row&#x27;s value?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">LEAD</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">LAG</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">RANK</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Daily trend dashboard query", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 12</p><h2>Daily trend dashboard query</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Window functions power rankings, running totals, and comparisons without discarding useful row detail.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>The owner needs daily revenue, running revenue, prior-day revenue, and change.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Aggregate to one row per date in a CTE.</li><li>Add a running total with an explicit ROWS frame.</li><li>Use LAG for prior revenue and calculate daily change.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Final grain is one row per date</li><li>Window order is deterministic</li><li>Running frame is explicit</li><li>First prior-day value is correctly NULL</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>WITH daily AS (\n  SELECT order_date, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\n  FROM orders GROUP BY order_date\n)\nSELECT order_date, revenue,\n       SUM(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) AS running_revenue,\n       LAG(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS prior_revenue,\n       revenue - LAG(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY order_date) AS revenue_change\nFROM daily ORDER BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_date</th><th>revenue</th><th>running_revenue</th><th>prior_revenue</th><th>revenue_change</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">25.050</td><td class=\"\">13.000</td><td class=\"\">-0.950</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">37.550</td><td class=\"\">12.050</td><td class=\"\">0.450</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td><td class=\"\">8.250</td><td class=\"\">45.800</td><td class=\"\">12.500</td><td class=\"\">-4.250</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>4 rows returned.</p></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 9, "workflow_number": 12}, {"title": "Query Performance", "desc": "Read execution plans, design indexes, and reduce unnecessary query work.", "lessons": [{"title": "Measure Before Optimizing", "time": 12, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 13 · SECTION 1</p><h2>Measure Before Optimizing</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain measure before optimizing, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Production SQL must return the right result with evidence about how much work the database performs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: the section overview.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Performance tuning begins with a correct query and a baseline. EXPLAIN exposes access strategy, estimated rows, candidate indexes, and extra work such as temporary results.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment overview\"><h3>Chapter Roadmap</h3><p>Correct SQL must also remain practical as data grows. This segment teaches how to inspect query plans, design useful indexes, and avoid patterns that force unnecessary work.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Performance starts with measurement\"><h3>Performance starts with measurement</h3><p>Do not optimize from intuition alone. Record the query, parameters, row counts, execution time, and plan before changing it.</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL does not return the SELECT's normal business rows. It asks the optimizer to describe how it intends to access the tables and perform the work.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One plan row per table access in this query; this example accesses the orders table once.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Here, type is ref, key is product_id, estimated rows is 3, and Extra says NULL. These are estimates, not the query&#x27;s business result.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>EXPLAIN</code><strong>Request a plan</strong><p>Ask for optimizer estimates instead of normal query output.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>PLANNED QUERY</code><strong>SELECT * FROM orders WHERE product_id = 1;</strong><p>This is the query whose work MySQL is estimating.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>READ THE PLAN</code><strong>type · possible_keys · key · rows · Extra</strong><p>Start with access method, available index, chosen index, estimated rows, and extra operations.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Run the SELECT without EXPLAIN to verify its answer separately. After a tuning change, compare both the plan and the unchanged result.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Predict whether MySQL will scan or use an index, then compare your prediction with type and key.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE product_id = 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">ref</td><td class=\"\">product_id</td><td class=\"\">product_id</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">const</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN describes MySQL&#x27;s plan without returning the normal result rows.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Read the important EXPLAIN columns\"><h3>Read the important EXPLAIN columns</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT\n    order_date,\n    SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY order_date;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">ALL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td><td class=\"\">Using temporary</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Start with table, type, possible_keys, key, rows, and Extra. Estimated rows are not guaranteed to equal actual rows.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN output is evidence, not a promise. MySQL can choose a different plan after data grows, statistics change, indexes are added or removed, or the MySQL version changes. Record the plan you actually see, then verify that the tuned query still returns the same business result.</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Teaching fragment</strong></div><p>This block illustrates SQL syntax but is not complete enough to execute by itself.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Full scans\"><h3>Full scans</h3><p>A full table scan is not automatically bad. It can be reasonable for small tables or queries that need most rows. It becomes expensive when a large table is scanned to return a tiny subset.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date = &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">ALL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">10.00</td><td class=\"\">Using where</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section></div><figure class=\"lesson-visual\"><img src=\"assets/lesson-visuals/segment-13-performance.webp\" alt=\"A slow query scan being explained and redirected through an organized index toward a fast result.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption><strong>Visual model</strong>EXPLAIN reveals the query plan, while appropriate indexes can reduce the rows MySQL must inspect. <em>Concept illustration; use the lesson tables for exact course values.</em></figcaption></figure>", "source_titles": ["Segment overview", "Performance starts with measurement", "Read the important EXPLAIN columns", "Full scans"]}, {"title": "Index Design and Searchable Predicates", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 13 · SECTION 2</p><h2>Index Design and Searchable Predicates</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain index design and searchable predicates, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Production SQL must return the right result with evidence about how much work the database performs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Measure Before Optimizing.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Indexes are ordered lookup structures with costs. We compare single and composite indexes, leftmost prefixes, and date predicates that preserve index searchability.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Create a single-column index\"><h3>Create a single-column index</h3><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>This statement tells MySQL to build a lookup structure for <code>idx_orders_order_date</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>This operation changes or inspects database state; it does not produce an analytical row grain.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>The statement&#x27;s success message proves only that MySQL accepted it. A separate verification statement proves the intended state.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>CREATE INDEX</code><strong>CREATE INDEX idx_orders_order_date ON orders (order_date);</strong><p>Build a lookup structure.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Read MySQL&#x27;s success or affected-row message, then use DESCRIBE, SHOW CREATE TABLE, SHOW INDEX, or a narrow SELECT to confirm the outcome.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>State what should exist or change before running the statement, then verify that exact condition afterward.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE INDEX idx_orders_order_date\nON orders (order_date);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Index created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>idx_orders_order_date</code>; confirm its column order with <code>SHOW INDEX</code>.</p></aside><p>This index can help equality and range filters on order_date. Indexes consume storage and add work to INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Verify index use\"><h3>Verify index use</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT\n    order_id,\n    product_id,\n    quantity\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27; AND &#x27;2026-06-22&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">ALL</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_order_date</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">90.00</td><td class=\"\">Using where</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>Look for idx_orders_order_date in key and compare estimated work.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Composite indexes\"><h3>Composite indexes</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>CREATE INDEX idx_orders_product_date\nON orders (product_id, order_date);</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Index created</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. MySQL creates <code>idx_orders_product_date</code>; confirm its column order with <code>SHOW INDEX</code>.</p></aside><p>Column order matters. This index supports filters beginning with product_id and can continue into order_date.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"The leftmost-prefix idea\"><h3>The leftmost-prefix idea</h3><p>The composite index (product_id, order_date) is naturally useful for product_id alone or product_id plus order_date. It is generally less useful for order_date alone.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE product_id = 1\n  AND order_date &gt;= &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">range</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_order_date,idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td><td class=\"\">Using index condition</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Write searchable date filters\"><h3>Write searchable date filters</h3><p>Avoid wrapping an indexed column in a function when a range expresses the same condition.</p><p>Less index-friendly:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT * FROM orders WHERE YEAR(order_date) = 2026;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside><p>More searchable:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date &gt;= &#x27;2026-01-01&#x27;\n  AND order_date &lt; &#x27;2027-01-01&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Create a single-column index", "Verify index use", "Composite indexes", "The leftmost-prefix idea", "Write searchable date filters"]}, {"title": "Reducing Work Without Changing Results", "time": 15, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 13 · SECTION 3</p><h2>Reducing Work Without Changing Results</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain reducing work without changing results, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Production SQL must return the right result with evidence about how much work the database performs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Index Design and Searchable Predicates.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">Selecting fewer columns, indexing relationships, controlling join cardinality, and removing unused indexes can reduce work. Every change must preserve the verified answer.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Select only needed columns\"><h3>Select only needed columns</h3><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL will read rows from <code>orders</code>, then keep rows where <code>product_id = 1</code>, then return <code>order_id, product_id, order_date</code>.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One output row per source row that survives WHERE, unless LIMIT keeps fewer.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Every returned row passed the WHERE condition; rows that evaluate false or unknown are absent.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>FROM</code><strong>orders</strong><p>Choose the rows the outer query starts from.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>WHERE</code><strong>product_id = 1</strong><p>Remove source rows that do not satisfy this condition before grouping.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>SELECT</code><strong>order_id, product_id, order_date</strong><p>Calculate and name the columns displayed in the final result.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Expect 3 rows with columns order_id, product_id, order_date. Check the row count before interpreting values.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Change one filter value, predict which rows will enter or leave, then run the modified query.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    order_id,\n    product_id,\n    order_date\nFROM orders\nWHERE product_id = 1;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Naming columns reduces transferred data and makes the query&#x27;s contract clearer.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Index join keys\"><h3>Index join keys</h3><p>Primary and foreign-key columns used for joins should be indexed appropriately.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT\n    p.product_name,\n    SUM(o.quantity * o.unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM products AS p\nJOIN orders AS o ON o.product_id = p.product_id\nGROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">p</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">ALL</td><td class=\"\">PRIMARY</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td><td class=\"\">Using temporary</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">o</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">ref</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">course_audit.p.product_id</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>2 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Avoid accidental row multiplication\"><h3>Avoid accidental row multiplication</h3><p>Performance and correctness both suffer when a join condition is incomplete. State the expected grain and verify row counts before and after a join.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT COUNT(*) AS order_rows FROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">10</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT COUNT(*) AS joined_rows\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p ON p.product_id = o.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>joined_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">10</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside><p>For this many-to-one relationship, the counts should match when every order has a valid product.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Remove unused indexes carefully\"><h3>Remove unused indexes carefully</h3><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>DROP INDEX idx_orders_order_date ON orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Named object removed if present</strong></div><p>No data rows are returned. With <code>IF EXISTS</code>, an absent object produces a note instead of stopping the reset script.</p></aside><p>Confirm an index is redundant and unused by important workloads before removing it.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Common mistakes\"><h3>Common mistakes</h3><p>Do not add indexes to every column, assume an index must be used, optimize only on tiny development data, ignore write costs, compare timings without controlling conditions, or change several things before measuring again.</p></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Select only needed columns", "Index join keys", "Avoid accidental row multiplication", "Remove unused indexes carefully", "Common mistakes"]}, {"title": "Performance Lab and Chapter Summary", "time": 18, "body": "<p class=\"chapter-label\">CHAPTER 13 · SECTION 4</p><h2>Performance Lab and Chapter Summary</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Explain performance lab and chapter summary, identify when it is useful, and apply it to the course database.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Production SQL must return the right result with evidence about how much work the database performs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Reducing Work Without Changing Results.</p></div></section><p class=\"chapter-lead\">The exercises require before-and-after plan evidence, result reconciliation, and explicit tradeoffs. Avoid claiming improvement from an index name alone.</p><div class=\"chapter-reading\"><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 1: Explain a product filter\"><h3>Practice 1: Explain a product filter</h3><p>Answer:</p><section class=\"query-teaching\"><p class=\"teaching-kicker\">UNDERSTAND THE QUERY</p><h3>Read it as a sequence of decisions</h3><div class=\"teaching-summary\"><div><span>PLAIN ENGLISH</span><p>MySQL does not return the SELECT's normal business rows. It asks the optimizer to describe how it intends to access the tables and perform the work.</p></div><div><span>RESULT GRAIN</span><p>One plan row per table access in this query; this example accesses the orders table once.</p></div><div><span>WHAT TO NOTICE</span><p>Here, type is ref, key is idx_orders_product_date, estimated rows is 2, and Extra says NULL. These are estimates, not the query&#x27;s business result.</p></div></div><ol class=\"clause-walkthrough\"><li><span>1</span><div><code>EXPLAIN</code><strong>Request a plan</strong><p>Ask for optimizer estimates instead of normal query output.</p></div></li><li><span>2</span><div><code>PLANNED QUERY</code><strong>SELECT order_id, quantity, unit_price FROM orders WHERE product_id = 2;</strong><p>This is the query whose work MySQL is estimating.</p></div></li><li><span>3</span><div><code>READ THE PLAN</code><strong>type · possible_keys · key · rows · Extra</strong><p>Start with access method, available index, chosen index, estimated rows, and extra operations.</p></div></li></ol><div class=\"teaching-check\"><strong>How to verify it</strong><span>Run the SELECT without EXPLAIN to verify its answer separately. After a tuning change, compare both the plan and the unchanged result.</span></div><div class=\"teaching-check practice-prompt\"><strong>Predict, then try</strong><span>Predict whether MySQL will scan or use an index, then compare your prediction with type and key.</span></div></section><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT\n    order_id,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price\nFROM orders\nWHERE product_id = 2;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">ref</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">const</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 2: Inspect indexes on orders\"><h3>Practice 2: Inspect indexes on orders</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SHOW INDEX\nFROM orders;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>Table</th><th>Non_unique</th><th>Key_name</th><th>Seq_in_index</th><th>Column_name</th><th>Collation</th><th>Cardinality</th><th>Sub_part</th><th>Packed</th><th>Null</th><th>Index_type</th><th>Comment</th><th>Index_comment</th><th>Visible</th><th>Expression</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"\">0</td><td class=\"\">PRIMARY</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">order_id</td><td class=\"\">A</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\">BTREE</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\">YES</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">product_id</td><td class=\"\">A</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\">BTREE</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\">YES</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">order_date</td><td class=\"\">A</td><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\">BTREE</td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\"></td><td class=\"\">YES</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>3 rows returned.</p></aside><p>Because product_id is a foreign key in this course schema, MySQL requires a supporting index and creates one automatically when needed. Do not add a redundant single-column index without checking first.</p></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 3: Test the composite product-date index\"><h3>Practice 3: Test the composite product-date index</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN\nSELECT\n    order_id,\n    quantity,\n    unit_price\nFROM orders\nWHERE product_id = 1\n  AND order_date &gt;= &#x27;2026-06-20&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>id</th><th>select_type</th><th>table</th><th>partitions</th><th>type</th><th>possible_keys</th><th>key</th><th>key_len</th><th>ref</th><th>rows</th><th>filtered</th><th>Extra</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">SIMPLE</td><td class=\"\">orders</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">range</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">idx_orders_product_date</td><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"null-value\">NULL</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">100.00</td><td class=\"\">Using index condition</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 4: Rewrite a monthly date filter\"><h3>Practice 4: Rewrite a monthly date filter</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date &gt;= &#x27;2026-06-01&#x27;\n  AND order_date &lt; &#x27;2026-07-01&#x27;;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_id</th><th>product_id</th><th>quantity</th><th>unit_price</th><th>order_date</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-20</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">1.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">5</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2.900</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-21</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">7</td><td class=\"\">6</td><td class=\"\">4</td><td class=\"\">1.250</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">8</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">2</td><td class=\"\">3.000</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">9</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">1.500</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-22</td></tr><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">1</td><td class=\"\">3</td><td class=\"\">2.750</td><td class=\"\">2026-06-23</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>10 rows returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Practice 5: Compare join row counts\"><h3>Practice 5: Compare join row counts</h3><p>Answer:</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>SELECT\n    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM orders) AS order_rows,\n    COUNT(*) AS joined_rows\nFROM orders AS o\nJOIN products AS p ON p.product_id = o.product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Output from the course dataset</strong></div><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table expected-table\"><thead><tr><th>order_rows</th><th>joined_rows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"\">10</td><td class=\"\">10</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>1 row returned.</p></aside></section><section class=\"textbook-subsection\" data-source-title=\"Segment 13 cheat sheet\"><h3>Segment 13 cheat sheet</h3><div class=\"table-scroll\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Tool</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Inspect a plan</td><td>EXPLAIN</td></tr><tr><td>Support one search column</td><td>Single-column index</td></tr><tr><td>Support ordered filter columns</td><td>Composite index</td></tr><tr><td>Keep filters searchable</td><td>Compare indexed columns directly to ranges</td></tr><tr><td>Reduce output work</td><td>Select only required columns</td></tr><tr><td>Validate joins</td><td>Compare grain and row counts</td></tr><tr><td>Remove an index</td><td>DROP INDEX ... ON table</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section></div>", "source_titles": ["Practice 1: Explain a product filter", "Practice 2: Inspect indexes on orders", "Practice 3: Test the composite product-date index", "Practice 4: Rewrite a monthly date filter", "Practice 5: Compare join row counts", "Segment 13 cheat sheet"]}, {"title": "Section knowledge check", "time": 8, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">ASSESS · SECTION 13</p><h2>Check your understanding</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Retrieve the section&#x27;s key ideas from memory before beginning the project.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Production SQL must return the right result with evidence about how much work the database performs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Performance Lab and Chapter Summary.</p></div></section><p>Answer each question before moving to the project. Feedback explains the rule, not just the letter.</p><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"EXPLAIN describes how MySQL intends to access and join data.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 1 OF 3</span><h3>What is EXPLAIN for?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Inspecting a query plan</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">Formatting dates</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Committing a transaction</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"0\" data-why=\"A function on the indexed column can make the predicate non-sargable.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 2 OF 3</span><h3>Why can wrapping an indexed date column in YEAR() hurt?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">It may prevent an efficient range lookup</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">YEAR deletes dates</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Indexes only support text</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section><section class=\"quiz\" data-correct=\"1\" data-why=\"Indexes trade faster reads for storage and maintenance overhead.\"><span class=\"quiz-tag\">KNOWLEDGE CHECK 3 OF 3</span><h3>Is every index beneficial?</h3><div class=\"answers\"><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"0\">Yes</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"1\">No; indexes cost storage and write work</button><button class=\"answer\" data-answer=\"2\">Only primary keys cost space</button></div><div class=\"feedback\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div></section>"}, {"title": "Mini-project: Query tuning report", "time": 35, "body": "<p class=\"eyebrow\">APPLY · SECTION 13</p><h2>Query tuning report</h2><section class=\"learning-brief\" aria-label=\"Lesson purpose\"><div><span>LEARNING GOAL</span><p>Combine this section&#x27;s skills into a reproducible business deliverable.</p></div><div><span>WHY IT MATTERS</span><p>Production SQL must return the right result with evidence about how much work the database performs.</p></div><div><span>CONNECTION</span><p>Builds on: Section knowledge check.</p></div></section><div class=\"project-brief\"><strong>Business brief</strong><p>A monthly product sales report is slow on a large orders table.</p></div><h3>Deliverables</h3><ol><li>Capture EXPLAIN before optimization.</li><li>Rewrite the date filter as a half-open range and propose a justified composite index.</li><li>Capture EXPLAIN after optimization and compare access type, key, and estimated rows.</li></ol><h3>Acceptance criteria</h3><ul class=\"project-checklist\"><li>Before/after query results are identical</li><li>Index order follows filter/join needs</li><li>Claims use EXPLAIN evidence</li><li>Report discusses write and storage tradeoffs</li></ul><details class=\"project-hint\"><summary>Need a starting hint?</summary><p>Write the required result grain in one sentence, identify the source rows, then build and test one clause at a time.</p></details><details class=\"project-solution\"><summary>Reveal reference solution after attempting</summary><p>This is one valid solution. Compare the result grain, logic, and output—not only formatting.</p><div class=\"code-block\"><div class=\"code-label\"><span>REFERENCE SQL</span><button data-copy>Copy query</button></div><pre><code>EXPLAIN SELECT product_id, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date &gt;= &#x27;2026-06-01&#x27; AND order_date &lt; &#x27;2026-07-01&#x27;\nGROUP BY product_id;\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_orders_date_product ON orders(order_date, product_id);\n\nEXPLAIN SELECT product_id, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date &gt;= &#x27;2026-06-01&#x27; AND order_date &lt; &#x27;2026-07-01&#x27;\nGROUP BY product_id;</code></pre></div><aside class=\"expected-result result\"><div class=\"expected-result-title\"><span>EXPECTED RESULT</span><strong>Ordered outcomes for this script</strong></div><ol class=\"script-outcomes\"><li><strong>1. <code>EXPLAIN SELECT product_id, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue FROM…</code></strong><span>Returns the execution-plan columns for the following query; it does not return normal query rows.</span></li><li><strong>2. <code>CREATE INDEX idx_orders_date_product ON orders(order_date, product_id)</code></strong><span>Creates the index; verify its columns with SHOW INDEX.</span></li><li><strong>3. <code>EXPLAIN SELECT product_id, SUM(quantity * unit_price) AS revenue FROM…</code></strong><span>Returns the execution-plan columns for the following query; it does not return normal query rows.</span></li></ol></aside></details><h3>Self-assessment rubric</h3><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ready</td><td>All criteria pass; result is verified and explained in business language.</td></tr><tr><td>Revise</td><td>Query partly works, but one criterion, validation step, or explanation is missing.</td></tr><tr><td>Relearn</td><td>Result grain or core section concept is incorrect; revisit the linked lessons before retrying.</td></tr></tbody></table>"}], "source_number": 13, "workflow_number": 13}];
